VALUES ( N'HuH', N'huh', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A satirical and alternative humor magazine that flourished in the 1990s, covering pop culture and politics aimed at Gen-Xers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH, short for "Here''s How" was a monthly satirical and alternative humor magazine that flourished in the 1990s. The magazine covered topics such as pop culture, politics, and scathing commentary, primarily aimed at Gen-Xers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH was founded in 1986 by Michael Shore and was established as a response to the mainstream media''s lack of coverage for Generation X. It quickly gained popularity for its irreverent editorial style, unique layout, and the inclusion of innovative interactive elements.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine grew rapidly and expanded its readership to a loyal base of Gen-Xers. Through the 1990s, the magazine became an icon of alternative culture, finding a place in coffee shops and independent bookstores across the country.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Different from other alternative publications, which started on fringes and aimed to be counter-culture, HuH became a respected establishment of sorts. It featured notable writers, illustrators, and photographers, who consistently produced witty and thought-provoking content for the publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After an impressive 14-year-long career, the magazine was closed in 2000 and turned into an online media outlet. However, in recent years, the magazine has remained inactive, leaving an iconic void in alternative humor publishing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH covered a variety of topics, including music, film, television, and politics. The magazine was known for its irreverent and unique sense of humor, as well as its satirical take on pop culture and current events.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s layout incorporated interactive elements that allowed readers to engage with the content in new ways, such as pop-out letters, hidden messages, and secret codes. HuH also included cartoons, comics, and illustrations alongside its written content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine featured notable writers, illustrators, and photographers, such as David Foster Wallace, Mark Leyner, Ben Katchor, Bruce McCall, and Roz Chast.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH had a notable impact on the publishing industry and the culture at large, particularly among Gen-Xers. The magazine helped to establish the alternative humor genre and define the aesthetic of 1990s counterculture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH''s influence can still be seen in contemporary publications like The Onion and McSweeney''s, which carry on the tradition of biting satire and originality. HuH magazine further helped to establish alternative media as a way of capturing niche audiences, paving the way for influential publications like Vice and Pitchfork.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Humbug
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Humbug', N'humbug', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A pioneering satirical magazine of the late 1950s challenging conventions through biting humor and social commentary.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Humbug was a short-lived satirical and comic magazine published in the United States in the late 1950s. The magazine was established by a group of influential comic book artists, who sought to put a new spin on the comic book format.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Humbug magazine was founded in 1957 by Harvey Kurtzman, who previously worked for Mad Magazine, along with a group of artists including Will Elder, Jack Davis, Al Jaffee, Arnold Roth, and others. The magazine was a response to the limitations and censorship of the comic book industry at the time, and sought to provide a new avenue for satire and commentary.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue was published in August 1957, and it immediately gained a loyal fan base and critical acclaim. Humbug''s style was distinct from other popular comic magazines of the time, such as Mad Magazine, with a more satirical and political bent.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the initial success of the magazine, Humbug faced financial struggles and distribution difficulties. The magazine''s final issue was published in the summer of 1958, after only eleven issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Humbug''s content was known for its biting satire and irreverent take on pop culture, politics, and the media. The magazine featured a mix of comic strips, articles, and illustrations, often employing a unique and experimental layout.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s aesthetic was heavily influenced by the artists who founded it, who had previously worked on various comic book projects. The magazine often included parodies of popular comic book characters and media figures, using humor as a vehicle for social commentary.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short lifespan, Humbug is remembered as an influential publication in the history of comic books and satirical media. The magazine''s emphasis on political and social commentary was a departure from the more lighthearted tone of other popular comic magazines of the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Humbug''s founders went on to have significant careers in the comic book industry, including work for publications like Mad Magazine and National Lampoon. The magazine also inspired later generations of satirical media, including The Daily Show, The Onion, and other contemporary publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Humbug magazine’s short-lived presence in the comic industry marked a pioneering effort to push the boundaries of artistic and editorial freedom, and laid the groundwork for the future of satire in the general media.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hunter-Trader-Trapper
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hunter-Trader-Trapper', N'hunter-trader-trapper', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American magazine for hunters, traders, and trappers, providing news, information, and stories related to their interests.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hunter-Trader-Trapper magazine was an American magazine first published in 1919. The magazine catered to a niche audience of American hunters, traders, and trappers, providing them with news, information, and stories related to their interests.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hunter-Trader-Trapper was founded by Arthur F. Neumann, a writer and publisher from New York City. The magazine initially focused on hunting and trapping, with a section dedicated to fur prices. The first issue was published in June 1919, and it quickly gained popularity among its target audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the 1920s and 1930s, Hunter-Trader-Trapper expanded its focus to include international hunting and fishing, as well as adventure travel. The magazine''s articles were often illustrated with photographs, which helped to promote exotic destinations and experiences to its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After Neumann''s death in 1928, Hunter-Trader-Trapper was sold to Charles L. Cadieux, who expanded the magazine''s focus to include firearms and shooting. Cadieux ran the magazine until his death in 1972, at which point it was sold to Outdoor Sportsman Group.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hunter-Trader-Trapper''s content varied, ranging from news and opinion pieces to how-to guides and personal narratives. The magazine''s articles often featured exotic locales, detailing the experiences of hunters, trappers, and traders around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s illustrated covers were often provocative, featuring images of game animals, hunting equipment, and women in various poses. The magazine featured a mix of advertising and editorial content, with ads for guns, ammunition, and hunting gear often appearing as full-page spreads.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hunter-Trader-Trapper remained popular among American hunters and outdoors enthusiasts throughout the 20th century. The magazine''s emphasis on travel and adventure helped to promote hunting and fishing as an international activity, and its how-to guides and personal anecdotes helped to educate and inspire its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the early 2000s, Hunter-Trader-Trapper was absorbed by Outdoor Life magazine, which is still published under the Bonnier Corporation. Although the magazine is no longer in circulation, it remains a nostalgic symbol of American hunting and outdoor culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hunter-Trader-Trapper magazine offered a unique perspective on hunting and trapping in America, combining news, information, and entertainment to create a publication that was both informative and engaging. The magazine''s success paved the way for a variety of other outdoor publications, helping to shape American hunting and outdoor culture for decades to come.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hutchings' Illustrated California
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hutchings'' Illustrated California', N'hutchings-illustrated-california', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A 19th-century monthly magazine from San Francisco featuring California''s natural beauty with a focus on Yosemite, and engravings by California artists.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hutchings'' Illustrated California Magazine was a monthly publication that ran from 1856 to 1861. The magazine was published in San Francisco, California, and was named after its founder, James Mason Hutchings.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'James Mason Hutchings, a British immigrant, moved to California during the Gold Rush and became a successful businessman. In 1855, he founded the California Magazine, which focused on literature and news related to California.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The following year, Hutchings revived the magazine as Hutchings'' Illustrated California Magazine, with a stronger emphasis on art and illustration. The magazine featured engravings and lithographs of California landscapes, as well as portraits of Californians, and articles on natural history and travel in the state.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1861, Hutchings sold the magazine to another publisher, who changed the title to Hutchings'' California Magazine. The magazine continued to publish until 1866.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hutchings'' Illustrated California Magazine featured a mix of content, including fiction, poetry, and non-fiction. The magazine''s most distinctive feature was its illustrations, which were produced by some of California''s most talented artists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine featured articles on California''s natural beauty, with a focus on Yosemite Valley. Hutchings was an early advocate for the protection of Yosemite, and his magazine helped to promote the region to a wider audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its natural history content, Hutchings'' Illustrated California Magazine also featured articles and stories related to the social and political issues of the day.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hutchings'' Illustrated California Magazine is remembered as an important publication in the history of California literature and art. The magazine''s illustrations helped to promote appreciation for California''s natural beauty, and its articles and stories provided a window into the social and political issues of the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hutchings himself played a significant role in the development of Yosemite National Park, and the park''s Hutchings Museum was named in his honor.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hutchings'' Illustrated California Magazine played an important role in the development of California art and literature. Its illustrations and articles helped to promote appreciation for California''s natural beauty and bring attention to important social and political issues of the day.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hyphen
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hyphen', N'hyphen', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A non-profit magazine devoted to providing a platform for Asian American voices and experiences.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hyphen is a non-profit print and online magazine that focuses on Asian American perspectives.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hyphen was founded in 2002 by a group of San Francisco-based Asian Americans who felt that their voices were not adequately represented in mainstream media. The magazine''s name refers to the hyphenated identity of many Asian Americans, whose identities are often shaped by their Asian heritage and their experiences in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue of Hyphen was published in 2003, with a focus on music, film, and fashion. The magazine quickly gained a reputation for its in-depth reporting and thoughtful analysis of issues affecting the Asian American community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Since its founding, Hyphen has published articles on a wide range of topics, including politics, social issues, and entertainment. The magazine is known for its dedication to promoting Asian American voices and experiences, and for its celebration of the diversity and complexity of the Asian American community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hyphen covers a wide range of topics, with a particular focus on issues affecting the Asian American community. The magazine has published articles on topics such as immigration, discrimination, and cultural identity, as well as profiles of prominent Asian Americans and coverage of Asian American arts and culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hyphen''s website features a blog that provides daily news and commentary on current events, as well as exclusive web-only content that complements the magazine''s print offerings.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print and online content, Hyphen also sponsors events and educational programs that promote Asian American culture and address issues facing the community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Awards and Recognition' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hyphen has been recognized for excellence in journalism and design. In 2007, the magazine won a New America Media Award for Outstanding Community Coverage, and in 2011, it was recognized with a Maggie Award for Best Regularly Featured Department in a Consumer Publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2008, Hyphen won an Utne Reader Independent Press Award for Best New Magazine, and in 2009, it was named one of the "Top 25 Magazines of the Year" by the American Society of Magazine Editors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hyphen is a respected voice in the Asian American community, with a reputation for in-depth reporting and thoughtful analysis of issues affecting Asian Americans. The magazine''s dedication to promoting Asian American experiences and perspectives has made it an important part of the media landscape in the United States.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- I.D.
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'I.D.', N'i-d', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A former American magazine covering all aspects of design, known for showcasing emerging design trends and recognized for its distinctive design and photography.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'I.D. (International Design) magazine was an American magazine, focused on covering the industry of art and design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'I.D. was founded in 1954 by Monroe Wheeler, an art historian, and Harriette Estel Berman, a designer. The magazine was initially named "Industrial Design," and focused on the intersection of design and business. In the late 1970s and early 1980s, I.D. shifted its focus to cover all aspects of design, including architecture, fashion, and product design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1990, I.D. was acquired by F+W Media, who expanded its coverage to include digital and interactive design. Over the years, I.D. became known for its coverage of emerging design trends and for showcasing the work of emerging designers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, as of March 2009, F+W Media ceased the print version of the magazine and in May of the same year, they relaunched the website as an online-only publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'I.D. covered a wide range of design-related topics, including architecture, fashion, product design, and digital and interactive design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was known for its distinctive design and photography, and for its focus on emerging design trends. It regularly featured profiles of leading designers and architects, as well as in-depth articles on design-related topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print and online content, I.D. sponsored design competitions and educational programs, including the I.D. Annual Design Review, which recognized outstanding design achievements in various categories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Awards and Recognition' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'I.D. was recognized with a number of awards for its design and editorial content. In 2007, the magazine won a National Magazine Award for General Excellence in Design, and in 2009, it was named one of the "Top 40 Magazine Covers of the Last 40 Years" by the American Society of Magazine Editors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The end of the print edition of I.D. magazine was a blow to the design community and was mourned by many fans of the publication. However, the magazine''s influence on the design world continued to be felt after its closure. Many prominent designers and architects got their start in the pages of I.D., and the magazine''s focus on emerging design trends helped to shape the conversation around design in the United States and beyond.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Ignite Your Faith
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Ignite Your Faith', N'ignite-your-faith', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A Christian magazine inspiring young readers to engage with their faith and explore issues related to spiritual growth, prayer, and social issues.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ignite Your Faith (IYF) magazine was a popular American magazine focused on covering the Christian faith and inspiring young readers to engage with their faith.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'IYF was founded by Christianity Today International and launched in 1960 as Campus Life magazine. The focus of the magazine was to provide guidance and resourcing for Christian teenagers and young adults. They later changed the magazine''s name in 2008 to the current name.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'For over 60 years, the magazine was published under the auspices of Christianity Today International, one of the largest publishers of Christian media in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ignite Your Faith covered a broad range of topics related to the Christian faith, including personal stories of faith, spiritual growth, prayer, apologetics, and social issues. The magazine was known for its engaging and thought-provoking content, which inspired readers to think deeply about their faith and how it impacted their daily lives.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print content, Ignite Your Faith also maintained an active website and social media presence, featuring articles and videos on a range of Christian topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s primary audience was Christian teenagers and young adults, with a focus on inspiring them to engage in their faith and live out their beliefs in practical ways.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Ignite Your Faith was recognized with several awards for its content, including multiple awards from the Evangelical Press Association for its design and editorial content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Closure' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During a major reorganization of the publisher''s ministry in 2020, Christianity Today International made the decision to retire Ignite Your Faith and focus on other publications and digital media platforms.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the closure of Ignite Your Faith was a disappointment to many of its readers, the magazine''s legacy and impact on the Christian faith continued to be felt by many.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Illustrated American
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Illustrated American', N'the-illustrated-american', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A prominent American magazine known for its high-quality illustrations and coverage of events like the Spanish-American War and 1896 presidential election.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Illustrated American was a prominent American magazine that covered a broad range of topics including politics, culture, and society. It was known for its high-quality illustrations and engaging stories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Illustrated American was founded in 1890 by Walter S. Jackson and George W. Townsend. The magazine soon gained popularity for its coverage of events like the Spanish-American War and the presidential election of 1896.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s circulation grew rapidly, with over 100,000 subscribers by 1895. The Illustrated American was published on a weekly basis and featured articles written by well-known journalists and authors like Jack London and Theodore Roosevelt.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content of The Illustrated American covered a wide range of topics, including politics, culture, society, and the arts. The magazine was known for its high-quality illustrations which were produced by some of the most talented artists of the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the most popular features of the magazine was its coverage of the Spanish-American War. The magazine sent reporters and artists to the front lines of the conflict, and their coverage brought the realities of war to the American public.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Illustrated American appealed primarily to the middle and upper-class readers who were interested in politics, culture, and society. The magazine''s illustrations and stories captured the attention of the public, and its circulation continued to grow throughout the 1890s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity, The Illustrated American struggled financially due to rising costs associated with high-quality printing and illustrations. In 1898, the magazine was sold to Leslie''s Weekly and was eventually absorbed into that publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short lifespan, The Illustrated American left an indelible mark on American publishing. It played a significant role in shaping the visual language of American journalism and influencing the development of modern magazines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, original copies of The Illustrated American are highly sought after by collectors and historians alike, and the magazine is remembered as a significant contribution to the cultural and literary history of the United States.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Illustrated Police News Boston
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Illustrated Police News Boston', N'illustrated-police-news-boston', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A weekly illustrated publication in Boston during the late 19th to early 20th centuries known for its vivid descriptions of crimes and trials, often featuring illustrations and photographs.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Illustrated Police News was a weekly magazine published in Boston, Massachusetts, United States from 1869 to 1890. It was known for its groundbreaking use of photographs and illustrations to report on notorious crimes and other events taking place in Boston and New England.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Illustrated Police News of Boston was founded in 1869 by Edward F. Underhill, a well-known printer and publisher in the Boston area. The magazine was published on a weekly basis and sold primarily through newsstands.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s editorial team consisted of several experienced journalists and crime reporters, who worked alongside illustrators and photographers to produce a unique and compelling format that combined text, illustrations, and photographs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Illustrated Police News of Boston covered a wide range of topics, including notorious crimes, police investigations, trials, and other significant events taking place in Boston and the wider New England area. The magazine''s content was highly graphic and often included graphic illustrations and photographs of the crimes and events being reported.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also featured profiles of famous law enforcement officers and articles on criminal psychology and forensic science, making it popular with both law enforcement officials and the general public.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Illustrated Police News of Boston was primarily aimed at a working-class audience and was sold through newsstands and other retailers. The magazine''s graphic content and groundbreaking use of photographs and illustrations made it hugely popular among readers, who were fascinated by the lurid details of the crimes and events being reported.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was also widely read by law enforcement officials and lawyers, who appreciated its in-depth coverage of criminal cases and investigations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Illustrated Police News of Boston played a significant role in the development of modern crime reporting and journalism in the United States. The magazine''s use of photographs and illustrations helped establish a new standard for crime reporting, which was later adopted by newspapers and other publications across the country.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity, the magazine faced criticism from some quarters for its sensationalist reporting and graphic content. The magazine was eventually forced to cease publication in 1890, after a series of scandals and controversies eroded its reputation.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Imagine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Imagine', N'imagine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Imagine was an educational magazine aimed at children, covering topics such as science, history, and art to make learning fun and engaging for young readers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Imagine was an educational magazine aimed at children aged between six and twelve. The publication covered a range of topics, including science, history, and art.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Imagine was first published in 2006 by publisher Future plc. The magazine was published in the UK and was distributed internationally.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine had a team of editors and writers who were responsible for creating the content. The team included leading experts in the fields of science, history, and art.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Imagine was aimed at children and aimed to make learning fun. The magazine''s content was designed to be both informative and entertaining, and covered a range of topics, including science and technology, history, and art.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of Imagine contained features on specific topics, as well as puzzles, quiz and comic strips.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Imagine was popular with both children and parents, who praised the magazine for its quality and entertainment value. The magazine won several awards.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication was recommended by teachers and librarians as a valuable educational resource for children.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Cessation of Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2016, Future plc announced the closure of Imagine magazine. The final issue was published in December 2016.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its closure, Imagine magazine had a lasting impact on the educational publishing industry. The magazine inspired several other educational publications for children, many of which are still in circulation today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Clarkesworld Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Clarkesworld Magazine', N'clarkesworld-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American, monthly science fiction and fantasy publication offering a mix of genre short stories, interviews, and articles.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Clarkesworld Magazine is an American online monthly science fiction and fantasy magazine. It was launched in October 2006 by Neil Clarke, after whom the magazine is named. Apart from being an online magazine, Clarkesworld also releases its content as e-books, and there are print anthologies of selected stories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As of my last training cut-off in September 2021, the magazine published fiction and non-fiction from around the world, but primarily from American authors. They also have a podcast that features short stories from the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Clarkesworld is known for being very selective, publishing only a small fraction of the submissions they receive. This has allowed the magazine to maintain a high level of quality, and it has won numerous awards, including multiple Hugo Awards, World Fantasy Awards, and Nebula Awards, among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s content tends to be a mix of science fiction and fantasy, with a notable number of stories falling into the "soft" science fiction category. They often deal with big ideas and intellectual themes. Clarkesworld has been known for publishing stories that are a bit avant-garde and that push boundaries in various ways.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Additionally, Clarkesworld has been known to publish translations of science fiction stories from non-English speaking countries, making it a valuable source of international speculative fiction. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As of 2021, the magazine''s editorial staff consisted of editor-in-chief Neil Clarke, non-fiction editor Cheryl Morgan, and podcast director Kate Baker. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'For the most recent information, I would recommend visiting the magazine''s official website or their latest publications.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Access Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Access Magazine', N'access-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Canadian-based publication offering analysis and insights on disability issues, featuring interviews, reviews, and advocacy pieces.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Access Magazine' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Access Magazine* is a biannual publication based in the United States, specifically in Los Angeles. It was founded in 1992 by Melvin M. Webber, Professor of City and Regional Planning at the University of California, Berkeley, and ceased its print editions in 2017. Following this, the magazine transitioned into an online publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine reports on research conducted at the University of California Transportation Center and the University of California Center on Economic Competitiveness. The primary objective of *Access Magazine* is to translate academic research into readable prose that can be beneficial for policymakers and practitioners. It aims to propel academic research into debates about public policy, and to convert knowledge into actionable solutions. The authors of the papers published in *Access Magazine* are solely responsible for their content. Much of the research featured in *Access Magazine* was sponsored by the US Department of Transportation and the California Department of Transportation, neither of which is liable for its content or use.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The University of California Transportation Center (UCTC), a multi-campus organization headquartered on the UC Berkeley campus, facilitated research, education, and public service on the University of California campuses at Berkeley, Davis, Irvine, Los Angeles, Riverside, and Santa Barbara, and on the California State University campuses at Pomona, Sacramento, San Bernardino, and San Luis Obispo. UCTC published issues 1 through 44 of *Access Magazine* from the Fall of 1992 through the Spring of 2014. They also will be publishing the Spring 2016 and Fall 2016 issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Editor in Chief of *Access Magazine* is Donald Shoup, while John A. Mathews serves as the Managing Editor. Notably, the magazine has been used in the curricula of top Urban Planning programs including the University of California, Los Angeles, Cornell University, Rutgers University, the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Portland State University, and Florida State University.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Access Magazine* has achieved considerable recognition in its field. In 2013, it was named “Organization of the Year” at the 24th Annual California Transportation Funding (CTF) Transportation Awards, where it was cited as the “face of the University of California Transportation Center” and lauded for publishing “incisive commentary on transportation issues of the day”. It also received the American Planning Association''s (APA) 2014 National Planning Excellence Awards: Communications Initiative as well as APA California''s 2014 Communications Initiative Award. That same year, *Access Magazine* was awarded the Certificate of Excellence from the Western Publishing Association, being a Finalist in the “Initial Trade Print Categories: Semi-Annuals, Three-Time, and Quarterly”.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, *Access Magazine* has been widely referenced, reprinted, and translated in numerous publications, including Al Jazeera America, the Atlantic, Fortune, the Huffington Post, the Los Angeles Times, the New York Times, the Observer, the Telegraph, U.S. News & World Report, the Washington Post, and Wired, among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As of Spring 2016, *Access Magazine* had issued 48 print editions and had over 8,500 subscribers. The magazine''s reach and influence have grown over the years, making it one of the most widely read publications of transportation research.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Addicted to Noise
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Addicted to Noise', N'addicted-to-noise', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Online music publication of the 90s, renowned for extensive reviews, in-depth interviews, and constant updates on the rock scene.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Encyclopedia Article_' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Addicted to Noise* was a trailblazing online music magazine in the nascent days of the World Wide Web. Established in 1994 by ex-*Rolling Stone* associate editor and senior writer Michael Goldberg and online music pioneer Jon Luini, the magazine published its first issue in December 1994. Notably, *Addicted to Noise* was the first online publication to incorporate audio samples alongside new album reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine became known for its in-depth interviews with an array of artists, including R.E.M., Neil Young, Patti Smith, Sonic Youth, Chris Isaak, Eminem, Green Day, Metallica, American Music Club, Tom Waits, Paul Westerberg, Lou Reed, David Lowery of Cracker/Camper Van Beethoven, Sleater-Kinney, and Prince. The unique logo, initially a coat of arms with two syringes but later replaced with two guitars, was created by artist Frank Kozik, who regularly contributed graphics to the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Addicted to Noise*’s daily "Music News of the World" quickly became a go-to source of music news for MTV, numerous global radio stations, and many print publications, including *NME* and *Melody Maker*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The roster of contributors to *Addicted to Noise* read like a "who''s who" of music criticism. Names such as Dave Marsh, Mark Brown, Greil Marcus, Richard Meltzer, Ed Ward, Billy Altman, Deborah Frost, Bud Scoppa, Roy Trakin, Chris Morris, and more penned articles for the magazine. Notably, music and literary figures like Joey Ramone, William Gibson, Was (Not Was) co-leader David Was, Patti Smith Group guitarist Lenny Kaye, and Sleater-Kinney''s Corin Tucker also contributed guest columns or reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1997, *Addicted to Noise* and SonicNet were both purchased by Paradigm Music Entertainment. This company was subsequently bought by TCI Music, which was itself acquired by Viacom in 1999. After these transactions, *Addicted to Noise* was integrated into MTV''s online operation, MTVi, with Goldberg becoming a Senior Vice-President.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Post-*Addicted to Noise*, Goldberg went on to establish a music and culture blog, Days of the Crazy-Wild, and is a columnist for the Australian *Addicted to Noise*. Luini continues his work in the digital media field and serves as the president and founder of Chime Interactive, a digital media consulting agency. David Hyman, former Director of Ad Sales for *Addicted to Noise*, went on to found MOG.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In a later development, MTV initiated a short-lived online venture in 2008 using the same domain name as *Addicted to Noise*.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Addisonia Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Addisonia Magazine', N'addisonia-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Historic botanical periodical providing colored illustrations and descriptions of North American plants, active 1916-1964.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Addisonia* is a distinguished illustrated journal with a focus on botanical and horticultural themes. The *New York Botanical Garden* served as its publisher from 1916 until 1964.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The initiation of *Addisonia* was the result of a bequest by Judge Addison Brown, a co-founder of the *New York Botanical Garden*. The magazine''s content was dedicated exclusively to vascular plants originating from the United States and its territorial possessions, or those flowering within the *New York Botanical Garden* or its conservatories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first editors of *Addisonia* were the botanist John Hendley Barnhart and George Valentine Nash, who was the head gardener of the *Botanical Garden* at that time. Subsequent editors included Henry Gleason and Edward Johnston Alexander.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Originally, *Addisonia* was a quarterly publication. However, various factors led to an extension in the publication schedule over time. Starting with volume 18 in 1933–34, the magazine transitioned to a semi-annual schedule; by volume 21 in 1939, it had become an annual publication. During its last few years, issues were printed irregularly as funds became available. Remarkably, the cover price of $10 remained unchanged over the magazine’s 50-year history.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its first five years, *Addisonia* encompassed a wide range of topics such as acacias, dwarf polyantha roses, and cacti. The principal illustrator of the magazine in its initial three decades was Mary Emily Eaton, a staff illustrator at the *New York Botanical Garden*. Eaton was responsible for creating over three-quarters of the magazine''s 800 plates.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, *Addisonia* is still recognized as a valuable reference work and educational tool due to the high quality of its illustrations, the detailed plant descriptions provided by renowned authorities, and the meticulous provision of bibliographical citations. Throughout its existence, *Addisonia* reported on three new genera and 31 new species.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Adriatic Review
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Adriatic Review', N'the-adriatic-review', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Quarterly journal discussing the culture, history, politics, and current affairs of the countries bordering the Adriatic Sea.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# The Adriatic Review' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_The Adriatic Review_ was a monthly periodical published in Boston, United States. It was issued for the first time in September 1918 and its final issue was released in October 1919. The magazine was published by Vatra, the Pan-Albanian Federation of America, and it was aimed at disseminating information about Albania and its cause.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first editor of _The Adriatic Review_ was Fan Noli, who managed the journal for the initial six months of its existence. Following Noli, the editorial helm was taken over in 1919 by Constantin Anastas Chekrezi, also known as Costa Chekrezi. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The language of publication for _The Adriatic Review_ was English. As a product of its time and a bridge between cultures, this periodical offered valuable insights into the historical context of Albania in the early 20th century. Its mission was to serve as an informative and educational resource, spreading knowledge and understanding about Albania to its readership. Throughout its brief span of publication, _The Adriatic Review_ demonstrated a clear commitment to this mission, fostering a deeper appreciation of Albanian culture and history among its readers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Advance for Medical Laboratory Professionals
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Advance for Medical Laboratory Professionals', N'advance-for-medical-laboratory-professionals', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Professional resource for medical lab professionals, featuring latest industry news, research updates, and career advice.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Advance for Medical Laboratory Professionals* was a business magazine catering to the medical laboratory field. This biweekly trade journal was initially established in 1991, and throughout its circulation, it catered to a diverse audience of medical laboratory professionals. This included bench technologists, chief technologists, cytotechnologists, generalists, histotechnologists, laboratory directors and managers, laboratory section heads, medical laboratory scientists and technicians, blood specialists, educators, and others within the medical laboratory field. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s format included both paper and online mediums. It was owned by Merion Matters and operated from its headquarters in King of Prussia, Pennsylvania, USA. The editor during its operation was Matthew T. Patton. The magazine’s ISSN was 1088-5676 and it had an online presence known as "Advance for Laboratory."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Advance for Medical Laboratory Professionals* was known for its special issues. These included the education issue, the National Medical Laboratory Professionals Week issue, the industry outlook issue, the new graduate issue, and the annual safety issue. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its regular content, the publication conducted a biannual salary survey of laboratory professionals in collaboration with another publication, *Advance for Administrators of the Laboratory*. Furthermore, it featured a regular column titled “Ask NCA”, thanks to an editorial agreement with the National Credentialing Agency for Laboratory Personnel Inc.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Advance for Medical Laboratory Professionals* gained recognition for its contributions to the field of medical laboratory science. It received the Corporate Recognition Award from the Pennsylvania chapter of the American Society for Clinical Laboratory Science. In 2006, the magazine''s editor, Matthew Patton, won an award in the Awards for Publication Excellence in the Editorial and Advocacy Writing category.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'At the height of its popularity, the magazine had a circulation of 41,875. However, it has since ceased publication.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Advent Tidende
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Advent Tidende', N'advent-tidende', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Danish Seventh-day Adventist publication, providing religious study, news, and spiritual enlightenment from 1876 to 1947.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Advent Tidende' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Advent Tidende*, known as *Advent Herald* in Danish, was a Christian magazine published in the United States. This monthly periodical, printed in the Danish language, was in circulation from 1871 to 1883. Its editor was John Gotlieb Matteson and the publisher was Syvende-Dags Advent Trykkeri-Selskab. The magazine was headquartered in Battle Creek, Michigan, a city known for its significant Seventh-day Adventist population.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication of *Advent Tidende* marked the first time the Seventh-day Adventists published in a language other than English. The magazine was initiated by the Scandinavian Seventh-day Adventists, a Protestant Christian denomination. The first issue was a 21-page monthly publication, but in the second year of its existence, the magazine expanded to thirty-two pages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its run, several copies of *Advent Tidende* were sent to both Denmark and Norway from the USA. When the magazine ceased publication in 1883, its legacy was carried forward by its successor, *Sandhedens Tidende*.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Armchair General
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Armchair General', N'armchair-general', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Interactive strategy and history magazine, offering in-depth military analysis alongside stimulating war gaming experiences.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Armchair General' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Armchair General* was an American military history magazine that was established in 2003 and first published in February 2004. Published by the Weider History Group, the magazine was circulated bi-monthly until its final issue in May 2015. The magazine’s headquarters was located in Thousands Oaks, California.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Armchair General* featured a variety of content focused on military history and warfare. It included tactical situations which could be resolved by readers sending solutions to the magazine''s staff. Modern warfare was also discussed in the form of "dispatches", or news briefs, as well as movie, video game, and war game reviews. The magazine was well-regarded for its in-depth coverage and unique reader engagement model, earning a spot as number 25 on the *Chicago Tribune''s* list of "Best 50 Magazines" in June 2005.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though the print publication of *Armchair General* ceased in 2015, the magazine’s website continued to provide complementary material and feature its own articles. Many of these online articles were written by readers of the print magazine and members of the site''s online forum community, further fostering a sense of community among its audience.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Adventure Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Adventure Magazine', N'adventure-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Pulp fiction periodical showcasing thrilling tales of exploration, peril, and heroism, active from 1921 to 1971.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_**Adventure**_ was an American pulp magazine first published in November 1910 by the Ridgway company, a subsidiary of the Butterick Publishing Company. The magazine was notably successful, becoming one of the most profitable and critically acclaimed of all American pulp magazines, with a total of 881 issues published.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Its first editor was Trumbull White, succeeded in 1912 by Arthur Sullivant Hoffman (1876–1966), who would remain the editor until 1927. Over the years, _Adventure_ showcased fiction from distinguished writers such as Rider Haggard, Rafael Sabatini, Gouverneur Morris, Baroness Orczy, Damon Runyon, and William Hope Hodgson. The magazine nurtured a core group of authors, referred to by Hoffman as his "Writers'' Brigade". Each member of the brigade had their own specific areas of fictional focus, ranging from colonial India to the South Seas, from medieval Europe to the Western frontier.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1912, Hoffman, along with his assistant, novelist Sinclair Lewis, created a popular identity card with a serial number for readers. This card served a unique purpose: if the cardholder were to die, a finder of the card would notify the magazine, which would then notify the individual''s next of kin. The popularity of this initiative among travellers led to the formation of the Adventurers'' Club of New York, which inspired the establishment of similar clubs in Chicago, Los Angeles, Copenhagen, and Honolulu.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine took an unsuccessful detour in 1915, attempting to appeal to women readers with a new title (_Stories of Life, Love, and Adventure_), but reverted to its original title and male readership in 1917.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hoffman also served as secretary of an organization named the "Legion", which counted Theodore Roosevelt Jr. as one of its vice presidents. This group played a significant role during World War I, with membership cards detailing members'' skills and specialties being forwarded to the War Department. The information was used to create two regiments of aviation mechanics and provided a model for the American Legion''s organization after the war.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Adventure_ had an interactive relationship with its readership. Its letters page, "The Camp-Fire", not only featured Hoffman''s editorials and background information from authors about their stories, but also discussions by the readers. Hoffman encouraged the establishment of Camp-Fire Stations, meeting places for _Adventure_ readers, which were so popular that by 1924, they had been set up across the United States and in several other countries, including Britain, Australia, Egypt, and Cuba.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also featured several notable columns, including "Ask Adventure", which utilized the expertise of 98 specialists to answer various questions, ranging from the status of slavery in Ethiopia to the fighting prowess of lions versus gorillas. Several of _Adventure_''s fiction writers contributed to this column, providing insights based on their respective areas of expertise. Other columns included "Lost Trails", which aided people in finding missing relatives and friends, and "Old Songs Men Have Sung", a column dedicated to the discussion of American folk songs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Adventure_ continued its publication until 1971, undergoing several format changes and outlasting all its major rivals. The period of Hoffman''s editorship from 1912 to 1927 is widely regarded as the high-water mark in the magazine''s history, in terms of both its quality and popularity.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Adventurers Club
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Adventurers Club', N'adventurers-club', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Youth-oriented publication centered on outdoor activities, expeditions, science, environment, and nature education.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Adventurers Club* was a quarterly magazine first published in 1983 by Hero Games, a renowned name in the gaming industry. The editorial mantle was held at different times by Steve Peterson, Bill Robinson, and Bruce Harlick, with the latter having a longstanding 20-year relationship with Hero Games, culminating in his role as company president. In total, the magazine had a 12-year run, concluding in 1995 with a total of 27 issues published.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine originally featured supplementary material for Champions and Espionage, two popular games from Hero Games. It also included news from Hero Games and a letter column that was, amusingly, purportedly edited by the fictional villain Foxbat. However, by 1986, Hero Games was having issues with cash flow and manpower, and the magazine''s seventh issue, which had been prepared in March 1985, was delayed for over a year as resources were diverted toward other projects.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1988, Hero Games merged with Iron Crown Enterprises (ICE), leading to a significant change in the magazine''s content. Five issues of the magazine, from number 8 to number 12, featured articles about both Hero and ICE games. This did not sit well with the readership, who were divided over the inclusion of ICE game articles. Consequently, the magazine once again dedicated itself solely to Hero games, while ICE published a separate tabloid magazine, Iron Crown Quarterly, which focused only on ICE games such as Rolemaster, Spacemaster, and Middle-earth Role Playing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Adventurers Club* received mixed reviews over its lifetime. Allen Varney, who reviewed the magazine twice in the pages of Dragon, criticized its inconsistency in maintaining a quarterly publication, noting that it had “appeared more or less annually for years.” He also highlighted some concerns about the magazine''s style, grammar, and value for money. However, he acknowledged its attention-worthy scenarios, NPCs, gadgets, and campaigning tips. He further noted that the magazine''s coverage of all the different Hero System game genres meant that any single issue may not offer much for individual campaigns. On the other hand, in the Nov-Dec 1983 edition of Space Gamer, Russell Grant Collins recommended the magazine for players of Champions, calling it a “worthy addition to the Hero line.”' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the *Adventurers Club* magazine had its share of challenges and criticisms, it remains a significant artifact in the history of role-playing games, embodying a specific era of gaming culture and serving as a testament to the enduring influence of Hero Games.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Airliners Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Airliners Magazine', N'airliners-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Comprehensive magazine offering in-depth coverage of global aviation news, historical retrospectives, and high-quality aircraft photography.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# _Airliners_' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Airliners_ was an American magazine dedicated to the airline industry, with six issues circulated each year. The magazine was first published by World Transport Press in 1988. From the 100th issue, released in July/August 2006, it was produced by Airliners Publications, LLC. Initially, the editorial headquarters of the magazine was situated in Castro Valley, California, but later it relocated to Miami.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was dedicated to the civil aviation sector, presenting articles about the world of commercial aircraft and air carriers. The range of covered topics was broad, encompassing new low-cost airlines, changes at legacy companies, as well as descriptions of jetliners such as the Airbus A380 and Boeing 787. Furthermore, the magazine also included articles about trips around the world, historical airlines, adventurous flights, airliner crashes, and images of airliner liveries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Airliners_ featured a host of esteemed authors including John Adlard, Sebastian Schmitz, Dave Nichols, Ben Wang, Bill Hough, Joel Chusid, Royal King, Robbie Shaw, and Cody Diamond. Additionally, the magazine also highlighted the contributions of photographers who provided images of airlines, aircraft, personnel, facilities, and operations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'John Wegg was the magazine''s first editor, who later left _Airliners_ to found Airways Magazine in 1994. The subsequent editors included Bryant Pettit, Nick Veronico, Jon Proctor, David Kaufman, and Jay Selman. Starting with the November/December 2007 issue, the editor was Dwayne Darnell. On December 11, 2009, Darnell announced his departure, and Robert Christensen, the designer and Creative Director, assumed the leadership of the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2010, under the leadership of Robert Christensen, the magazine embarked on a series of online initiatives, including releasing e-book formats of the print magazine and establishing a social media presence. The magazine was re-titled as _Airliners & Airports_. It endeavored to bring back popular components from past issues such as the Air Photo News section to the magazine''s pages. However, around the end of December 2012, the magazine abruptly ceased publishing, and the website is no longer active.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Airman Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Airman Magazine', N'airman-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Official U.S. Air Force publication focusing on the service''s news, technology, operations, and personnel stories.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# *Airman Magazine*' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Airman Magazine* is the official publication of the United States Air Force. It serves as a key source of information and news pertaining to Air Force members and their families, addressing issues of interest and relevance to this audience. The magazine is produced by the Defense Media Activity group for the Secretary of the Air Force Office of Public Affairs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The inception of *Airman Magazine* can be traced back to August 1957, when it was first published under the title *The Airman*. Prior to this, the magazine''s direct predecessor was the *Air Service Weekly Newsletter*, which began publication on September 21, 1918. The last printed edition of *Airman Magazine* was released on September 1, 2011, and the magazine transitioned to a digital format, with the September/October 2011 edition being the first to be published online.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The digital format of *Airman Magazine* has been designed specifically for Apple and Android tablet users, offering in-depth feature stories and high-quality photos that readers have come to expect from the publication. This format also introduces layers of multimedia content and interactivity only available through new publishing techniques. A limited interactive version of the magazine is also viewable in web browser format. For more stories, readers are directed to *Airman Online*, the website for the official magazine of the U.S. Air Force.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Airman Magazine* also publishes *The Book* annually, which is a summary of basic Air Force facts, including summaries of weapons and aircraft. An archive of past issues is available in .pdf format, providing a valuable resource for those interested in the history and operations of the U.S. Air Force.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- All About Beer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'All About Beer', N'all-about-beer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Specialty periodical covering the culture, history, and diversity of beer, with reviews, brewing tips, and industry news.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# *All About Beer*' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*All About Beer* was an esteemed English-language magazine, known for its comprehensive coverage of the beer community. The magazine was first established in Los Angeles in 1979 by Mike Bosak, a printing executive, along with six of his colleagues from the printing and publishing industry. The inaugural issue was launched in March of the same year, marking the beginning of a legacy that would span four decades.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine emerged as a respected source for news, features, analysis, and reviews related to the beer industry. It was lauded for its dedication to covering the people, places, news, trends, and events that defined the beer community. This commitment continued under the stewardship of long-time journalists Andy Crouch and John Holl, who relaunched the magazine''s website, allaboutbeer.com, in 2022.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, the magazine''s influence extended beyond its pages. For thirty-nine years, *All About Beer* was home to some of the most revered writers in the scene and played a significant role in the craft beer movement, both nationally and in North Carolina. In addition to its editorial contributions, the magazine and its staff were behind the well-known World Beer Festival and were instrumental in key industry developments like the 2005 change to North Carolina law that allowed the state''s beer scene to flourish.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its existence, *All About Beer* consistently positioned itself on the leading edge of the burgeoning craft beer scene. Even in its early years, when there were fewer than one hundred breweries across America, the magazine foresaw the burgeoning movement of craft and small-batch brewing. It championed this ultra-nouveau trend, contributing significantly to the growth and recognition of now-famous brands like Sierra Nevada.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s mission extended beyond simply promoting or documenting the evolving craft beer industry. It aimed to educate the public about beer appreciation and beer quality, helping to elevate the image of beer in the public''s eye and demonstrating that beer could be as well-respected as wine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the mid-nineties, the magazine further expanded its reach by introducing the World Beer Festival. This event brought brewers from around the country to Durham, thus furthering the magazine''s mission of beer education in a way that transcended traditional print media【33†source】.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its profound impact and beloved status in the beer world, *All About Beer* faced challenges. Under previous owner Chris Rice, the magazine filed for bankruptcy in 2019【17†source】. The discontinuation of its issues on newsstands was regarded as a sad event by beer enthusiasts and industry insiders alike【29†source】.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*All About Beer* remains a significant part of beer industry history, remembered for its commitment to education, enjoyment, and the promotion of beer culture. Its legacy continues to influence the narrative of the beer community, reflecting its enduring relevance even after its print publication ceased.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- All-Star Western
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'All-Star Western', N'all-star-western', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Comic anthology series spotlighting tales of the Old West and its legendary heroes, published from 1951 to 1961.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# All-Star Western' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*All-Star Western* was a renowned American comic book series published by DC Comics. The series, which centered around Western fiction, featured both continuing characters and anthological stories. It was not a single continuous series, but rather three distinct series that carried the *All-Star Western* name. The first run spanned from 1951 to 1961, the second from 1970 to 1972, and the third was part of The New 52 and ran from September 2011 to August 2014.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The original *All-Star Western* began with issue #58 in May 1951, taking over the number of its predecessor title, *All Star Comics*—a superhero omnibus that had introduced the enduring team, the Justice Society of America. With the postwar decline in the popularity of superheroes, DC Comics altered the series format and title. This first series of *All-Star Western* ran for 62 bimonthly issues, culminating with issue #119 in July 1961. The cover logo did not incorporate a hyphen until issue #108 in September 1959, when it was significantly reduced in size and placed above the much larger logo for what was then the title feature, “Johnny Thunder”. This character shared the cover space with Madame .44, the “masked outlaw queen”, for some issues, and remained on the cover until the final issue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue of *All-Star Western* contained the features "The Trigger Twins", created by writer Robert Kanigher and penciler Carmine Infantino and running through #116; "Don Caballero", drawn by Gil Kane, and "Roving Ranger", penciled by Alex Toth, the writer-creator uncredited; and "Strong Bow", created by writer David Wood and artist Frank Giacoia. Other features that appeared throughout the years included "Super-Chief", by writer Gardner Fox and artist Infantino; and, beginning with #67 in November 1952, "Johnny Thunder", featuring the masked, vigilante persona of a schoolteacher in an Old West Mormon settlement. This character had been created by writer Kanigher and artist Toth in DC''s *All-American Comics* in 1948.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series experienced a revival in the following decade, running for 11 bimonthly issues from September 1970 to May 1972 before changing its title and slightly its format to become *Weird Western Tales*. *All-Star Western* vol. 2, #1 starred Pow-Wow Smith, scripted by John Broome, with art by Carmine Infantino. The next four starred the characters Outlaw and El Diablo. From issue #5, the character Outlaw was dropped, with the cover logo "Outlaw" now referring to the replacement-feature star, Billy the Kid. The Western "all-stars" now included such historical characters as Wild Bill Hickok, Buffalo Bill, and Davy Crockett, in a mix of new stories and reprints, as well as DC stalwarts Pow-Wow Smith, El Diablo, and Bat Lash.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Issue #10 in February–March 1972 introduced the enduring and popular character Jonah Hex, created by writer John Albano and artist Tony DeZuniga. Jonah Hex continued as the star of the comic when it changed its name to *Weird Western Tales* with issue #12 in July 1972, and he persisted into issue #38 in February 1977 of the 59-issue series.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As part of the line-wide The New 52 relaunch in September 2011, the series was revived once more, written by' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Justin Gray and Jimmy Palmiotti with art by Moritat. This iteration of the series followed the adventures of Jonah Hex and Amadeus Arkham in an Old West-version of Gotham City, with back-up tales featuring other Western characters.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*All-Star Western* was a magazine-format publication and was part of DC’s ongoing series during its runs. The series was published in English and ran from April-May 1951 to June-July 1961, comprising 62 issues from #58 to #119. The publication maintained standard dimensions, transitioning from standard Golden Age U.S. to standard Silver Age U.S. over its lifetime. It featured a glossy cover and newsprint interior, held together with saddle-stitch binding.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The indicia titles varied slightly during the run of the series, with issues #58-59 carrying the title *All-Star Western*, and issues #60-119 titled *All Star Western*. All script and art credits for stories and fillers in the series have been verified from copies of DC editorial records.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over its various runs, *All-Star Western* left an indelible mark on the landscape of American comic books, introducing enduring characters and exploring the rich tapestry of the Old West through its unique blend of continuing characters and anthological stories.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Alt Variety
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Alt Variety', N'alt-variety', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Publication focused on alternative culture, highlighting underground art, music, fashion, and pop culture phenomena.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Alt Variety' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Alt Variety* was a New York City-based monthly publication that centered on alternative and subversive themes. Having first appeared online in February 2012, it eventually ceased operations in July 2013.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s inception can be traced back to the internet''s earliest alternative Usenet newsgroups. These groups were characterized as obscure and largely unregulated, their identities often concealed by arcane prefixes such as ''alt''. *Alt Variety* emerged from this milieu under the guidance of Luke H. Walker, who assumed the pseudonym Lee Wong. By the time it made its transition from the digital sphere to physical stands as a free publication, the magazine had garnered a reputation for its daring and unconventional content, particularly the publication of remarkable yet veritable tales from the demimondaine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Alt Variety* had a humble inception as a strictly online blog, with a focus on various themes such as investigative reporting, fringe culture, satirical political inquiries, the arts, as well as more controversial topics like pornography and illicit drug use. Regular celebrity interviews were also a part of the magazine''s offerings, though these were far from ordinary. Rather than adhering to a standard narrative, these interviews often veered towards the eccentric and the unexpected, providing a unique spin on the familiar format.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Amateur Astronomer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Amateur Astronomer', N'the-amateur-astronomer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Resource for astronomy enthusiasts, providing sky charts, observing tips, and articles on celestial phenomena and equipment.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Amateur Astronomer* was a four-page bulletin circulated by the Amateur Astronomers Association of New York from 1929 to 1935. The inaugural editor was C. S. Brainin, and starting in 1933, a section titled “Meteor Notes” was managed by Virginia Geiger. The publication''s life came to a close in 1935 when it amalgamated with *The Sky*, a publication produced by the Hayden Planetarium. This union did not mark the end of *The Amateur Astronomer*''s lineage, as *The Sky* later merged with *The Telescope* in 1941 to form *Sky & Telescope*, a periodical that continues to be printed to this day.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Amazing World of DC Comics
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Amazing World of DC Comics', N'the-amazing-world-of-dc-comics', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Specialized fanzine providing insights into DC Comics universe, with exclusive interviews, previews, and behind-the-scenes content.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Amazing World of DC Comics* was a self-produced fan magazine by DC Comics that ran for 17 issues from July/August 1974 to April 1978. This exclusive fanzine, available only through mail order, offered an in-depth exploration of DC characters, their creators, and the broader Bronze Age DC corporate and creative culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was conceived by DC production manager Sol Harrison. Bob Rozakis, who started his career through letters to comic book letter columns, was tasked to oversee its development. Rozakis not only edited the magazine but also contributed to its content and managed the letters page. He was supported by a team of young fans turned DC Comics editorial employees, fondly known as the "Junior Woodchucks". Carl Gafford, another key contributor, took on multiple roles including editing, writing, production work, and color separations. Each issue could be subscribed for $1.50.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The editorial team of the magazine saw a few changes during its run. Initially, the bulk of the issues were edited by Allan Asherman, followed by Paul Levitz and then Cary Burkett. Individual issues were edited by Carl Gafford, Bob Rozakis, and Neal Pozner. The list of contributors to the magazine includes names like Ramona Fradon, Jack C. Harris, Nestor Redondo, Steve Skeates, Michael Uslan, Wally Wood, and Mark Gruenwald.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Amazing World of DC Comics* not only provided text articles but occasionally also featured previously unpublished stories and artwork. Examples include Jack Kirby’s material intended for “In the Days of the Mob #2 Murder Inc”, Tony DeZuniga’s artwork for Jonah Hex, and John Rosenberger’s last penciled pages originally intended for Wonder Woman.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The inaugural issue of the magazine offered a diverse range of features, including an interview with Joe Kubert, a retrospective of the Superman television series, an overview of the comic creation process, and a decade-by-decade retrospective titled “Yesteryear”. Issue #7 promoted “The Legend of King Arthur and the Knights of the Round Table”, a four-part King Arthur treasury edition series that was never published. In a notable revelation, issue #14 stated that Clark Kent''s hometown of Smallville was in Maryland, a location that was later supported in the actual comics with a map of Smallville and the surrounding area.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its tenure, *The Amazing World of DC Comics* served as a rich source of insight into the universe of DC Comics, its characters, and the individuals who brought them to life.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The American Architect
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The American Architect', N'the-american-architect', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Archived architectural publication showcasing design trends, theories, blueprints, and works of prominent architects (1876–1938).}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The American Architect* was a periodical on architecture, published in the United States between 1876 and 1938. Initially christened as *The American Architect and Building News*, the magazine underwent its first name change in 1909, becoming *The American Architect*. Subsequently, it underwent a few more name alterations. In 1921, it absorbed the *Architectural Review* and carried both names. However, in 1925, the magazine reverted to its original name, *The American Architect*. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded in 1876 and was originally published by Ticknor and Company Publishers, situated on Tremont Street in Boston, Massachusetts. Over its lifespan, it was later published by Swetland Publishing Company and Standard Publishing Company. The periodical was published annually, with its final issue, volume 152, released in 1938. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its publication, *The American Architect* merged with other periodicals. Around 1920, it merged with the *Architectural Review*. In August of 1929, the magazine was bought by International, a division of Hearst, and its title was changed to *The American Architect*. Later, it merged with *Architecture* and carried both titles. The magazine’s final merger occurred in 1938 when it was absorbed by *Architectural Record*. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was known to cover a range of topics within architecture, including building and construction, and it has been described as a historical journal. However, the specifics of the magazine’s content and its impact on the architectural world are more elusive due to limited online resources. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Unfortunately, I was unable to find specific information on the magazine''s influence or legacy in the field of architecture. The exact nature of its content, beyond a general focus on building and construction, is also not clearly documented in the available online sources. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, it’s important to note that the magazine was published during a transformative period in American architectural history, from the late 19th century into the early 20th century. This was a time of rapid urbanization and industrialization, and the architecture of the period reflects these broader societal changes. Therefore, while the specific influence of *The American Architect* is not well-documented, it was undoubtedly a part of the larger discourse of architecture during this pivotal era.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Chess Bulletin
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Chess Bulletin', N'american-chess-bulletin', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Dedicated chess magazine (1904–1963) featuring coverage of tournaments, game analysis, and news from the international chess scene.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# *American Chess Bulletin*' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The American Chess Bulletin* was a revered chess periodical, published monthly from November through April and bimonthly from May through October. It originated in 1904 and continued its run until 1963. The magazine’s operations were conducted from the bustling city of New York. The distinguished Hermann Helms (1870–1963) founded the *American Chess Bulletin* and served as its editor until his death. After Helms’ demise, the publication came to a halt.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The maiden issue of the *Bulletin*, produced in collaboration with Hartwig Cassel, was an elaborate report on the esteemed Cambridge Springs tournament of 1904. The magazine’s content transcended mere reporting on chess events; it included news of the regional chess organizations that eventually amalgamated to form the United States Chess Federation. After 1933, the *North American Chess Reporter* was incorporated with the *Bulletin*. Notable chess personalities, such as Samuel Reshevsky, were among those who contributed articles to the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to Hermann Helms, the *American Chess Bulletin* saw other eminent individuals serve as its editors. Hartwig Cassel held the position from 1904 to 1917, and Edgar Holladay from 1956 to 1963. The magazine was described as being “Devoted to the Interests of all Branches of the Royal Game, Home and Abroad,” reflecting its comprehensive coverage of chess activities. It held the status of the official publication of the United States Chess Federation until 1933.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The American Cricketer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The American Cricketer', N'the-american-cricketer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Historic publication (1877–1929) on cricket, featuring match reports, player profiles, and articles enhancing understanding of the sport.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The American Cricketer* was a significant publication of record for club cricket in the United States, with a publication history that spanned over half a century. First published in Philadelphia in 1877, the slim magazine continued to grace the printing press through 1929, a total of 52 years. During the summer cricketing season, *The American Cricketer* was published weekly, transitioning to a monthly frequency during the winter months.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'George Newhall, a member of the renowned Newhall cricketing family of Philadelphia, served as one of its esteemed editors. His stewardship, along with that of other dedicated individuals, allowed the magazine to flourish and provide a rich source of information about the state of cricket in the United States during that period.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the magazine''s primary focus was cricket, it also served as a chronicle for the broader American cricketing community. It provided a consistent and reliable source of news, updates, and analysis, making it an invaluable resource for those interested in the sport. Over its 52-year publication history, *The American Cricketer* played an instrumental role in the development and propagation of cricket across the United States.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 73 Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'73 Magazine', N'73-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Amateur radio enthusiast periodical (1960–2003), offering technical advice, construction projects, and news within the ham radio community.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*73 Magazine*, alternatively known as *73 Amateur Radio Today*, was a United States-based periodical dedicated to the subject of amateur radio. The magazine was first published in 1960 and continued to issue monthly editions until 2003. It was renowned for its technical articles and the extensive editorials in each issue penned by the founder and publisher, Wayne Green.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s title, *73*, refers to a term in amateur radio lingo, translating to “best regards” when expressed in Morse code. The inaugural issue was launched from Green’s business offices located in Brooklyn, New York, in October 1960. A key contributing editor was Ken Sessions, K6MVH, who penned a column titled “The Chronicles of 76”, alluding to the FM transmitting frequency of 146.76 megahertz. Sessions was not only a prolific writer on the subject of amateur radio but also the designer of many how-to projects featured in the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jean Shepherd, K2ORS, was another notable contributor to *73 Magazine*. The publication had a significant impact on the amateur radio community, pioneering the promotion of SSB, FM, solid-state, easy construction projects, and most importantly, the fusion of personal computing and amateur radio. In 1962, the headquarters of *73 Magazine* relocated to Peterborough, New Hampshire. During the 1970s and 80s, the average issue of *73* comprised over 300 pages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*73 Magazine* was particularly known for its editorial column, “Never Say Die”, where Green, along with Sessions, often voiced criticism towards the American Radio Relay League. The column’s title, “Never Say Die”, was a clever backronym for Green’s amateur radio call sign, W2NSD. Green also founded several microcomputing magazines such as “Desktop Computing”, “Kilobaud Microcomputing”, and “80 Micro”, and played a role in the establishment of *Byte Magazine*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2003, after 43 years of uninterrupted publication, *73 Amateur Radio Today* announced its final issue in September. There was a plan for a combined October/November 2003 issue, which, however, never saw the light of day. Financial pressure resulting from diminished advertising revenue was cited by Green as the primary cause for halting the magazine''s publication.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Film Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Film Magazine', N'american-film-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly publication (1975–1992) providing comprehensive coverage of the American motion picture industry, its trends, and personalities.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# *American Film*' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Film* is a film and entertainment magazine originating from the United States. The publication, which was initially released on a monthly basis, was founded in 1975 by the American Film Institute (AFI). The last print issue was produced in 1992, marking a significant period in the magazine''s history.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine earned a reputation for its focus on analysis and deconstructionist criticism, offering content in a format similar to *Film Comment* magazine. This intellectual approach provided readers with in-depth insights into the world of cinema, making *American Film* a cherished resource for film aficionados.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In April 2012, the AFI undertook the task of reviving *American Film*, launching it as a monthly digital edition. This move marked the magazine''s transition from traditional print to the digital medium, adapting to the evolving landscape of media consumption while continuing to provide its audience with high-quality film criticism and analysis.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine maintains an online presence through its website, serving as a platform for its digital edition and continuing the legacy of *American Film* into the modern era of digital publishing.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Girl
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Girl', N'american-girl', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Bimonthly magazine for girls ages 8 to 14, focusing on self-esteem, social issues, and creativity through crafts, games, and advice.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Girl* is a magazine that was managed by the American Girl company, originally initiated by the Pleasant Company based in Middleton, Wisconsin in 1992. The inaugural issue was published in November/December 1992. Tailored specifically for girls aged 8–14, this bimonthly publication encompassed an array of content, including articles, recipes, advice columns, fiction, arts and crafts, as well as a variety of activity ideas. However, in late 2018, the American Girl company declared that the January/February 2019 issue would mark the magazine''s final publication.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Heritage
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Heritage', N'american-heritage', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Quarterly magazine (1954–present) focusing on American history and culture, featuring articles by popular historians and writers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Heritage* is a magazine predominantly focused on the history of the United States, catering to a mainstream readership. Founded in 1947, its initial purpose was to serve as a house organ for the American Association for State and Local History under the title *American Heritage: A Journal of Community History*. However, it broadened its scope in September 1949, targeting a wider audience while still maintaining features designed for educators and historical societies.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1954, the magazine was sold to a group of writers and editors from Time, Inc. This team, which included James Parton, Oliver Jensen, Joseph J. Thorndike, and Pulitzer Prize-winning historian Bruce Catton, transformed the publication into a hardcover, 120-page, advertisement-free “magazine”. It was from December 1954 onwards that the magazine, under the stewardship of the newly formed American Heritage Publishing Company, started a new volume numbering system. Each volume began in December and continued through the following October, with issues published every other month. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Bruce Catton remained with the magazine for 25 years until his death in 1979, contributing over 100 essays. He emphasized the necessity of viewing history without undue nostalgia, thus ensuring accurate understanding. Notable author David McCullough began his writing career as an editor and writer for *American Heritage* in 1964, often referring to the magazine as “my graduate school”. His articles on topics such as the Johnstown Flood and the transcontinental railroad were later expanded into bestselling books.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The *American Heritage* publishing company was purchased by McGraw-Hill in 1969, then acquired by Samuel P. Reed in 1978. The transition to a high-quality softcover format occurred in 1980 due to rising costs. The magazine was subsequently bought by Forbes in 1986. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine ceased publication temporarily with the April/May 2007 issue. Edwin S. Grosvenor, former editor of the fine arts magazine *Portfolio* and other publications, bought the magazine from Forbes later that year. He has since served as the president and editor-in-chief. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Print publication was suspended in 2013, but *American Heritage* was resurrected in digital format in 2017, complete with a new website and subscriber management system. As of the Winter 2020 issue, the magazine continued to feature essays from renowned historians on diverse topics that illuminate what makes America great.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Machinist
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Machinist', N'american-machinist', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Technical journal (established 1876) providing insights about advancements and trends in the machining and metalworking industry.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Machinist* is a comprehensive technical magazine serving the metalworking industry, particularly in the United States. The magazine was first published in May 1877 by John A. Hill and Henry Haven Windsor, making it one of the oldest American magazines still in publication. The headquarters of *American Machinist* is located in New York City.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Published by Informa Markets, the magazine is headed by Editor-in-Chief Bruce Vernyi. *American Machinist* has a robust circulation, reaching approximately 100,000 readers per issue. The magazine is a monthly publication, and in addition to its print offerings, it publishes a daily newsletter and maintains an active website.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Machinist* is more than a magazine—it is a multi-platform media brand. Beyond its print and digital editions, the brand extends to other platforms, including social media, webinars, and sponsored content. The magazine''s content is deeply focused on the metalworking industry, with a focus on operational efficiency, productivity, metalworking, and materials science. Its goal is to provide its audience with insights, analysis, and editorial opinions on the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each year, *American Machinist* hosts the End User Event, a major industry conference. This event is a testament to the magazine''s influence and prestige in the metalworking industry. Despite extensive research, there is limited information available on the specific historical milestones and significant developments of the magazine since its inception.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Please note that this description is based on the information available as of my last training cut-off in September 2021 and subsequent online research. For the most current details, please refer to the latest sources.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The American Magazine and Historical Chronicle
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The American Magazine and Historical Chronicle', N'the-american-magazine-and-historical-chronicle', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription One of the earliest American magazines (1743-1746) furnishing historical chronicles and contributions by prominent figures of the era.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# *The American Magazine and Historical Chronicle*' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The American Magazine and Historical Chronicle* was a periodical published in Boston, Massachusetts from 1743 to 1746. This important early periodical was printed by Rogers & Fowle, who were Gamaliel Rogers and Daniel Fowle. Its publishers were Samuel Eliot and Joshua Blanchard. It is suggested by scholars that Jeremiah Gridley served as the editor of the periodical.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Modeled after London magazines of the time, *The American Magazine and Historical Chronicle* primarily contained content relating to English and American politics and war. Its themes ranged from the politics and government of Great Britain from 1727 to 1760, the history of the United States during the colonial period, and the affairs of Great Britain’s American colonies. The magazine was made available in various cities across the American colonies, including Philadelphia and New York, which were key intellectual centers of the time. All of the magazine''s issues have been digitized and are available in the Phillips Library at The Peabody Essex Museum.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The American Magazine of Useful and Entertaining Knowledge
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The American Magazine of Useful and Entertaining Knowledge', N'the-american-magazine-of-useful-and-entertaining-knowledge', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription 19th-century periodical (1834-1837) offering a blend of practical information and general curiosity, in pursuit of public enlightenment.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The American Magazine of Useful and Entertaining Knowledge* was a monthly periodical that circulated in Boston, Massachusetts, from 1834 to 1837. It was initiated by a group of engravers with the intention of delivering to the public a work that was descriptive, encompassing not only subjects, scenes, places, and persons existing in distant climes, but also those found in their own fine and native country. The magazine featured a profusion of illustrated articles on a wide range of topics such as American animals, plants, natural scenery, colleges, banks, hospitals, churches, cities, and technology, among other subjects. It also carried biographical articles on significant individuals from the revolutionary and federal eras. Its format was inspired by the British *Penny Magazine*. Initially, its publication was handled by the Boston Bewick Company, but later, the responsibility was taken over by William D. Ticknor and John L. Sibley. In 1836, the esteemed writer Nathaniel Hawthorne served as the magazine''s editor.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Metal Market
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Metal Market', N'american-metal-market', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Trade publication providing news, pricing and analysis on metals and metal-related industries, active since 1882.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# `American Metal Market`' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Metal Market* is a renowned online provider of industry news and metal pricing information for the U.S. steel, nonferrous, and scrap markets. It was first published in 1882 as a weekly news and price paper, and it holds the distinction of being the longest continuously published newspaper in the industry. It transitioned from a traditional hard-copy newspaper to a strictly electronic format in April 2002, and it continues to thrive in this form today. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication is valued for its impartial coverage of the mining and manufacturing sectors. It has been described as being "as vital to the metal-buyer as the ticker is to Wall Street". This recognition stems from its ability to provide critical insights and up-to-date information that helps its readers navigate the intricacies of the metal markets. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its daily electronic publication, *American Metal Market* offers live news on its website, a series of weekly newsletters covering niche markets, and it hosts numerous industry conferences and events each year that delve into the state of various metal markets. The breadth and depth of its content have made it an indispensable resource for professionals involved in the U.S. steel, nonferrous, and scrap markets. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Metal Market* is a subsidiary of Astorg, a private equity company, and it is a sister publication to London-based *Metal Bulletin*. Both *American Metal Market* and *Metal Bulletin* were part of a Euromoney subsidiary known as Fastmarkets. After Euromoney was sold to a pair of private equity companies in July 2022, Fastmarkets was placed under the management of Astorg. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, *American Metal Market* has seen several changes. It absorbed *Metalworking News* in 1972, after which the Monday issue was called *American Metal Market. Metalworking News Edition* from 1972 to 1984, and *AMM* from 1984 to 1986. In 1987, *Metalworking News* again became a separate publication with its own numbering. *American Metal Market* eventually merged with *Metal Bulletin Magazine* to form *Metal Market Magazine*. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication covers a wide range of topics related to the metal trade, iron industry and trade, and steel industry and trade in the United States. It''s a trusted cross-commodity price reporting agency in the agriculture, forest products, metals and mining, and new generation energy markets. By offering its customers insights for trading and planning, *American Metal Market* plays a significant role in shaping the metal markets of today and tomorrow.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- All Hands Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'All Hands Magazine', N'all-hands-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Official magazine of the U.S. Navy from 1922-2017, providing sailors with news, information about naval life, and historical features.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# All Hands Magazine' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*All Hands* is the official online magazine of the United States Navy. Established in August 1922, the publication served as a significant resource for sailors, providing pertinent information and news impacting more than 300,000+ Sailors and their families. Originally published under various titles, the magazine adopted its current name in 1945. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is a public document, available to all, and it receives over 33 million page views annually. *All Hands* was initially a free-of-charge, monthly print publication. Its last printed issue was published in December 2011, although it continues to be published online. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Formerly published by the Naval Media Center in Washington, D.C., the publication operations moved to the Defense Media Activity’s Production Directorate’s Navy Production Division in Fort George G. Meade, Maryland, in August 2011, shortly before the cessation of its print edition. The magazine is produced for the Navy’s Chief of Information (CHINFO).' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In February 2013, *All Hands Magazine* resurfaced as a digital web-based publication, maintaining its role as a critical source of news and information for the Navy community. It continues to be updated daily, reflecting the evolving needs and interests of its readership.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The American Wargamer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The American Wargamer', N'the-american-wargamer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly periodical from 1973 to 1976, focused on war gaming and military simulations with editorial reviews and player strategies.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_The American Wargamer_ was a wargaming magazine first published in 1973. As a medium-sized newsletter, it was the official publication of the American Wargaming Association. The inaugural issue appeared in December 1973, marking the magazine''s establishment by founder Gene McCoy. _The American Wargamer_ continued its publication until it was renamed _Military Digest_ in 1984 with its 11th volume, 11th issue. The magazine endured under this new name until May 2000, making its lifespan a notable 27 years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publisher of this esteemed publication was McCoy Publishing Enterprises, operating out of Middleton, Wisconsin. The magazine''s reach, however, extended beyond its physical headquarters, connecting a network of enthusiastic wargamers across the nation. It was not merely a medium for relaying information; _The American Wargamer_ fostered a vibrant community of individuals united by their passion for historical wargaming.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Noted game designer Steve Jackson once reviewed _The American Wargamer_ in _The Space Gamer_ No. 32. In his review, Jackson characterized the magazine as catering to the "serious historical wargame fan—the person who plays a lot of wargames of different periods, likes to talk about them, likes to write about them, likes to read about them, likes to argue about them." He further suggested that for ''club'' wargamers—those part of a group or community of gamers—it could be worthwhile to join the American Wargaming Association to receive _The American Wargamer_. Jackson indicated, however, that those exclusively interested in science fiction, fantasy, or role-playing games might not find as much content of interest in the magazine【9†source】. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With its specialized focus on historical wargaming, _The American Wargamer_ carved a niche for itself in the broader landscape of gaming publications. It stood as a testament to the diverse interests within the gaming community, demonstrating that even within a common hobby, there are distinct subcultures and preferences. The magazine''s long tenure and the community it fostered speak to the enduring appeal and depth of historical wargaming.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- American Way
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'American Way', N'american-way', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription In-flight publication for American Airlines featuring travel, lifestyle, entertainment, tech and business articles.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*American Way* was a free, inflight magazine available across the entire American Airlines fleet and Admirals Clubs premium lounges. The magazine was first published in 1966, launching originally as *The American Way*. It was published on a monthly basis and reached over 16 million passengers every month. Since its inception, the inflight magazine has been a ubiquitous presence on American Airlines aircraft, offering thoughtful perspectives and cultural, lifestyle or travel-related feature articles. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2014, American Airlines appointed Ink as the new publisher of *American Way*. Ink''s first issue launched in January 2015 with a double cover edition featuring rock star David Grohl and the band Foo Fighters. The issue touted a fresh design and an editorial mix of international celebrities, world-class destinations, and extraordinary stories. This signaled a shift in the magazine''s focus, offering content that was as diverse and global as the airline''s passenger base.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, all good things must come to an end. In June 2021, *American Way* ceased publication. This decision was bittersweet, as the magazine had been a staple of American Airlines'' inflight entertainment for more than half a century. The last issue of *American Way*, published by Ink, continued to serve customers until its final days.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the magazine''s retirement, American Airlines remained committed to enhancing its inflight offerings. Passengers could look forward to a library of up to 600 movies and TV shows, a collection of more than 150 creative, productivity or language classes on American’s new Lifestyle inflight entertainment channel featuring Rosetta Stone and Skillshare content. They could also enjoy a wide range of kids’ content, live music and concert performances from top venues such as Austin City Limits, and meditation and relaxation exercises from Calm.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, American Airlines planned to introduce new inflight offerings designed to inspire wanderlust and provide even more ways to connect with family and friends while flying at 35,000 feet. Customers could stream on their phone, tablet or laptop by enabling airplane mode and connecting to the “AA-Inflight” signal. In addition to providing customers with more of what they want, this change also aimed to eliminate some paper waste and reduce weight on the aircraft, furthering the airline’s commitment to sustainability.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The American Weekly
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The American Weekly', N'the-american-weekly', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Weekly newspaper supplement from 1896 to 1966 with nationwide distribution, known for its cover art and wide-ranging content.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The American Weekly* was a Sunday newspaper supplement distributed by the Hearst Corporation, first published on November 1, 1896, and enjoyed a prosperous run until 1966. It originated during the 1890s as part of an insert within the *New York World* and the *New York Journal*, owned by Joseph Pulitzer and William Randolph Hearst respectively. The eight-page *Women''s Home Journal* and the 16-page *Sunday American Magazine* later evolved into *The American Weekly*. Notably, it was intended to have an extended shelf-life compared to the newspapers in which it was inserted, maintaining its appeal for days or even weeks after publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine boasted a readership of over 50,000,000, and was composed of a captivating mix of images and text, often showcasing scantily clad showgirls and thrilling tales of murder and suspense. The large format of the magazine, measuring approximately 21" x 15", and the fragile newsprint on which it was printed means that very few original copies have survived the passage of time. The magazine did, however, feature top-tier illustrations and cover art by notable artists such as Howard Chandler Christy, James Montgomery Flagg, Nell Brinkley, A. K. Macdonald, C. D. Mitchell, Léon Bakst, Erté, and Norman Rockwell, among others. A substantial portion of the interior art was the work of Lee Conrey, who was likely a significant influence on both Virgil Finlay and Alex Raymond. The magazine also featured occasional work by other artists such as John R. Flanagan, Orson Lowell, and Otto Soglow. The advertisements within the magazine were often spectacular and visually stunning, attracting the interest of many readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1963, the name of the magazine was changed to *Pictorial Living*, before it was ultimately discontinued in 1966. The poor quality of the paper on which it was printed has resulted in many issues being lost, despite the magazine''s substantial circulation. This has led to it becoming a sought-after collector''s item for enthusiasts in the present day.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- AmericanStyle Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'AmericanStyle Magazine', N'americanstyle-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Quarterly magazine focused on contemporary craft collectors, covering art glass, clay, fiber, metal, and wood creations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# AmericanStyle' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*AmericanStyle* was a quarterly cultural tourism magazine published by the Rosen Group from 1994 till 2012, with 82 issues released over the 28-year period. The magazine was conceived by Wendy Rosen, the founder of the Rosen Group, and was operated from the company''s office in the historic Mill Centre in Baltimore, Maryland.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*AmericanStyle* distinguished itself as the first cultural tourism magazine in America. It offered readers a wealth of cultural travel information and feature stories on collecting contemporary fine arts and crafts. In addition, it provided insights into the creators of these works and trends in art collection.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *AmericanStyle* was a treasure trove of tips and advice on art collection, home decoration, interior design, and display concepts. It featured designer jewelry and fashion, art glass, teapots, art furniture, and functional and sculptural ceramics. Moreover, it showcased portfolios of craftspeople and artists from various cities across America.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine underscored the cultural and economic importance of handmade objects and the significance of contributions made by craftspeople and artists to local neighborhoods and urban revitalization efforts. The readership enjoyed updates on over 200 gallery exhibitions, art festivals, and museum events in their datebook section. Also, it included exclusive features on artists’ lifestyles, homes of art collectors, and local art tours in different cities to promote their touristic potential.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*AmericanStyle* was noted for its annual “Top 25 Arts Destinations” edition. Cities held local and online competitions for inclusion in this coveted list, the results of which were based on readers'' polling. In 2012, the magazine''s quarterly publication had a circulation of about 65,000 copies.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The recognition from *AmericanStyle* was highly sought after by the selected destinations. They acknowledged and promoted these inclusions in their tourism''s promotional marketing material and campaigns.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Following the growth recession from 2007 to 2009 in America, *AmericanStyle* faced difficulties in generating and maintaining advertising revenue from art galleries struggling in the wake of the recession. As a result, the magazine closed after its 2012''s Fall Arts Preview edition.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The legacy of *AmericanStyle* magazine extends beyond its print life. The articles and features from the magazine have been used as citations in journals, such as *Sociation Today*, and books including *Outside the Center/On the Edge* by Lisa Austrin, published in 2005 by Bucknell University, and *The Guild Sourcebook of Architectural and Interior Art*, published in 2007. The magazine has also been referred to in books about local cultures and cities, including the 2010-2011 *Arlington/Fairfax Counties Real Estate Guide*, *Northport*, *American Advance: Westward from the French and Indian War*, and *Sustainable Communities: Creating a Durable Local Economy*.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Amerika Esperantisto
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Amerika Esperantisto', N'the-amerika-esperantisto', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Bimonthly periodical published by the Esperanto League for North America, focused on Esperanto language and culture.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Amerika Esperantisto* (American Esperantist), also known as *Amerika Esperantista Revuo*, was a North American Esperanto-language monthly publication. It was founded in January 1907 by the American Esperanto Association (Amerika Esperantista Asocio), a national association formed by Boston Esperantists in March 1905. The magazine was initially published in Oklahoma City by Arthur Baker of the American Esperantist Company, a specialized publisher and vendor of Esperanto material that was dedicated to the promotion of the Esperanto language.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1907, the headquarters of *Amerika Esperantisto* moved to New York City. Following its first national convention in Chautauqua, New York in 1908, the Amerika Esperantista Asocio was renamed Esperantista Asocio de Norda Ameriko (EANA). The publication of *Amerika Esperantista Revuo* ceased and *Amerika Esperantisto* became the official organ of EANA.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s editors included Arthur Baker, Ivy Kellerman, and J. J. Süssmuth. It was committed to the promotion and proliferation of the Esperanto language, and it offered a variety of articles and features that catered to both Esperanto speakers and those interested in the language.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the notable articles in *Amerika Esperantisto* concerned the use of Esperanto in the U.S. Army''s “Aggressor Force.” The article showcased how the language was being used in military exercises to enhance intelligence play and add realism to field exercises. This led to a surge in interest among soldiers who wrote to EANA for information about Esperanto, intrigued by the language''s utility in travel and global friendships.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'This engagement with the military was further highlighted when a major television network featured a movie that used Esperanto during sequences showing the interrogation of prisoners by the “Aggressor Force.” In addition, the magazine contained valuable resources such as an elementary grammar of the Esperanto language, an English-Esperanto and Esperanto-English vocabulary, and special tables on days and months, numerals, weights and measures, and approximate conversions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Amerika Esperantisto* continued its publication until the rise of the Esperanto League for North America, which led to the decline of EANA and the eventual cessation of the magazine''s publication in 1963. Despite its closure, *Amerika Esperantisto* remains a significant historical document for those interested in the evolution and promotion of the Esperanto language in North America.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 3-2-1 Contact
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'3-2-1 Contact', N'3-2-1-contact', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Parallel to a famed television series, this publication explored science in everyday life, games, and puzzles from 1983 to 1985, with a brief return in 1989.}}The 3-2-1 Contact magazine was a publication that paralleled the television series. It featured content related to the scientific and educational themes of the show, including write-ups on the science of everyday life, games, and puzzles. The magazine also included a serialized mystery series that followed a group of young detectives, known as the Bloodhound Gang, who used science to solve mysteries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of the timeline, the magazine ran from 1983 to 1985, with a brief return in syndication in 1989. This coincided with the show’s original run, which spanned from 1980 to 1988.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- ANALOG Computing
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'ANALOG Computing', N'analog-computing', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Dedicated to Atari 8-bit computers, this 1980s and 1990s periodical offered programming advice, hardware reviews, and hands-on coding exercises. Its significant impact on the understanding and use of these computers continues to resonate today.}}*ANALOG Computing* magazine was a prominent periodical in the field of computer technology, particularly during the 1980s and 1990s. The magazine stood out as a comprehensive resource for those interested in the Atari 8-bit family of home computers, focusing not only on programming but also on general usage, hardware, and software reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### History ###' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded in 1981 by Lee Pappas and John Ziegler, Analog Computing Magazine quickly positioned itself as a trusted voice in the rapidly growing field of personal computing. The magazine was first based in Worcester, Massachusetts, before moving to its later base in Chelmsford.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The name "Analog" was a nod to the analog synthesis capabilities of Atari 8-bit computers, showcasing the magazine’s dedication to this computer series. Analog Computing initially published six issues per year, but due to its success and the booming interest in Atari computers, it increased its frequency to monthly publication in the mid-1980s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Content and Features ###' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Analog Computing was known for its broad range of content, which appealed to a variety of readers, from hobbyists and novice users to advanced programmers and computer science professionals. It offered in-depth software and hardware reviews, how-to guides, game walkthroughs, interviews with industry figures, and, most importantly, programming advice and tutorials.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine’s iconic features was its type-in programs, which allowed readers to manually input computer programs into their Atari systems. This was a common practice in the 1980s before software distribution became widespread, and it gave many young computer users their first taste of programming.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another standout feature of the magazine was its dedication to quality writing and comprehensive reviews. The contributors to Analog Computing were deeply involved in the computing scene, and their insight and expertise showed in their articles. This commitment to quality and insightfulness set the magazine apart from its competitors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Influence and Legacy ###' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Analog Computing had a significant impact on the popular understanding and use of the Atari 8-bit family of computers. The magazine played an instrumental role in educating its readers about programming and the potential of personal computers, inspiring many to delve deeper into the world of computing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine ceased publication in 1989, a casualty of the declining market for Atari 8-bit computers as the industry moved toward 16-bit systems like the Commodore Amiga and Atari ST. However, its legacy lives on. Many programmers and computer enthusiasts cite Analog Computing as a significant influence on their careers and personal interests.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its ultimate demise, the magazine’s contributions to the Atari 8-bit community and the broader field of personal computing are still acknowledged and respected today. It remains a notable part of computer history, representing an era of innovation, discovery, and excitement about the possibilities of home computing.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 7ball
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'7ball', N'7ball', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Influential in the Christian music scene from the mid-1990s to early 2000s, this American bimonthly publication was known for its diverse coverage and inclusion of sampler CDs in each issue.}}**7ball Magazine** was an American bimonthly magazine that made significant contributions to the Christian music scene from the mid-1990s through the early 2000s. Known for its diverse coverage of both mainstream and independent Christian music, 7ball broadened the dialogue about faith-based music within the larger cultural conversation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established in 1995, 7ball Magazine was the brainchild of Chris Well, a seasoned journalist with a passion for Christian music. The magazine was originally published by VoxCorp, based in Nashville, Tennessee, a city known for its thriving music scene. In 1999, the publication was acquired by the Cornerstone Publishing Group, which continued to produce the magazine until its final issue in 2004.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'7ball was known for its comprehensive music reviews, feature articles, artist interviews, and coverage of Christian music events. The magazine was not confined to one musical genre but instead embraced the diversity within the Christian music scene. It covered a broad range of genres, from rock, pop, and hip hop to worship, gospel, and contemporary Christian music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine’s distinguishing features was the inclusion of a sampler CD in each issue. These CDs featured tracks from the artists profiled in the magazine, providing readers with a tangible extension of the publication’s content. This innovative approach served as a powerful promotional tool for both established artists and emerging talent within the Christian music scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another notable aspect of 7ball was its commitment to high-quality, professional journalism. The magazine’s writers and contributors were experienced professionals who approached their work with a discerning eye for detail, accuracy, and relevance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'7ball Magazine played an instrumental role in bringing attention to the Christian music scene, fostering a broader appreciation for faith-based music and the artists who create it. During its run, the magazine profiled many influential artists and bands, including Jars of Clay, DC Talk, and Switchfoot, among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although 7ball ceased publication in 2004, its influence on the Christian music industry can still be felt today. Its commitment to quality journalism, diverse content, and promotion of emerging talent set a standard for other publications in the field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Many former readers and contributors recall 7ball as a significant influence in shaping their musical tastes and understanding of Christian music. Despite the magazine’s eventual discontinuation, its contributions to the Christian music industry are still acknowledged and respected today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 7x7
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'7x7', N'7x7', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A critical influencer of San Francisco''s cultural landscape since 2001, this publication covers diverse aspects of lifestyle and features local businesses. Transitioned to digital in 2014, it continues to thrive.}}*7x7 Magazine* is a prominent lifestyle and culture publication based in San Francisco, California. The publication has held a critical role in chronicling and influencing the Bay Area''s cultural landscape since its inception in 2001. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*7x7* was established in 2001 by Tom Hartle and Heather Hartle, with the aim of catering to San Francisco’s vibrant and diverse cultural scene. The magazine’s title is a reference to the approximate land area of San Francisco, which is roughly seven by seven miles. Initially, the magazine was printed in a monthly format. However, in 2014, *7x7* transitioned to a digital-first platform, focusing primarily on their online content while continuing to produce special print editions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*7x7 Magazine* offers a broad range of content focusing on various aspects of San Francisco lifestyle and culture. The publication covers topics such as food and drink, arts and culture, style and design, health and wellness, and travel. Additionally, *7x7* also publishes feature articles on the city''s most notable individuals and spotlights unique local businesses and startups.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine''s standout features is its “Best of the Bay Area” issue. This annual edition is a comprehensive guide to the finest offerings in the region, spanning categories such as dining, shopping, entertainment, and outdoor activities. It''s regarded as an essential resource for both locals and visitors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another notable feature of *7x7* is its in-depth and engaging long-form features. These articles often delve into significant cultural, social, or historical aspects of the Bay Area, presenting readers with a comprehensive understanding of the region''s dynamic nature.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*7x7 Magazine* has played a crucial role in San Francisco''s cultural scene. Through its insightful coverage of local events, trends, and personalities, *7x7* has helped to shape the discourse around what defines the city and its inhabitants.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the shift from print to digital, the magazine continues to thrive, maintaining its relevance in a city known for its technological innovation. The move to digital has allowed *7x7* to reach an even broader audience, further solidifying its place as an integral part of San Francisco''s cultural landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In summary, *7x7 Magazine* serves as a rich source of information and inspiration for its readers, and its contributions to the preservation and promotion of San Francisco''s cultural heritage continue to be highly valued.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 032c
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'032c', N'032c', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription First published in 2001, this Berlin-based magazine covers contemporary culture, art, fashion, and politics. Known for its critical journalism and avant-garde design.}}*032c* is a Berlin-based, English-language biannual contemporary culture magazine that was first published in 2001. The publication was created by Joerg Koch, who continues to serve as its editor-in-chief. It is named after the Pantone designation for the color red, referencing the vibrant energy and creativity associated with the city of Berlin.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its early years, *032c* was primarily focused on contemporary art, fashion, and politics. Over time, the magazine expanded its scope to become a platform for critical journalism and innovative visual culture, encompassing a broad range of topics from pop culture and fashion to architectural design and global politics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*032c* is noted for its in-depth and meticulously researched articles, coupled with provocative and avant-garde visual design. The magazine presents a unique blend of high-end fashion editorials, comprehensive profiles of artists and designers, thought-provoking think pieces, and immersive reportage.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *032c* features a thematic focus, but the magazine doesn''t limit itself to its chosen theme, rather, it uses the theme as a starting point from which to explore the myriad ways in which contemporary culture is intertwined and coalescing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also distinguishes itself with its commitment to exploring the intersection of different fields and disciplines, such as the cross-pollination between art, fashion, design, and technology. This holistic approach sets *032c* apart from its contemporaries and contributes to its unique identity in the magazine landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the world of contemporary culture magazines, *032c* has carved out a significant niche for itself. It''s recognized for its intellectual rigor and its willingness to push the boundaries of traditional magazine journalism, both in its content and its visual presentation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the magazine maintains a firm foothold in its Berlin home base, its influence extends far beyond. Its comprehensive approach to covering global contemporary culture has made it a critical resource for readers interested in understanding the intricacies of today''s world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s influence is also apparent in its contribution to critical dialogue and creative expression in contemporary culture. Many notable figures in the realms of art, design, fashion, and beyond have been featured in *032c*, with the magazine often serving as a platform for emerging voices in these fields.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*032c*''s innovative and broad-ranging approach to contemporary culture continues to shape its identity as a publication that not only reflects the world around it but also actively participates in shaping that world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Acne Paper
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Acne Paper', N'acne-paper', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A Swedish fashion brand''s biannual culture magazine (2005-2014) focused on thematic deep-dives rather than trends. Known for its artistic and intellectually engaging content.}}Founded in 2005, *Acne Paper* is a biannual culture magazine and the brainchild of the Swedish fashion brand Acne Studios. The magazine was conceived by Acne''s Creative Director Jonny Johansson and Thomas Persson, the editor-in-chief and art director of the publication. *Acne Paper* focused on themes, rather than specific topics or trends, aiming to delve deep into a single concept with each issue, until its final issue in 2014.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'From its inception, *Acne Paper* distinguished itself from other fashion magazines by concentrating less on the seasonal nature of fashion, but more on the exploration of broader themes such as tradition, eroticism, education, and decadence, to name a few. The result was a publication that was both highly artistic and intellectually engaging.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *Acne Paper* was curated around a central theme, which was investigated through a variety of lenses, including interviews, essays, photography, and artistic contributions. This thematic approach allowed the magazine to transcend the typical constraints of fashion publications and delve into a rich dialogue spanning history, culture, and society.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, *Acne Paper* was celebrated for its aesthetic presentation. It utilized an impressive format, with high-quality paper and printing techniques. The magazine''s striking design and attention to detail earned it a reputation as not only a publication but also a collector''s item.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Acne Paper* has had a significant impact on the landscape of fashion and culture publications. Its thematic approach set it apart from its contemporaries and contributed to an ongoing dialogue about the interplay between fashion, culture, and society. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Its influence also extended to the artistic community, as it often featured collaborations with acclaimed photographers, artists, and thinkers. Notably, it was recognized for spotlighting both established and emerging talents, thus providing a platform for creative expression across various fields.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though *Acne Paper* ceased publication in 2014, its legacy continues to resonate. Its unique editorial approach and artistic presentation have left an enduring imprint on the field of fashion journalism. Its archival issues remain relevant, offering timeless explorations of their respective themes.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The New York Times Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The New York Times Magazine', N'the-new-york-times-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Launched in 1896, this Sunday newspaper supplement features in-depth analysis, profiles, essays, and critiques across various domains. Known for its iconic Crossword and "The Ethicist" column.}}*The New York Times Magazine* is a supplemental publication included with the Sunday edition of *The New York Times*. Launched in 1896, it''s one of the oldest magazine supplements for a newspaper in the United States. Its founding aim was to present in-depth and thoughtful explorations of current events, trends, and societal issues that went beyond the daily news coverage provided by *The New York Times*. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The New York Times Magazine* features a wide range of content, including long-form reportage, profiles, essays, and critiques. Topics covered span the spectrum of human interest, from politics, science, and technology to art, literature, and popular culture. The magazine’s commitment to thorough reporting, elegant prose, and nuanced analysis has distinguished it as a staple of Sunday morning reading for many.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A hallmark of *The New York Times Magazine* is its “The Lives They Lived” issue, released annually at year’s end. This issue remembers notable figures who have passed away during the year, celebrating their lives and contributions through evocative writing and photography. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The New York Times Magazine* also notably hosts the "The New York Times Puzzles & Games" section, which includes the iconic *New York Times* Crossword, a cultural fixture since its introduction in 1942. The section, under the editorship of Will Shortz since 1993, has expanded to include a variety of other puzzles, such as KenKen and Spelling Bee.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another significant feature is "The Ethicist," a weekly column where readers submit ethical dilemmas to be dissected and addressed. This feature, currently authored by Kwame Anthony Appiah, encourages readers to engage with the moral complexities of modern life.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The New York Times Magazine* has had a significant impact on journalism and storytelling. Its feature articles have often sparked discussion and drawn attention to pressing societal issues. Furthermore, its dedication to the craft of long-form journalism has provided a platform for many award-winning pieces.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine has been a podium for numerous esteemed writers and journalists, including Elizabeth Kolbert, Taffy Brodesser-Akner, Nikole Hannah-Jones, and Ronen Bergman, among others. Notably, the 1619 Project, a landmark initiative examining the impact of slavery on American society, was first published in *The New York Times Magazine* under the leadership of Hannah-Jones.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s commitment to deep-dive reporting, innovative storytelling, and thought-provoking commentary continues to influence the landscape of contemporary journalism. Its dedication to these principles ensures that *The New York Times Magazine* remains a revered publication in the constantly evolving world of media.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- FRUiTS
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'FRUiTS', N'fruits', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Founded in Tokyo in 1997, this street fashion magazine popularized Harajuku''s eclectic style. Its legacy endures, despite ending publication in 2017.}}*FRUiTS* was a renowned Tokyo-based street fashion magazine that captured and popularized the eclectic and vibrant street style of Harajuku, a district in Tokyo known for its fashion subcultures. The magazine was founded in 1997 by photographer Shoichi Aoki, who had previously established the avant-garde fashion magazine *STREET*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Aoki was inspired to create *FRUiTS* after noticing the inventive, do-it-yourself spirit of young people in the Harajuku district. The magazine quickly became a cultural touchstone, with its monthly issues featuring candid street-style photographs of the eccentric and original outfits worn by individuals around Harajuku.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS* was characterized by its distinctive snapshot aesthetic. Each issue was filled with photographs of individuals in their unique outfits, often accompanied by a brief description of the person’s clothing and accessories. The magazine did not feature articles or editorials; instead, it relied on the power of its images to tell a story about the dynamism and creativity of Harajuku’s fashion culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication celebrated individuality and self-expression, as showcased by the people featured in its pages. Many of these individuals were not professional models but ordinary people with extraordinary style, reflecting the magazine’s ethos of street fashion as an accessible and personal form of expression.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s focus on Harajuku''s street style had a significant influence on international fashion trends. It brought global attention to various Japanese fashion movements, including “Decora,” a style characterized by layered clothing and accessories, and “Lolita,” a fashion subculture inspired by Victorian and Rococo clothing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS* gained an international following and had a significant impact on global fashion trends. The magazine has been credited with introducing and popularizing Harajuku street style to a global audience, influencing designers and fashion enthusiasts around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After twenty years of documenting Harajuku''s ever-changing street fashion scene, *FRUiTS* published its final issue in February 2017. Aoki cited a “lack of fashionable kids” to photograph as the reason for the magazine’s closure. He noted that, in his view, street fashion had become more homogenized and less innovative in recent years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though the magazine is no longer in publication, its legacy endures. *FRUiTS* remains a symbol of Harajuku’s unique fashion subcultures and a testament to the district’s influence on global fashion. The magazine’s archives offer a colorful and diverse record of two decades of Tokyo street fashion, making *FRUiTS* an important part of the history of fashion documentation.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'FRUiTS', N'fruits', 1, 'ar' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'كانت مجلة *FRUiTS* مجلة مرموقة لأزياء الشارع مقرها طوكيو، التي تدعم وتروج للأسلوب المتنوع والمرح في الأزياء الشارعية في حي هاراجوكو في طوكيو، المعروف بثقافات الأزياء الفرعية الخاصة به. تأسست المجلة في عام 1997 على يدي المصور شويتشي أوكي، الذي أسس سابقا مجلة *STREET* التي تركز على أزياء الأفانت غارد.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'استوحى أوكي فكرة إنشاء *FRUiTS* بعد أن لاحظ روح الابتكار والحرفية الذاتية لدى الشباب في حي هاراجوكو. سرعان ما أصبحت المجلة مرجعًا ثقافيًا، حيث كانت تقدم في كل عدد شهري صورًا للأزياء الشارعية الملفتة والأصلية التي يرتديها الأفراد في حي هاراجوكو.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## المحتوى والميزات' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'كانت مجلة *FRUiTS* تتميز بجمالياتها الفوتوغرافية المميزة. كانت كل طبعة تحتوي على صور للأفراد في ملابسهم الفريدة، وغالبا ما يكون مرفقًا بها وصفًا موجزًا لملابس الشخص وإكسسواراته. لم تقدم المجلة مقالات أو موضوعات تحريرية؛ بل اعتمدت على قوة صورها لسرد قصة حول الحيوية والإبداع في ثقافة الأزياء في هاراجوكو.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'كانت المجلة تحتفي بالفردية والتعبير عن الذات، كما يتضح من الأشخاص الذين ظهروا في صفحاتها. كان العديد من هؤلاء الأفراد ليسوا عارضين محترفين وإنما أشخاصًا عاديين يتميزون بأسلوب استثنائي، مما يعكس فلسفة المجلة في أن أزياء الشارع هي شك.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## التأثير والإرث' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'حققت مجلة *FRUiTS* شهرة دولية وكان لها تأثير كبير على الاتجاهات العالمية في الأزياء. وقد نُسب إلى المجلة الفضل في تقديم وتعزيز أسلوب أزياء شارع هاراجوكو للجمهور العالمي، مما أثر في مصممي الأزياء وعشاق الأزياء في جميع أنحاء العالم.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'بعد عشرين عامًا من توثيق مشهد أزياء الشارع المتغير باستمرار في هاراجوكو، نشرت مجلة *FRUiTS* عددها الأخير في فبراير 2017. وأرجع أوكي السبب وراء إغلاق المجلة إلى "عدم وجود أطفال أنيقين" لتصويرهم، ولاحظ أن أزياء الشارع أصبحت في رأيه أكثر توحيدًا وأقل ابتكارًا في السنوات الأخيرة.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'بالرغم من أن المجلة لم تعد قيد النشر، لا يزال إرثها قائمًا. تظل مجلة *FRUiTS* رمزًا لثقافات الأزياء الفرعية الفريدة في هاراجوكو وشهادة على تأثير الحي على الأزياء العالمية. توفر أرشيفات المجلة سجلاً ملونًا ومتنوعًا لعقدين من أزياء الشارع في طوكيو، مما يجعل مجلة *FRUiTS* جزءًا مهمًا من تاريخ توثيق الأزياء.', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'FRUiTS', N'fruits', 1, 'ja' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'*FRUiTS*は、東京を拠点とするストリートファッション雑誌で、ファッションのサブカルチャーで知られる東京の原宿地区の個性的で活気あるストリートスタイルを捉え、普及させました。この雑誌は、前衛的なファッション雑誌*STREET*を創設した写真家、青木正一によって1997年に創設されました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'青木は、原宿地区の若者たちの創造的でDIYの精神に触発されて*FRUiTS*を創設しました。その月刊誌は、原宿周辺の個々の人々が着ている奇抜でオリジナルな服装のキャンディッドなストリートスタイルの写真を特集し、すぐに文化的な象徴となりました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## 内容と特徴' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS*は、その特徴的なスナップショットの美学で特徴付けられました。各号は、個々の人々のユニークな服装の写真で満たされ、しばしばその人の服装やアクセサリーの簡単な説明が添えられていました。雑誌は記事やエディトリアルを特集せず、代わりにそのイメージの力を使って、原宿のファッション文化のダイナミズムと創造性についての物語を語りました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'その出版物は、そのページに掲載された人々を通じて、個性と自己表現を祝福しました。これらの人々の多くはプロのモデルではなく、非凡なスタイルを持つ一般の人々であり、それはストリートファッションがアクセシブルでパーソナルな表現形式であるという雑誌の哲学を反映していました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'雑誌の原宿のストリートスタイルに焦点を当てることは、国際的なファッションのトレンドに大きな影響を与えました。それは、衣服とアクセサリーの層状という特徴を持つ"デコラ"スタイルや、ヴィクトリア朝やロココの衣服に触発されたファッションのサブカルチャーである"ロリータ"など、様々な日本のファッションムーブメントに世界的な注目を集めました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## 影響と遺産' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS*は国際的なフォロワーを獲得し、世界的なファッショントレンドに大きな影響を与えました。その雑誌は、原宿のストリートスタイルを世界的な観客に紹介し、普及させ、デザイナーやファッション愛好家達に影響を与えたことで称賛されました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'原宿の絶え間ないストリートファッションシーンを20年間にわたってドキュメンテーションした後、*FRUiTS*は2017年2月に最後の号を発行しました。青木は、写真を撮るための"おしゃれな子供たち"が不足しているという理由で雑誌の終了を引き受けました。彼は、彼の見解では、ストリートファッションが近年、より均一化し、革新性が少なくなったと述べました。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'雑誌がもう出版されていなくても、その遺産は続いています。*FRUiTS*は、原宿のユニークなファッションサブカルチャーの象徴であり、地区の世界的なファッションへの影響の証として残っています。その雑誌のアーカイブは、東京のストリートファッションの2つの十年にわたるカラフルで多様な記録を提供し、*FRUiTS*をファッションのドキュメンテーションの歴史の重要な部分にします。', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'FRUiTS', N'fruits', 1, 'xx-test' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'*FRUiTS* 杂志是一本日本街头时尚杂志，由摄影师田崎敬一（Aoki Shoichi）于1997年创立，其工作室位于东京涉谷区。该杂志专注于记录和展示日本街头时尚，特别是那些受到哈拉杰库文化影响的人。2017年，田崎宣布该杂志将不再出版，原因是在他看来，哈拉杰库的街头时尚已不再具有独特性。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## 内容与特色' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS* 杂志以其对街头时尚的深度报道而闻名，尤其是那些独特且个性化的装扮。每一期都包含了大量的街拍照片，这些照片不仅展示了个人的时尚品味，也反映了日本哈拉杰库区独特的时尚潮流。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'在它的二十年出版历史中，*FRUiTS* 成功地记录了哈拉杰库的时尚演变，从最初的“娃娃风”到“哥特萝莉”，再到“装饰性少女”，每一种风格都在这个杂志的页面上找到了展现的空间。这些深入报道和真实的街头照片，使 *FRUiTS* 成为理解和欣赏日本街头时尚的重要窗口。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## 影响和遗产' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS* 杂志在全球范围内对街头时尚的影响力不容小觑。杂志通过对哈拉杰库独特风格的长期报道，将其推向了全球的视野。许多西方的设计师和时尚爱好者，都从这本杂志中获得了灵感和启发。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'虽然 *FRUiTS* 在2017年停止出版，但它在时尚界的影响仍在持续。这本杂志为时尚研究者和爱好者提供了一个宝贵的资源，帮助他们了解和研究日本街头时尚的演变和影响力。' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'总的来说，*FRUiTS* 杂志是对日本哈拉杰库街头时尚最深入、最真实的记录，它的出版历史本身就是哈拉杰库时尚演变的缩影。', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Men's Non-no
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Men''s Non-no', N'mens-non-no', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription First published in 1986 by Shueisha in response to rising interest in men''s fashion, this Japanese magazine covers diverse styles, lifestyle topics, and has significantly influenced the men''s fashion industry.}}*Men''s Non-no* is a leading men''s fashion and lifestyle magazine based in Japan. It was first published in 1986 as a counterpart to the women''s fashion magazine *Non-no*, both of which are produced by the Shueisha publishing company.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The creation of *Men''s Non-no* was influenced by the changing dynamics of men''s fashion in the 1980s, as a growing number of men began to take a keen interest in personal style. Recognizing this trend, Shueisha launched *Men''s Non-no* to cater to the burgeoning demand for men''s fashion content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Men''s Non-no* provides a comprehensive range of content focused on men''s fashion, lifestyle, and culture. It covers a diverse array of styles from high-end designer brands to streetwear labels, showcasing the latest trends and providing style advice to its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A defining feature of the magazine is its highly visual content, featuring fashion spreads and editorials that combine vibrant photography with distinctive layout designs. The magazine frequently collaborates with renowned photographers and stylists to create visually compelling content that reflects the contemporary fashion landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to fashion, *Men''s Non-no* covers topics such as grooming, health and fitness, travel, music, film, and technology, offering a well-rounded perspective on modern men''s lifestyle.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also features interviews with prominent figures from various industries, including fashion designers, musicians, actors, and athletes, providing readers with unique insights into their lives and careers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Men''s Non-no* has exerted a significant influence on the men''s fashion industry in Japan and beyond. It has been instrumental in popularizing various fashion trends, and its pages have served as a launchpad for numerous models and actors who have gone on to achieve fame in Japan and overseas.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine has consistently stayed ahead of fashion trends, and its commitment to high-quality content and innovative visual storytelling has solidified its status as a must-read publication for fashion-conscious men.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Through its thoughtful coverage of fashion and lifestyle, *Men''s Non-no* has played a crucial role in shaping the conversation around men''s style and culture, contributing to the broader cultural shift towards the acceptance and celebration of men''s interest in fashion. Its enduring popularity testifies to its ability to evolve with the times while staying true to its core mission of providing readers with the latest in men''s fashion and lifestyle.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Clutch
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Clutch', N'clutch', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'Clutch Magazine, known as クラッチマガジン in its original Japanese, is a highly esteemed publication that, since its inception, has become an integral piece in the vibrant tapestry of Japan''s fashion journalism. The magazine has earned international acclaim for its dedication to the exploration and promotion of vintage and heritage-inspired menswear, embedding itself into the psyche of fashion enthusiasts worldwide.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'First published in 2012, Clutch Magazine has been relentless in its pursuit to provide readers with in-depth features, comprehensive profiles, and meticulous inspections of brands and designers who are reinterpreting the aesthetics of the past for the contemporary dresser. With a pronounced focus on American and Japanese vintage style, the magazine offers an unparalleled perspective on the global menswear landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The richness of Clutch Magazine’s content is a testament to its commitment to sartorial storytelling. Each meticulously curated issue includes detailed interviews with designers, retrospectives on seminal works, and articles illuminating the interplay between fashion, culture, and individual expression. Through these, the magazine delves into the heart of vintage fashion, exposing the stories behind the styles that continue to shape menswear.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Offering more than mere commentary, Clutch Magazine serves as a bridge, linking the world of vintage design to the high-paced, ever-changing dynamic of modern derivative fashion. Consequently, it plays a significant role in perpetuating the dialogue between retrospection and innovation, engendering a thoughtful appreciation for past artistic endeavors while elucidating their relevance and influence in contemporary fashion trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Straddling its homeland and the international scene, Clutch Magazine unites disparate cultures, traditions, and styles under a common banner of appreciation for quality and authenticity. The publication’s recognition extends beyond Japanese borders as it amasses a growing international readership, a testament to its skillful merging of tradition and modernity, its unique perspectives, and its undeniable authority within the menswear domain.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Zigzag', N'zigzag', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Zigzag* is an esteemed surfing magazine based in South Africa. Established in 1976 by Paul Botha, a notable figure in the South African surfing scene, the magazine has been an instrumental platform for promoting surfing in South Africa and abroad. Botha''s passion for the sport, coupled with his journalistic acumen, ensured *Zigzag*''s rapid ascent as a beloved publication amongst the surfing community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is famed for its coverage of all things surfing, encompassing news, features, interviews, and stunning photography. The publication provides a platform for both established and up-and-coming surfers, showcasing their talent and stories to a wider audience. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of *Zigzag*''s distinguishing features is its stunning and vivid photography. Capturing the thrill and beauty of the sport, the magazine''s visuals transport readers to the heart of the action, whether it be a local beach break or an exotic international location. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its focus on surfing, *Zigzag* also delves into environmental issues impacting the oceans and coastlines. The magazine takes its role as a custodian of the sport seriously, fostering dialogues about environmental stewardship and sustainability within the surfing community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, *Zigzag* has earned its reputation as a leading authority in the world of surfing. The magazine has been instrumental in documenting the evolution of the sport in South Africa, from its nascent beginnings to its current status as a globally recognized and respected discipline. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the longest-running surfing magazine in Africa, *Zigzag* has played a crucial role in championing the continent''s surfing scene. It has highlighted the talents of African surfers, showcased the continent''s world-class surfing locations, and brought international attention to the region''s unique surfing culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, *Zigzag* has evolved in response to the changing needs of its readership and the surfing community. In 2012, the magazine adopted a digital-first strategy, focusing on its online platform while still producing print editions. This shift allowed *Zigzag* to reach a wider, global audience and further cemented its place as an innovative leader in surf journalism. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While *Zigzag* is deeply rooted in South African surf culture, its influence and readership extend well beyond its home shores. It continues to inspire, inform, and engage readers with its exceptional coverage of the sport, reinforcing its position as a seminal voice in global surf culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Luxury Pools', N'luxury-pools', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Luxury Pools* magazine is a premium biannual publication that has set the standard for showcasing the world''s most extraordinary swimming pools and outdoor living spaces since its inception in 1997. It was founded by RMS Media Group, a company based in Massachusetts, USA, with a vision to provide a dedicated platform to celebrate, explore, and inspire high-end pool design and outdoor living.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *Luxury Pools* presents an immersive exploration of the world''s most impressive pools and outdoor spaces. The magazine is characterized by its meticulously curated high-resolution photographs, detailed architectural plans, and engaging articles that delve into the design process, materials used, and the unique features of each project.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the focus is primarily on luxury pools, the magazine also covers all elements of upscale outdoor living spaces. This includes innovative landscaping design, custom spas, water features, outdoor kitchens, and poolside architecture. *Luxury Pools* showcases the work of world-renowned designers, architects, and landscape artists, making it a leading source of inspiration for those interested in luxury outdoor living.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine’s standout features is its in-depth designer and builder profiles. These pieces offer readers an inside look at the creative minds behind the stunning designs, providing insight into their creative processes, design philosophies, and their perspectives on upcoming trends in the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Luxury Pools* has carved out a unique niche for itself within the home design publishing industry. By focusing exclusively on high-end pool and outdoor living design, the magazine offers a unique perspective not found in general home design publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a leading authority in its field, *Luxury Pools* has had a profound impact on the outdoor living design industry. The publication has been instrumental in promoting innovative design, advanced pool technology, and superior craftsmanship. Its influence can be seen in the increasing sophistication and creativity of luxury pool design around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s ongoing success attests to its appeal among its target audience of affluent homeowners, architects, and designers. While the publication caters to a luxury market, its reach extends to anyone seeking inspiration and insight into the possibilities of pool design and outdoor living. *Luxury Pools* continues to inspire and influence the world of luxury outdoor design.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Non-no', N'non-no', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Non-no* (ノン－ノ) is a Japanese women''s fashion and lifestyle magazine published by Shueisha. The magazine''s headquarters are located in Tokyo, Japan. Established in 1971, *Non-no* was initially a fortnightly publication, with the first issue appearing in February of that year. The magazine has a longer history compared to other Japanese fashion magazines such as Cawaii!, Olive, and the like. It targets teens and young women in their early 20s. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Unlike other magazines that focus on gossip, *Non-no*, along with another women''s magazine, An An, provides its readers with materials aimed at developing their self-identity. The magazine had a circulation of 850,000 copies in 1978, which decreased to 440,870 copies by the year 2006.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to the women''s version, a male demographic targeted counterpart, *Men''s Non-no*, was launched by Shueisha on 25 May 1987.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, *Non-no* has featured numerous models. The current models as of 2023 include Yūka Suzuki (2014–present), Fumika Baba (2015–present), Nanaka Matsukawa (2017–present), Risa Watanabe (2017–present), Manami Enosawa (2018–present), Asuka Kijima (2018–present), Mirei Sasaki (2019-present), Sakura Endo (2020-present), Mayu Yokota (2020-present), Ayaka Konno (2021-present), and Kanon (2022-present).' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also features a rich history of past models. This includes names such as Airi Tanaka, Akiko Kikuchi, Anne Watanabe, Ayumi, Azusa Takehana, Emi, Etsuko Sugai, Hana, Hana Matsushima, Izumi Yamaguchi, Keiko Kurihara, Lina Ohta, Manami Teruya, Michi Ōmori, Miki, Momoko Nagano, Nishida Naomi, Noriko Amakasu, Satsuki Katayama, Shiho, Yasue Sato, Yuko Gomiyo, Sachie Futamura, Mina Sayado, Yasuko Matsuyuki (1990s), Yui Natsukawa (1990s), Ryō (1990s), Sachiko Katō (1990s), Koyuki (1990s), Kimiko Mori (1999–2001), Miho Tanaka (2000–2012), Ema Fujisawa (2001–2005), Sachiko Ogata (2002–2005), Rena Takeshita (2004–2009), Miyu Kogawa (2004–2010), Momoko Kuroki (2005–2007), Mew Azama (2006–2007), Miyu (2006–2010), Saori Watanabe (2007–2010), Emi Takahashi (2007–2011), Mikiko Yano (2008–2012), Cecil Kishimoto (2008–2015), and Yumi Yamamoto (2009–2010).' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Overall, *Non-no* represents an influential publication in Japan''s fashion and lifestyle scene, contributing not only to fashion trends but also to personal development and identity among its readers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Haya', N'haya', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}_Haya_ (هَيَا) is a weekly high-end fashion and beauty magazine with a central focus on women. Established in November 2010, the magazine is a product of the MBC Group, a leading Arab broadcaster. The reach of _Haya_ extends across the Middle East and North Africa, where it is distributed.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s target demographic comprises women between the ages of 21 and 45. Testament to its popularity, _Haya_ boasts a weekly circulation of 90,000 copies, which are disseminated across the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) and Levant regions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Haya_ is renowned for its inspirational interviews, in-depth profiles, and biographies, with a particular emphasis on Arab and international stars. The magazine is a wellspring of behind-the-scenes information on the latest hit series and programmes that have sparked widespread conversation. Through dedicated reports, _Haya_ explores current social and cultural trends, inviting readers to transcend regional boundaries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notably, _Haya_ boasts an extensive glamour section, which serves as the ultimate fashion and beauty guide for its female readers in the region. This section offers comprehensive coverage of the latest fashion trends and beauty tips, marking it as an indispensable resource for women seeking to stay au courant with the world of fashion and beauty.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki G''s Magazine', N'dengeki-gs-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Dengeki G''s Magazine* (電撃G''s magazine) is a Japanese publication renowned for its focus on the bishōjo game genre, including related media such as anime, serialized manga, and light novels. Published by ASCII Media Works, the monthly magazine was sold on the thirtieth day of each month. The magazine''s moniker, “G''s”, denotes “Gals” and “Games”. The publication is distinguished for hosting reader participation games, such as Sister Princess and Strawberry Panic!, whose outcomes are directly shaped by the readers themselves.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also introduced several special edition spin-off versions. One such version, *Dengeki G''s Festival!*, was published at irregular intervals, each issue concentrating on a specific bishōjo game. Other special editions under the *Festival!* name included *Dengeki G''s Festival! Comic*, *Dengeki G''s Festival! Deluxe*, *Dengeki G''s Festival! Anime*, and *Dengeki Festival! Heaven*. *Dengeki G''s Magazine*''s sister publication is *Dengeki Girl''s Style*, which shares information on otome games, directed towards females.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its self-designation as a "magazine", *Dengeki G''s Magazine* comprised over 350 pages per issue, with about half of these pages in color, providing information about games or anime. The remaining pages, placed at the end of the magazine, featured serialized manga series. Unusual for Japanese publications, the pages were turned from right to left for the first half of the magazine, but this was reversed to the traditional left-to-right configuration when reading the manga series.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Dengeki G''s Magazine* was originally launched in 1992 under the name *Dengeki PC Engine*. Due to low sales, the magazine was renamed *Dengeki G''s Engine* in 1996. The magazine adopted its current title, *Dengeki G''s Magazine*, from the August 1997 issue. However, the Japanese title was altered from 電撃G''sマガジン to 電撃G''s magazine in 2002. The magazine celebrated its fifteenth anniversary of publication in 2007, marking its 200th issue with the October 2007 edition.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In May 2014, most of the manga serialized in the magazine was moved to *Dengeki G''s Comic*. The magazine concluded its publication with the December 2022 issue and transferred its content to G-Channel. Despite the magazine''s discontinuation, its spin-off magazine, *LoveLive! Days!*, persists in publication.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki PlayStation', N'dengeki-playstation', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Dengeki PlayStation* (Japanese: 電撃 PlayStation) is a Japanese video gaming publication initially developed by ASCII Media Works, a company that has since been rebranded as MediaWorks. The publication principally includes information related to the PlayStation brand.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was first introduced in December 1994 as a special edition of Dengeki G''s Magazine. It continued production until March 28, 2020, when it published its final issue, number 686, featuring Cloud Strife from the "Final Fantasy VII Remake" on its cover. This decision was prompted by shifting circumstances in the media industry and the way game information is delivered. However, the publication persists in a digital format through the Dengeki Online website.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, *Dengeki PlayStation* launched several special edition versions:' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'1. **Dengeki PS2** was released approximately three or four times a year at irregular intervals. First published on January 22, 1997, under the title *Dengeki PlayStation D*, it was later renamed to its current title in September 2001 and continued until its final issue on February 15, 2008. While the magazine predominantly covered PlayStation 2 games, it also included information about PlayStation 3 and PlayStation Portable games.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'2. **Dengeki PSP** was another special edition version published only a few times a year and at irregular intervals. The magazine mainly featured information on the PlayStation Portable and was published between December 3, 2004, and October 21, 2011.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'3. **Dengeki Girl''s Style** (Japanese: 電撃 Girl''s Style) was the third special edition version of *Dengeki PlayStation*. Initially published under the title *Dengeki PlayStation Girl''s Style* on December 4, 2003, the title dropped the "PlayStation" in early 2007. Initially sold quarterly, it switched to a bimonthly publication on April 10, 2007, and became an independent magazine. It began to be published monthly on April 10, 2012. The magazine mainly featured information on otome and boy''s love games but also included information on anime and manga targeted towards a female audience. A special edition version titled *Dengeki Girl''s Style BL Version* specifically covered information on shōnen-ai otome games and was first sold on June 30, 2008.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'4. **Dengeki Online D** was the fourth special edition version of *Dengeki PlayStation* and was first published between August 31 and December 21, 2007. The magazine covered online-capable video games for many different platforms, with games such as *Final Fantasy XI* and *Monster Hunter Frontier* featured in the first issue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In summary, *Dengeki PlayStation* has been a significant contributor to the video gaming publication landscape, particularly regarding PlayStation-related content. Despite ceasing its print publication in 2020, it continues to engage its readership through its digital platform, Dengeki Online, demonstrating its adaptability in an ever-evolving media environment.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Edge', N'edge', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Edge* is a multi-format video game magazine based in the United Kingdom, notable for its in-depth coverage and focus on the gaming industry. The magazine is published by Future plc, releasing 13 issues annually. It has also seen foreign editions in countries including Australia, Brazil, France, Germany, Italy, and Spain. The magazine was launched in October 1993 by Steve Jarratt, a long-time video games journalist known for launching several other magazines under the Future plc umbrella.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has seen numerous changes in editorial leadership over the years. Notably, the editorship of *Edge* passed back to Tony Mott, who had previously served as editor prior to João Diniz-Sanches, after a walkout in October 2003 led by the then-editor Diniz-Sanches, along with deputy editor David McCarthy and other staff writers. The only team member who remained after this event was Margaret Robertson, who replaced Mott as editor in 2006. Robertson stepped down in 2007, leading to Mott taking over as editor for the third time. Alex Wiltshire served as the magazine''s editor from May 2012 to March 2013, followed by Nathan Brown. Jen Simpkins took over the editor''s role from Nathan Brown in April 2020.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of physical design, *Edge* has undergone three redesigns since its inception. The first occurred in 1999, altering the magazine''s dimensions to be wider than the original shape. The second redesign took place in 2004, and the third and latest was in 2011. This recent design change once again altered the magazine''s physical dimensions and introduced a higher quality of paper stock than what was previously used.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *Edge* includes a "Making-of" article on a specific game, often featuring an interview with one of the original developers. Issue 143 introduced the "Time Extend" series of retrospective articles, offering an in-depth examination of a game''s most interesting or innovative attributes with the benefit of hindsight. The magazine also features "Codeshop," which examines more technical subjects like 3D modelling programs or physics middleware. Other regular sections include "Studio Profile" and "University Profile," providing summaries of specific developers or publishers and game-related courses at higher education institutions, respectively.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Between 1995 and 2002, content from the UK edition of *Edge* was published in the United States under the name *Next Generation*. In 2007, Future''s US subsidiary, Future US, began republishing selected recent *Edge* features on the Next Generation website. The *Edge* website and blog were subsequently incorporated into the NextGen site. In July 2008, the whole site was rebranded under the *Edge* title. However, in May 2014, it was reported that Future intended to close the websites of *Edge*, Computer and Video Games, and other videogame publications. By January 2015, it was announced that the *Edge* website would follow the same fate as the C&VG website.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Regarding circulation, *Edge* has had notable events in its publication history. For instance, the artwork for the cover of the magazine''s 100th issue was specially provided by renowned game designer Shigeru Miyamoto. The 200th issue, released in March 2009, had 200 different covers, each commemorating a single game. Only 200 magazines were printed with each cover, which was more than sufficient to satisfy *Edge*''s circulation of 28,898 at the time.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Popeye', N'popeye', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}_Popeye_ (ポパイ) is a well-regarded monthly fashion and men''s magazine, based in Tokyo, Japan. It carries the unique tagline, “Magazine for City Boys.” This publication is one of the oldest in its genre, featuring comprehensive articles on men''s fashion. The magazine is often likened to the Japanese equivalent of Nylon magazine, a similar fashion and lifestyle publication based in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The history of _Popeye_ traces back to 1976 when it was launched as a male counterpart to an an, a women''s magazine. The publication was the successor of two magazines, Ski Life and Made in U.S.A. The debut issue, which appeared in July 1976, highlighted the prevalent fashion trends in Los Angeles. The launch editor of the magazine was Yoshihisa Kinameri. The Magazine House Ltd., a Tokyo-based publishing company, and the founder of the magazine, then known as Heibun Shuppan, serves as the publisher. The magazine was initially published biweekly but has since transitioned to a monthly schedule. It caters to young, educated urban men, with a primary focus on fashion content, including clothes, bags, shoes, and accessories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2012, Takahiro Kinoshita assumed the position of editor-in-chief, marking a significant point in the magazine''s timeline. That same year, the magazine underwent a redesign, further refining its aesthetic and appeal.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, _Popeye_ has introduced several sister publications, including an an, Brutus, and Croissant. The magazine and its sibling Brutus received the best magazine award in 2013, and _Popeye_ celebrated its 40th anniversary in July 2016.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has enjoyed substantial circulation over the years, selling 220,000 copies in 1999. Its impact on the fashion and cultural landscape, particularly for city boys in Japan, continues to be significant.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Seventeen (Japan)', N'seventeen-japan', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Seventeen* (Japanese: セブンティーン, Hepburn: Sebuntīn) is a Japanese fashion magazine primarily intended for female teenagers. The magazine is published monthly by Shueisha, a prominent publisher in Japan. The initial issue of *Seventeen* was released in 1967, initially as a weekly publication. It was inspired by the original American version of the magazine, Seventeen. In 1987, the name of the magazine was officially changed to SEVENTEEN, and it was further simplified to Seventeen in 2008.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'From the late 1990s, *Seventeen* has held the distinction of being the highest-selling teenage fashion magazine in Japan. One of the unique features of the magazine is its exclusive use of teenage models, referred to as ST-Mo (STモ - S even t een Mo del). Being featured in the magazine, particularly on its cover or prominent pages, is highly sought after among models, as it often leads to high-quality endorsements and prestigious contracts. Some well-known former Seventeen models include Megumi Asaoka, Keiko Kitagawa, Nana Eikura, Mirei Kiritani, Rie Miyazawa, Anna Tsuchiya, Hinano Yoshikawa, and Emi Suzuki.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In a notable period from 2005 to 2007, *Seventeen* made the controversial decision to let go all of its “mixed-race” models, specifically those of Eurasian ancestry, who were often considered to be overweight models. This move was referred to as the “moggy zero movement” or the “lard purge” by critics. Following this period, the sales of the magazine began to surge significantly.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s editorial direction underwent a shift around 2005 due to the influence of the now-defunct lifestyle magazine Burst. Burst was known for its radicality and had helped many of its featured female models become millionaires. After Burst ceased publication, *Seventeen* hired at least three former Burst editors as prominent staff members. This led to changes in the magazine’s presentation and content, with many of Burst''s “characteristic phrases” making their way into Seventeen''s headlines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The circulation of *Seventeen* was reported to be 327,334 in 2008, indicating its significant reach and influence among the teenage population in Japan.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Seventeen (USA)', N'seventeen-usa', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Seventeen* is an American bimonthly teen magazine based in New York City. Established in 1944, the publication primarily targets a demographic of 13-to-19-year-old females. Owned by Hearst Magazines, the magazine was originally created to inspire teen girls to become model workers and citizens. However, it soon shifted its focus towards a more fashion and romance-oriented approach, while still emphasizing the importance of self-confidence in young women. Alongside these primary themes, *Seventeen* also reports the latest news about celebrities. With nearly eight decades of inspiring young women, *Seventeen* remains a distinguished publication in the realm of teen magazines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Seventeen*''s first publisher, Helen Valentine, provided teenaged girls with working-woman role models and information about their development and growth. The magazine played a key role in the emergence of "teenager" as a distinct demographic. It was launched in New York City in September 1944, and it quickly became an important source of information to manufacturers seeking guidance on how to satisfy consumer demand among teenagers. Today, the magazine continues to entertain and promote self-confidence in young women.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of its history of diversity, Joyce Walker became the first black model to be featured on the cover of *Seventeen* in July 1971. In 1981, Whitney Houston was also featured on the cover of the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine changed hands several times, being sold to K-III Communications by the New York City-based News Corporation in 1991, then to Hearst in 2003. Despite increased competition, *Seventeen* remains popular on newsstands.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In response to reader protests against the magazine''s airbrushing its models'' photos, *Seventeen* ended its practice of using digital photo manipulation to enhance published photographs in 2012.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2016, the magazine shifted its publishing schedule to only six issues a year instead of 10, to focus on their online presence and appeal to the Generation Z market. In the same year, Michelle Tan was relieved from her position as editor-in-chief while she was on maternity leave. Michele Promaulayko, who was appointed editor-in-chief of Cosmopolitan, also took over as *Seventeen*''s editorial director. In 2018, Jessica Pels took over from Promaulayko as editor-in-chief of Cosmopolitan, and Kristin Koch was appointed *Seventeen*''s new executive director, overseeing all its content.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Architectural Forum', N'architectural-forum', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Architectural Forum* was an American magazine devoted to the homebuilding industry and architecture. Its inception in Boston, Massachusetts dates back to 1892 when it was originally named *The Brickbuilder*. The magazine later integrated the content of *Architect''s World* in October 1938. The ownership of *Architectural Forum* transitioned among several proprietors over its lifespan, including Time, Inc., Urban America, Inc., Whitney Publications, and ultimately Billboard Publications in 1972. After Billboard''s acquisition of the *Forum*, chief editor Peter Blake and most of the staff departed to establish a new magazine, *Architecture Plus*, in 1973. *Architectural Forum* discontinued its publication in 1974.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its existence, the journal was published under a couple of different names. Between 1892 and 1916, it was known as *The Brickbuilder* and from 1917 to 1974, it carried the title *Architectural Forum*. For a period, the journal also included a subtitle, *The Magazine of Building*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notable contributions include those by graphic designer Paul Rand who designed the covers for the March and April 1945 issues. One of the magazine''s significant contributions to architectural discourse was the introduction of the term *194X* in its October 1943 issue. This term was used to represent post-war urban and city planning, where the ''X'' symbolized the anticipated end of the war. The issue presented plans for shopping centers, housing, and schools, tailored to the needs and size of a population. This represented a broader shift in American culture, as many anticipated that the end of the war would mark the beginning of a new era of architecture and urbanization that had been stagnated due to the war.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Boston Magazine', N'boston-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}_Boston_ is a monthly publication that delves into life in the Greater Boston area. With its roots dating back to 1805, it stands as one of the longest-running magazines in the region. The magazine was acquired by Metrocorp, Inc. in 1970, a company that also owns _Philadelphia_ magazine. Boasting a circulation of 500,000 issues per month, _Boston_ holds a commendable record for newsstand copies sold, marking its standing among the highest of any magazine in the United States. It has been recognized for its excellence on multiple occasions, receiving accolades as one of the nation''s best city magazines by the City and Regional Magazine Association nine times in the past decade.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, _Boston_ has been under the guidance of several notable editors-in-chief, including Carly Carioli, John Wolfson, and Andrew Putz. Its contribution to the city''s culture and lifestyle was acknowledged in May 2015 when it was honored by the City and Regional Magazine Association.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine''s defining features is its annual "Best of Boston" awards, a tradition that began in 1974. These awards cover a broad spectrum of categories that change each year, ranging from the best clam chowder and cookware to the best day spa, gym, jewelry store, martini, mojito, pizza topping, shiatsu, teeth whitening, and Thai food, among others. The recognition carries weight within the local community, with many businesses proudly displaying their awards in store windows, on company materials, and in advertising. Complementing these annual awards, _Boston_ also features articles that quantify local resources, such as "Top Schools," "Top Restaurants," and "Top Doctors."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its main publication, _Boston_ magazine extends its reach through several ancillary publications. _Boston Home_ is a quarterly publication that caters to readers with an interest in high-end interior design, home decor, and architecture. _Boston Weddings_, released biannually, serves as a resource for wedding planners and brides-to-be.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s ownership has remained with the Philadelphia-based company Metrocorp since 1971. The magazine enjoys collaborative relationships with local media entities such as WCVB-TV Channel 5, WBZ NewsRadio, Greater Media, WBUR, and Magic 106.7. Furthermore, _Boston_ magazine is a member of the American Society of Magazine Editors (ASME).{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bound & Gagged', N'bound-and-gagged', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Bound & Gagged* was a magazine published by the Outbound Press from 1987 to 2005. It catered to the interests of gay bondage and discipline practitioners, providing articles about actual and fictional encounters, techniques, fantasies, and images of bound and gagged men. The magazine was based in New York City and was published in English.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Bob Wingate, the founder and editor-in-chief of *Bound & Gagged*, provided a unique perspective on the magazine''s inception. He stated, “When *Bound & Gagged* first appeared on the scene, there was virtually nothing else out there. Drummer published bondage stories and photos from time to time, but there was nothing devoted to bondage in all its varied manifestations, from average guys simply cuffing and rope tying each other for fun, to whole ritualistic life-styles in leather and latex, making use of the most elegant and expensive restrictive devices—not to mention everything in between.”' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The final issue of the magazine was released in June 2005. A complete set of *Bound & Gagged* is preserved at the Leather Archives and Museum, along with a 25-box collection of papers from Robert W. Davolt, a subsequent editor of the magazine. In 2017, Davolt was honored with other notable figures, his name engraved on bronze bootprints as part of the San Francisco South of Market Leather History Alley.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Car & Driver', N'car-and-driver', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}Car and Driver (CD or C/D) is an esteemed American automotive enthusiast magazine based in Ann Arbor, Michigan. The magazine was founded in 1955 under the original title Sports Cars Illustrated. In its early years, the magazine primarily focused on small, imported sports cars. However, in 1961, the editor Karl Ludvigsen renamed the magazine to Car and Driver to reflect a broader automotive focus.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine gained popularity due to its irreverent tone and habit of "telling it like it is," especially when addressing underperforming automobiles. The editorial approach of the magazine is decidedly pro-automobile. Though it frequently delves into controversial issues, especially regarding politics, the intrusion of politics into editorial columns rarely intrudes into reviews of cars themselves or feature articles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Prominent personalities such as Bruce McCall, Jean Shepherd, and Brock Yates have featured as columnists in Car and Driver, and P. J. O''Rourke was a frequent contributor. The magazine has had several notable editors, including William Jeanes and David E. Davis, Jr.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notably, rather than electing a Car of the Year, Car and Driver publishes its top ten picks each year in its Car and Driver 10Best. The magazine is also known for the John Lingenfelter Memorial Trophy, an award given annually at their Supercar Challenge.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Internationally, Car and Driver is published in Germany, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and Spain. The Spanish version, however, only makes use of the Car and Driver name and does not share editorial direction with the American version. The Middle Eastern edition of the magazine is issued by ITP Publishing based in Dubai.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In recent years, Car and Driver has continued to provide its readers with in-depth industry reporting and explorations of various automotive topics. For instance, in 2021, the magazine''s coverage ranged from detailed reviews of new and upcoming car models to the analysis of broader industry trends such as the shift towards electric vehicles and the impact of supply-chain issues. The magazine''s unique and creative cover designs, such as a vending machine filled with their annual 10Best winners, continue to engage its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In conclusion, Car and Driver remains a major voice in automotive journalism, providing comprehensive coverage of the global automotive industry while maintaining a unique and reader-focused approach.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'16', N'16', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*16 Magazine* was an American fan magazine published from 1956 to 2001. Its primary audience was teenagers, and its name derived from its intended demographic—16-year-old readers. The magazine was a key publication in the teen idol phenomenon of the 1950s through the 1980s, featuring articles, photographs, and interviews with popular teen stars of the time. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded by former *Radio Mirror* and *Hit Parader* editor, Gloria Stavers. Stavers served as editor-in-chief from 1958 to 1975 and was renowned for her close relationships with many of the celebrities featured in the magazine. This often granted *16 Magazine* exclusive interviews and photographs, setting it apart from its competitors. It was under Stavers’ leadership that the magazine gained significant popularity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*16 Magazine* was distinctive in its innovative approach to fan culture. It was the first to provide song lyrics and pin-up posters of popular music stars. In addition, it published personal information about celebrities such as their likes, dislikes, and fan mail addresses. This allowed readers to feel a sense of personal connection with their idols, a strategy that greatly contributed to the magazine''s success.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s content primarily focused on music and film celebrities. It initially featured teen idols from the 1950s, like Elvis Presley and the Beatles. However, it eventually extended its coverage to include television actors, especially those from popular teen-oriented shows. In the 1960s and 1970s, *16 Magazine* expanded its scope to cover rock bands such as the Rolling Stones and Led Zeppelin. By the 1980s and 1990s, the magazine was covering a wide range of popular culture figures, from the New Kids on the Block to the cast of Beverly Hills, 90210.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity, *16 Magazine* began to face challenges in the late 1990s. As teen interests shifted towards new media platforms, the magazine struggled to maintain its relevance. Although it attempted to adapt its content to changing trends, it was unable to keep pace with the rapidly evolving media landscape. The magazine ceased publication in 2001.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*16 Magazine* left a lasting impact on popular culture and the publishing industry. It set a precedent for other fan magazines and played a significant role in shaping teen culture during its publication period. Even after its discontinuation, *16 Magazine* is remembered for its iconic status in the realm of teen fan culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki Moeoh', N'dengeki-moeoh', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}_Dengeki Moeoh_ (電撃萌王) is a Japanese seinen manga magazine, marketed primarily towards male readers. The magazine originated as a special edition version of _Dengeki Daioh_, and has been in circulation since March 2002. It was initially published on a quarterly basis until December 2005. After a three-month hiatus following its sixteenth issue, the magazine resumed publication in March 2006 on a bimonthly schedule, with issues being released on the twenty-sixth of every other month.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content of _Dengeki Moeoh_ heavily emphasizes moe, a term used within the anime and manga communities to describe feelings of affection towards characters, particularly those that are cute or endearing. This focus is further highlighted by the magazine’s high ratio of color pages, as _Dengeki Moeoh_ regularly publishes a significant number of color illustrations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has been home to a variety of series, including but not limited to “Neet Kunoichi to Naze ka Dousei Hajimemashita,” “Sasha-chan to Classmate Otaku-kun,” “Isekai Ittara, Sude ni Imouto ga Maou to Shite Boukun Shite Ita Hanashi,” “Fuukiihan Sugiru Maid to ♂♀ Tsukutte Jinruikyuusai!,” “The Devil is a Part-Timer no Meshi!,” “Etotama: Pretty Theater,” and “Bara Nikki.”' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its niche demographic, _Dengeki Moeoh_ has managed to establish a firm presence within the manga industry, consistently offering its readers a unique and colorful selection of moe-themed content over the course of its publication history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki Maoh', N'dengeki-maoh', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*Dengeki Maoh* (電撃マオウ) is a Japanese seinen magazine published by ASCII Media Works, which was formerly known as MediaWorks. The magazine first went on sale on October 27, 2005, and has been sold every month on the twenty-seventh since then. *Dengeki Maoh* features information on various forms of media including video games, manga, and light novels.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A special edition version of the magazine, *Dengeki Black Maoh* (電撃黒マ王), was published quarterly from September 19, 2007, until June 19, 2010. This edition also focused on the seinen demographic and was published by ASCII Media Works.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of content, *Dengeki Maoh* has published a variety of original manga series. Some of the original series published in the magazine include "This Art Club Has A Problem!", "Mattaku Saikin no Tantei to Kitara", "Oroka na Tenshi wa Akuma to Odoru", "Wana Girl", "Zatsu Tabi: That''s Journey", "Gun Festa", "Zenbu Kimi no Sei", "Coffee Moon", "Watashi wo Tabetai, Hitodenashi", "Touring After the Apocalypse", "Shoujo Juuki", "Poker Face Josou Danshi to.", "Ikimono Suki no Anima-san ni wa Honno Choppiri Doku ga Aru", "NYA-KANO Genic!!", and "Okawa Bukubu no Kusomanga Dojo".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to original series, the magazine has also published manga adaptations of existing works, including "Puchimas! Petit iDOLM@STER", "The iDOLM@STER Million Live!: Blooming Clover", "The Reformation of the World as Overseen by a Realist Demon King", "Rebuild World", "Tanaka-ke, Tensei Suru.", "The Magical Revolution of the Reincarnated Princess and the Genius Young Lady", "Heat the Pig Liver", "Muteki Shounin no Isekai Nariagari Monogatari", and "Ossan, Tensei Shite Tensai Yakusha ni Naru".{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki hp', N'dengeki-hp', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription }}*__Dengeki hp__* (電撃hp) was a Japanese magazine dedicated to the publication of light novels. The magazine was published by MediaWorks and catered towards a young adult male readership. Its first issue was released on December 18, 1998, and for the initial eight issues, it was published quarterly. Subsequently, from the ninth issue onwards until its 50th and final issue, the magazine followed a bimonthly publication schedule. The final issue of *Dengeki hp* was published in October 2007. The magazine ceased publication and was succeeded by *Dengeki Bunko Magazine* in December 2007.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*__Dengeki hp__* was known for featuring various notable works during its publication run. Some of the serialized titles include:' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- *__Boogiepop Doesn''t Laugh__* (ブギーポップは笑わない): This manga series, written by Kouhei Kadono and illustrated by Kouji Ogata, is a drama, mystery, and supernatural story set in an unnamed Japanese city. The plot revolves around five students at Shinyo Academy as they try to unravel the mystery behind a new drug and recent disappearances among the student population.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- *__Satsujinki Series__*: A light novel series penned by Kazuma Kamachi and illustrated by Kiyotaka Haimura, this fantasy narrative occurs in a world where individuals known as Killer Demons have each mastered a unique form of killing. The series follows different characters'' encounters with these Killer Demons.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- *__Kirin wa Ichizu ni Koi wo Suru__*: This light novel series, written by You Shiina and illustrated by Kazuya Shimura, is a fantasy romance story. The synopsis for this series was not available at the time of writing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- *__Heaven''s Dust Syndrome__*: Authored by Yoshimiru, this manga is a sci-fi tale about the journey of a small robot and an android maiden in search of their origins and a secret place.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- *__Beat''s Discipline__*: Another light novel series by Kouhei Kadono and Kouji Ogata, this action story is a spin-off of the *Boogiepop* series, focusing on the character Minoru Sera.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Dengeki Daiouji
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki Daiouji', N'dengeki-daiouji', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Launched in 2013, this monthly Japanese magazine targets a male audience with its focus on fiction, 4-Koma and Gag Manga. It includes both original and derivative series.}}*Dengeki Daiouji* (コミック電撃だいおうじ), is a monthly Japanese magazine primarily geared towards male readership and known for its fiction content. The magazine was first issued in September 2013 by ASCII Media Works, and it is released on the 27th of each month. The magazine is considered a special edition of *Dengeki Daioh* and has a focus on 4-Koma and Gag Manga.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine features numerous original and derivative series, including but not limited to:' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Original series such as *Gabriel DropOut*, *Ane no Shinyuu, Watashi no Koibito.*, *Gahi-chan!*, *Ninja to Koroshiya no Futarigurashi*, *Kouhai OL wa Maid no Hina-san Nanka Janai*, *Yuyunoyu!*, *#Zombie Sagashitemasu*, *Kitamachi-san wa ''Tada no'' Tomodachi*, *Cinderella Cosplaytion*, *Yukidoke to Agapanthus*, *♀ Gaki to Oji-san*, *Kankaku Kyouyuu Maid-san!*, *Yuushuu Dakedo Yabai OL*, *Satomu Fallin'' Love*, *Kimyou de Kaii na Nichijoutan!*, *Fuyuriina-sensei no Ro-bai*, and *Ab-rabu-kadabra*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Derivative works like *The Irregular at Magic High School: Yonkoma Arc*, *Nyanta to Pomeko: Imasara Shinjiteiru to Iwaretemo Mou Teokure da (Manga)*, *Koi wa Futago de Warikirenai (Manga)*, *Imouto wa Kanojo ni Deki Nai no ni (Manga)*, and *Danshi da to Omotte Ita Osananajimi to no Shinkon Seikatsu ga Umaku Ikisugiru Ken Nitsuite (Manga)*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also features irregular serializations like *Gamate* and *Nonkafe*.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Dengeki Daioh
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki Daioh', N'dengeki-daioh', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Launched in 1993, this Japanese manga magazine known for its captivating cover art has played a major role in shaping pop culture, with many of its manga series adapted into globally acclaimed anime.}}_Dengeki Daioh_ (電撃大王) is a monthly Japanese shōnen manga magazine published by ASCII Media Works (formerly MediaWorks). The magazine was first published in 1993 and is known for publishing manga series that are later adapted into popular anime. The magazine''s title is derived from "dengeki", meaning "electric shock", and "daioh", meaning "great king".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_"Dengeki Daioh"_ is primarily aimed at a young male audience, but its diverse range of manga titles has allowed it to garner a broad readership. Over the years, the magazine has introduced various manga series that have had a substantial impact on Japanese pop culture. Some of the notable manga series that began serialization in _"Dengeki Daioh"_ include "Toaru Majutsu no Index", "Yotsuba&!", and "Azumanga Daioh", among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is known for its unique and distinctive aesthetic, often featuring elaborate cover art that showcases characters from the manga series currently being serialized within its pages. It also includes bonus content such as fan art submissions, author interviews, and manga-related news. Despite being a print publication, _"Dengeki Daioh"_ has embraced digital trends and offers online subscription services, making it accessible to readers outside of Japan.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_"Dengeki Daioh"_''s influence extends beyond the realm of manga. Many series originally published in the magazine have been adapted into anime, light novels, video games, and other forms of media, greatly contributing to the multimedia nature of contemporary Japanese pop culture. Some of these adaptations have gained international acclaim and have been instrumental in popularizing manga and anime in the West.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Dengeki Bunko
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Dengeki Bunko', N'dengeki-bunko', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Originating as a special edition of Dengeki Daioh, this Japanese light novel magazine served as a platform for ASCII Media Works'' publishing label. Ceased publication in 2020.}}_Dengeki Bunko Magazine_ (電撃文庫MAGAZINE) was a Japanese light novel magazine published by ASCII Media Works, which was formerly known as MediaWorks. Its inception followed the discontinuation of the light novel magazine *Dengeki hp*, and it was originally issued as a special edition of *Dengeki Daioh* for its first two issues. The first issue made its debut on December 10, 2007. *Dengeki Bunko Magazine* gained independence with the publication of its third volume on April 10, 2008.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine served as a platform to disseminate information related to ASCII Media Works’ light novel publishing label, *Dengeki Bunko*. In addition to this, it featured short stories penned by well-established authors who had previously had their light novels published under the *Dengeki Bunko* label. Other content within the magazine included details on adaptations of these light novels into other media formats such as video games, anime, or manga.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Dengeki Bunko Magazine* ceased publication on April 9, 2020.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Magma
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Magma', N'magma', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Annual art publication featuring exclusive works from diverse creative fields.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Magma* is a print publication founded by Paul Olivennes, focused on the restoration of the revues d''art format, reminiscent of influential 20th-century art magazines such as Georges Bataille''s Documents (1929), the surrealist Minotaure (1933), and the early issues of Andy Warhol''s Interview magazine (1969). The magazine is supported by Matthieu Blazy''s Bottega Veneta, known for its advocacy of various media formats.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Concept' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Magma serves as a cultural and societal resurgence, documenting seminal, epochal works, words, and art that define an era. It aims to revive the aesthetic, graphic, and intellectual sophistication of the revues d''art format, putting artists and writers back at the center stage and fostering dialogue between them.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine features a large number of previously unpublished works or works created exclusively for the journal, offering a glimpse into the creative process of the artists. It is designed to be collected and is released once a year.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Contributors' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The inaugural issue of Magma includes contributions from a diverse range of artists, writers, architects, filmmakers, sculptors, and photographers. Hans Ulrich Obrist, Artistic Director of Serpentine Galleries London, wrote the publication preface, stating that "Magma brings worlds into contact with other worlds." Its aim is to continue the tradition of great 20th-century art magazines, serving more as a history lesson than anything else.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Availability' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue of Magma is priced at €60 (approx. $65 USD).{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 47
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'47: The Magazine of the Year', N'47-the-magazine-of-the-year', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American magazine with a unique annual renaming practice, published from 1947-1948, offered diverse content and boasted top contributors but struggled financially, leading to its closure.}}_47: The Magazine of the Year_, also known as _48: The Magazine of the Year_, was an American magazine first published in March 1947, with its final issue released in June 1948. The magazine was based in New York, New York, and was published on a monthly basis.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s unique feature was that it altered its title with the changing calendar year, hence being recognized as _47_ in the year 1947 and as _48_ in the year 1948. This novel approach to titling led to the magazine being indexed in libraries by its subtitle, "The Magazine of the Year".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_47_ was a cooperative venture owned and contributed to by hundreds of renowned writers and artists of the era. Clifton Fadiman led the publication, which boasted an impressive list of contributors including Roy Chapman Andrews, Roger Butterfield, Ilka Chase, Walter Van Tilburg Clark, Laura Z. Hobson, Howard Lindsay, Walter Lippmann, John McNulty, Andy Rooney, Christopher Morley, Ogden Nash, S. J. Perelman, Upton Sinclair, John Steinbeck, and Irving Wallace among others. Also contributing were graphic artists Karsh and Marsh, Gropper, and Virgil Partch.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was published both on pulp and coated paper, approximately the size of _Reader''s Digest_ and _Coronet_. It aimed to depict the changing times and the dawning of a new world. Its readers across the forty-eight states learned about a wide range of topics, from the territory of Alaska and FM broadcasting, to the latest developments in Social Security and the dangers of rheumatic fever. The magazine also included a range of features such as tasteful nudes and mildly amusing cartoons.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its impressive contributor list and diverse content, _47_ was more expensive than many of its contemporaries, costing 35 cents per copy at a time when the weekly _Saturday Evening Post_ cost only 10 cents a copy. This pricing may have contributed to the magazine''s struggles. By September 1947, the magazine was acknowledging its shortcomings in a postcard to subscribers, admitting that it had "let everybody down" and had been "flat, dull, ordinary".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication began to run advertisements early in 1948, but by May of that same year, it found itself having to lay off its circulation department and seek court approval for a reorganization under the National Bankruptcy Act. Despite the talents of its owner-contributors, the magazine had struggled to afford the prices other magazines paid for top-drawer pieces and had been forced to purchase more affordable, less desirable content. The magazine ultimately came to an end with the June 1948 issue, after having published sixteen issues. At the time of its closure, publisher Walter Ross announced that the magazine was $150,000 in debt, having cost its investors $700,000.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 73
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'73 Amateur Radio Today', N'73-amateur-radio-today', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Founded by Wayne Green in 1960, this American amateur radio magazine emphasized technical articles and editorials. Publication ceased in 2003 due to financial pressures.}}*73 Magazine*, alternatively known as *73 Amateur Radio Today*, was a United States-based periodical dedicated to the subject of amateur radio. The magazine was first published in 1960 and continued to issue monthly editions until 2003. It was renowned for its technical articles and the extensive editorials in each issue penned by the founder and publisher, Wayne Green.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s title, *73*, refers to a term in amateur radio lingo, translating to “best regards” when expressed in Morse code. The inaugural issue was launched from Green’s business offices located in Brooklyn, New York, in October 1960. A key contributing editor was Ken Sessions, K6MVH, who penned a column titled “The Chronicles of 76”, alluding to the FM transmitting frequency of 146.76 megahertz. Sessions was not only a prolific writer on the subject of amateur radio but also the designer of many how-to projects featured in the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jean Shepherd, K2ORS, was another notable contributor to *73 Magazine*. The publication had a significant impact on the amateur radio community, pioneering the promotion of SSB, FM, solid-state, easy construction projects, and most importantly, the fusion of personal computing and amateur radio. In 1962, the headquarters of *73 Magazine* relocated to Peterborough, New Hampshire. During the 1970s and 80s, the average issue of *73* comprised over 300 pages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*73 Magazine* was particularly known for its editorial column, “Never Say Die”, where Green, along with Sessions, often voiced criticism towards the American Radio Relay League. The column’s title, “Never Say Die”, was a clever backronym for Green’s amateur radio call sign, W2NSD. Green also founded several microcomputing magazines such as “Desktop Computing”, “Kilobaud Microcomputing”, and “80 Micro”, and played a role in the establishment of *Byte Magazine*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2003, after 43 years of uninterrupted publication, *73 Amateur Radio Today* announced its final issue in September. There was a plan for a combined October/November 2003 issue, which, however, never saw the light of day. Financial pressure resulting from diminished advertising revenue was cited by Green as the primary cause for halting the magazine''s publication.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 944
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'944', N'944', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Founded in Phoenix, expanded to a nationwide presence, this once thriving lifestyle publication navigated both great success and bankruptcy before its closure in 2011.}}*944* was a regional fashion, entertainment, and lifestyle publication that operated in the United States from 2001 to 2011. This noteworthy publication was the brainchild of the original *944 Media* company, founded by Marc Lotenberg in Phoenix, Arizona, in 2001. With time, it became part of *944 Media* based in Los Angeles, marking a significant phase in its evolution.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In a bold move that showcased the magazine’s growth and expanding influence, *944 Media* announced the acquisition of *Six Degrees* in March 2009. *Six Degrees* was a competing upscale lifestyle magazine with editions in Atlanta, Detroit, Miami, and Las Vegas, as well as an accompanying web portal. By October of that year, *944 Media* ceased the publication of *Six Degrees* and launched two new editions of *944* to penetrate the Atlanta and Detroit markets. The magazine’s expansion continued in April 2010 with the launch of its tenth edition, this time targeting the Dallas market.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, despite its expansion and success, the company faced significant challenges. In April 2010, *944 Media, LLC.* declared Chapter 11 bankruptcy in the United States Bankruptcy Court for the Central District of California, Los Angeles Division. The company was represented by Landau Gottfried & Berger LLP during this period.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ultimately, on June 1, 2011, *944* announced the publication of their last issue and the permanent closure of the business. This marked the end of a decade-long journey that had seen the magazine grow from a local Phoenix publication to a nationwide lifestyle brand.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Fire & Movement 
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Fire & Movement ', N'fire-and-movement', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Quarterly publication providing in-depth analysis of historical military operations and tactics.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Fire & Movement", a quarterly publication first issued in 1976, has etched its place in the spectrums of academia and military knowledge. This professional periodical, printed in English, delves into the subject of historical military operations and tactics, earning esteemed recognition in intellectual circles. Although it is an American creation, and doesn''t have a native name in a foreign language, the magazine is available and followed globally.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The spectrum of the magazine''s focus is impressively broad, encompassing diverse periods and theatres of military history: from the world changing maneuvers of World War II, through the geopolitical complexities of 20th and 21st century wars, to the intricacies and evolution of military technology. Therefore, researchers and military professionals find invaluable insights and analyses in its pages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond the periodic printed version, its viewership extends to an extensive online archive that allows access to prior issues. This digital facility enriches its inherent value for both military enthusiasts and historical researchers everywhere.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With an illustrious editorial board composed of veteran military officers and trailblazers in military history, the reputation of "Fire & Movement" perpetually proliferates. Esteemed contributors, respected globally for their erudition on military knowledge, including Gunther E. Rothenberg, B. H. Liddell Hart, and Peter Paret have helped shape the intellectual landscape of the publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Predominantly, "Fire & Movement" can be accessed through a subscription, but it can also be found in various bookstores worldwide. Consequently, ensuring this resource continues to intellectualize, debate, and chronicle the evolving discussion on military history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Fire Chief 
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Fire Chief ', N'fire-chief', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Specialized resource for fire service leaders, detailing tactics, administration, innovation, and public safety issues.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Fire Chief" is an American magazine created exclusively for leaders within the fire and rescue service industries. First established in 1956, the publication has functioned as a premier resource for higher-level firefighters all across the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With focal domains including emergent rescue techniques, administrative practices, fire service innovations and key aspects of public safety, "Fire Chief" explores a span of crucial topics that are pertinent within the field of fire rescue services. The primary readership includes fire chiefs, deputy fire chiefs, battalion chiefs, along with other influential individuals placed at strategic positions within various fire service departments.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of "Fire Chief" serves to highlight successful techniques and strategies, present data trends, provide expert insights, and even cover issues related to fire litigation and policy making. By doing so, the magazine assists fire service administrators and managers in making strategic decisions that have profound impacts on manpower, resources, budgeting, safety practices, and overall departmental efficiency.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Renowned contributors from various spheres of fire service, including fire chiefs and captains, fire safety experts, firefighters, paramedics, and fire-safety researchers, all find a place in the insightful pages of "Fire Chief". This leads to a multi-faceted exploration of perspectives, encapsulating real-world advice alongside cutting-edge research and discovery in fire service.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its physical distribution, the magazine also maintains a strong digital presence, offering its wide readership the option for accessing archived issues and engaging with a community of experienced professionals through online forums. As a result, "Fire Chief" fosters an environment of learning, growth, and collaboration amongst fire service individuals both within and beyond American borders.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Flak Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Flak Magazine', N'flak-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Independent digital publication featuring cultural commentary, art critiques, and socio-political discourse.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flak Magazine, a celebrated independent online publication, cemented its reputation in the bold flurry of the burgeoning digital journalism scene during the early 2000s. Its inception dates back to March 2001, when the world was rapidly embracing the Internet as an authentic platform for enriching, expansive, and expressive journalism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With its youthful audacity and thought-provoking content, Flak Magazine catered primarily to a demographic composed of late teens to young adults. The spectrum of topics covered by the magazine was vast, spanning from erudite cultural commentary, intellectual critiques on various forms of art and entertainment, to in-depth socio-political discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flak Magazine gained recognition for its judicious blend of formal and informal writing styles. Its informational content, infused with a certain laid-back conversational ease, engaged the audience on a level that was uncommon for traditional media outlets during this time. Precise reviews of music, books, video games, and films, alongside opinion pieces that openly dissected and deliberated contemporary issues, were its cornerstone.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was known not just for its unorthodox content, but also for its contemporary design aesthetics that showcased the intersection of minimal design with expressive pop culture. Its web layout, regularly updated to keep pace with the evolving digital landscape, added another layer to its modern editorial voice.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Balancing elements of pop culture, intellectual discussion, lifestyle, and subtle humor, Flak Magazine became a pioneering platform that not only entertained but also informed and challenged its readership. The individualistic stance it adopted in discussing societal and cultural phenomena emphasized the necessity of critical thinking, making it a truly progressive force in the digital journalism sphere.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Flex Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Flex Magazine', N'flex-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Professional bodybuilding and fitness publication featuring workout routines, athlete profiles, and competition coverage.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flex Magazine, celebrated as the stalwart publication in the realm of professional bodybuilding and fitness, first graced the industry in November 1983. Published by American Media, Inc. (AMI), it is primarily disseminated in the United States but has an international following of fitness enthusiasts and bodybuilders who swear by its expertise.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is revered for its comprehensive coverage of male and female bodybuilding. It regularly features profiles of eminent bodybuilders, both upcoming and established, along with their tailored workout routines, diet plans, training regimens, and exclusive interviews. Alongside this, Flex Magazine also delivers trend insights into bodybuilding equipment, performance nutritional supplements, and fitness-related consumer products.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The distinguished editorial voice of Flex Magazine is marked by its depth of experience and unwavering dedication to the art and sport of bodybuilding. The magazine routinely engages leading figures from the field as guest experts and contributors to ensure its audience benefits from the most recent, authentic, and insightful information and perspectives in bodybuilding.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flex Magazine''s sophisticated and navigable layout is another of its admirable facets. High-quality photography, featuring dramatic shots of athletes showcasing their peak forms, constitutes a significant part of its visual storytelling process. It augments the magazine''s in-depth articles, creating a holistic and motivating tapestry of professional bodybuilding.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Competitions hold a special place in the magazine''s content framework. From the much-awaited amateur contests to the epic universal showdown – Mr. Olympia, Flex Magazine maintains thorough coverage of these bodybuilding milestones.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Reverberating with the contagious energy of bodybuilding, the magazine''s modus operandi encompasses more than just routine information dissemination. It aims to inspire, inform, and incentivize readers, encouraging them to push their limits and build not just their bodies, but their lives, to their potential pinnacle.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Flipside Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Flipside Magazine', N'flipside-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Groundbreaking punk zine of the late 20th century, focusing on music, counterculture, and underground scenes.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flipside Magazine, a trailblazer in the field of punk zines, was launched in Los Angeles, California, in 1977. The magazine connected audiences to the heart of the emergent punk rock scene, offering an articulate and passionate platform for the counterculture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Co-created by Pooch, Al Kowalewski, and several other passionate Los Angeles music lovers, Flipside charted the unorthodox arcs and narratives of punk and alternative rock across various phases of their evolution, both domestically and internationally. The magazine''s focus was not limited to music alone, however. It extended to the broader cultural context and ethos of the punk scene, brandishing comic strips, reviews of fanzines and records, interviews, and photographs as part of its eclectic content assemblage.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flipside Magazine''s unique approach to journalism, deliberately informal yet insightful, resonated with the punk ethos of the time. The magazine was run like a collective, with a plethora of contributors including writers, photographers, and artists who shared the vision of shedding light on underground music scenes.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its tenure, Flipside Magazine remained faithful to its roots. Even as various alternative and punk musicians rode the wave of mainstream success, the publication continued to explore the evolving underground punk landscape. This entailed striking a delicate balance in covering established bands and unearthing new talent, a task the magazine''s editorial team executed with commendable precision.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of Flipside''s salient aspects was its long-form interviews. Conducted with sheer sincerity and audacity, they encapsulated the true spirit of the punk and alternative scenes, providing insightful narratives and candid views from artists who became synonymous with these genres.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s visual presentation dovetailed perfectly with its content, mashing together collages, DIY aesthetics, and scratchy, raw photographs that visually encapsulated the punk ethos. Flipside served not only as a witness to the evolution of numerous influential bands and artists but also as a touchstone of authenticity and integrity in the ever-changing realm of music journalism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite ceasing its print edition in 2000, Flipside continues to live in the hearts of numerous punk and alternative enthusiasts, personifying a valuable chronicle of a pivotal era in music and cultural history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Flux Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Flux Magazine', N'flux-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A UK-based publication blending music, the arts, and culture, renowned for its in-depth features and innovative perspectives.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flux Magazine, originating from the United Kingdom, has consistently demonstrated its prowess as an all-encompassing medium for contemporary wisdom and artistic expression since its establishment in 1990.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Conceptualized and founded by Lee Taylor, the magazine was envisioned as a platform for contrasting viewpoints and an array of arts coverage, ranging from music and theatre to visual arts and film. It steadily gained recognition for its thoughtful, provocative, and often paradigm-challenging pieces, rapidly making inroads into the creative industries it sought to critique and celebrate.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flux Magazine''s content spectrum is as diverse as its readership. The publication welcomed fresh talent in the music industry while also providing engaging features on established acts, earning a firm niche within the competitive music press landscape. Aside from music, Flux has explored a host of diverse topics including fashion, travel, technology, and socio-cultural issues, effortlessly transitioning across genres and realms of knowledge.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A distinctive hallmark of Flux Magazine has been its unyielding commitment to showcasing unique and innovative perspectives. Recognized for its discerning eye for aesthetically compelling and often avant-garde visual elements, the magazine is equally noted for its bold, in-depth interviews and articles that unfold lesser-known narratives, prompting a rethink of established paradigms or introducing groundbreaking ideas to a broader readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'This synthesis of visual and intellectual stimulation is factored meticulously within Flux''s design ethos. The publication has consistently worked with a number of creative minds, from graphic designers to illustrators, to construct a magazine that furnishes readers a visually arresting experience to complement its potent content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flux''s attention to culture extends beyond the geographical realms of its origin. Its features regularly catalogue international nuances, earmarking the magazine as an echo chamber for global narratives and trends, thereby contributing to its international appeal.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over its lifespan, Flux Magazine has excelled in narrating the complex tapestry of contemporary life and culture, unearthing richness in diversity, and fostering a space for singularity in expression.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Flying Aces
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Flying Aces', N'flying-aces', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A pulp publication from 1928-1944, focusing on aviation fiction and adventure, known for its high-quality content and illustrations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flying Aces was a preeminent literary medium largely focusing on aviation, fiction, and notably, the genre of the pulp magazine. Established in the United States in 1928, it offered a vibrant exploration of flight technology, combat stories, and adventure tales until its culmination in 1944.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'This periodical was the brainchild of Periodical House, Inc., a New York-based publisher known for generating content that captivated audiences with gripping narratives and visual stimuli. The publication found a steadfast audience among adventure-seekers and aviation enthusiasts alike, promising tales of daring endeavors, historic engagements, and awe-inspiring chronicles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flying Aces was renowned for the high standard of it''s content, covering a spectrum of subjects that included informative articles about aircraft, serialized novels, and action-adventure short stories. The magazine''s depiction of air adventure was especially immersive, enabling readers to virtually experience the pulsating thrills of aerial combats and chivalry high above the trenches.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the most distinctive facets of Flying Aces was its portfolio of illustrators and writers. Authenticity was a crux in the publication, and to maintain this, it drew upon the expertise of renowned authors such as Donald Keyhoe, Arch Whitehouse, and O.B. Myers. Through the pens of these narrative craftsmen, the magazine''s tales retained an air of veracity, transporting readers into the throbbing heart of skies aflame with dogfights and high-octane pursuits.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'An equally integral part of the magazine''s distinct identity was formed by its intricate cover designs. Fred Meagher, an esteemed illustrator and veteran of World War I, lent his master strokes, portraying aircrafts and war scenes with surgical precision and ineffable dynamism. These images became synonymous with the publication, weaving tales before the pages were even turned.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over time, Flying Aces became a migratory stage for talents transitioning from the pulp magazine industry to mainstream book publication. Luminaries such as Robert Sidney Bowen and Raoul Whitfield propelled their careers forward using the Flying Aces platform, shaping the realm of aviation literature and inspiring an entire generation of aviation story enthusiasts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Clean and compact in its delivery, Flying Aces redefined the spectrum of aviation literature. More than a magazine, it was a beacon for those drawn to the heady blend of history, technology, and human valor found in the world of aviation.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Flying Models
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Flying Models', N'flying-models', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American magazine (1928-2014) dedicated to model aviation enthusiasts, featuring construction guides, reviews, and community events.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flying Models, an American-based publication, was cherished by aviation aficionados and model hobbyists alike for its dedicated coverage of model aviation. The magazine commenced its journey in 1928, delivering knowledge, insights, and inspiration to its readership until it ceased publication in 2014.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s publishing house, Carstens Publications, Inc, known for a diverse array of hobbyist-centric content, was instrumental in transforming Flying Models into a cornerstone within the model aviation community. Throughout its 86-year tenure, the magazine remained faithful to its pivotal role of steering readers through the fascinating world of aerodynamic design, construction techniques, and the mastering of model flight.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Flying Models was widely appreciated for its intricate focus on all niches of model aviation. Be it free-flight, control-line, radio control, or indoor flight models, the magazine proved an invaluable guide. Enriched with comprehensive articles, in-depth reviews, and connective editorials, it encouraged both beginners and veterans to explore the universe of miniature aviation in all its splendid diversity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'An illustrious ensemble of writers and contributors lent their expertise to Flying Models. Esteemed veterans like Don Ross, Walt Mooney, and Nick Ziroli penned articles, guides, and tips, their collective knowledge resonating in each page, guiding readers through the nuances of model flight with precision and passion.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of Flying Models'' distinguishing features was the inclusion of detailed construction plans. These ranged from simple beginner models to complex competition designs. Coupled with comprehensive instructional guides and exquisite photographic accompaniments, these plans provided readers with the complete toolset to bring their aviation models to life.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, the magazine kept its readership updated on the pulse of the model aviation community, with regular features on events, competitions, and showcases across the globe. Its pages were a platform for enthusiasts not only to learn but also to connect, share experiences, and celebrate their achievements.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its lifetime, Flying Models did not just print pages; it shaped experiences. It incubated dreams, nurtured curiosity, and fulfilled the demand for quality knowledge in the realm of model aviation, proving an integral part of the fabric of the entire hobbyist community..{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Football Digest
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Football Digest', N'football-digest', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American publication (1970-present) offering insightful coverage of the NFL through features, team analyses, and game statistics.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Football Digest, founded in 1970 and published by Century Publishing based in Evanston, Illinois, is a premier publication dedicated to the enthralling sport of American football. This compact-sized magazine quickly gained a cherished reputation for its stellar coverage of professional football, with particular attention to the National Football League (NFL).' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s content, uniquely concise and comprehensive, offered readers its signature mix of feature articles, team assessments, player bios, and game statistics. Notable writers within the domain of sports journalism contributed to this esteemed publication, drawing in readers with their vivid storytelling and insightful commentary.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Emerging as a bastion for true football purists, Football Digest presented each issue with a cover story generally profiling a renowned player or a critical turning point in the football season. Additionally, ''Scouting Reports'', an integral section of the magazine, augmented fans'' understanding of team strategies, forging intimate connections between on-field actions and spectators'' perceptions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Known for its accessibility and readability, football Digest stood apart from other sports publications. Its format of recreating the top ten games of the previous month into an engaging ''printcast'' was a fan favorite. These game recaps, written with a passion and precision akin to radio narration, offered readers the excitement of reliving these iconic matches.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'''The Thinking Man''s Guide to Pro Football'' and ''Digest Poll'', were among the other exceptionally popular features. The annual NFL player poll, in particular, drew widespread attention for offering unique insights into player perspectives concerning their peers, coaches, and the sport overall.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'More so than any other sports magazine of its time, Football Digest served as a vibrant chronicle embodying the spirit and tenacity inherent to football. It provided fans with a deeper understanding of the players, teams, and dynamics that constituted the pulse of the National Football League. In doing so, the magazine underscored its role as a torchbearer in the realm of football journalism.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- For Men Only
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'For Men Only', N'for-men-only', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Mid-20th century men''s adventure magazine laden with high-octane narratives, masculine features, and scantily-clad pin-ups.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'For Men Only, a now-defunct magazine, was an American popular men''s periodical that rose to prominence in the mid-20th century. First published in August 1950 by Canam Publishers Sales Corp., the magazine was part of the wave of men''s adventure magazines, also colloquially termed as "the sweats," in postwar America.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s content was a testosterone-fueled melange that encompassed real and fictional tales of peril and bravery, interspersed with eye-catching pin-up illustrations. This peculiar blend of rugged adventure narratives and racy imagery was aimed at sating a burgeoning readership among American men in the throes of post-war cultural metamorphosis.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Known for its sensational storytelling, For Men Only exhibited a remarkable penchant for graphic tales often set against backdrop of wars, expeditions, and explorations. These narratives strove to evoke the primal instincts in readers, often spotlighting scenarios of ''man versus wild'', ''man against man'', and the timeless ''damsel in distress''. These stories, though far from the realm of literary classics, served as prized escapism for an entire generation of men.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Distinguished illustrators of that era, including Norman Saunders, James Bama, and Mort Künstler, graced the magazine''s pages with their vivid and risqué depictions. These artworks were not merely ornamentation; they substantiated the hypermasculine narratives, becoming the visual cornerstone of For Men Only.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine carried a robust tradition of featuring articles on survival skills, sporting accounts, and profiles of inspiring adventurers, further reinforcing its masculine appeal. Yet, on the same token, it bore a distinctive pandering to male fantasies, evidenced in its liberal showcasing of scantily-clad women.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The daring audacity of For Men Only etched an indelible mark in the annals of magazine publishing. Its uninhibited portrayal of men''s fantasies and aspirations came to define a genre and era, offering a unique prism into the shifting paradigm of post-war American masculinity. Even though the ink of the last issue has long dried, its legacy forms a riveting chapter in the annals of American publishing.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Forced Exposure
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Forced Exposure', N'forced-exposure', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American counterculture magazine renowned for eclectic music and arts coverage; also a record label and online distribution platform.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Forced Exposure is a notable counterculture periodical hailing from the United States, renowned for its unique perspective on the music and arts scene. The magazine was founded in 1980 in Boston, Massachusetts by Jimmy Johnson and Byron Coley, two figures ingrained in the alternative music community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Initially distributed as a fanzine, Forced Exposure began its journey spotlighting the burgeoning hardcore punk scene. The magazine rapidly garnered a reputation for its incisive, thorough, and at times confrontational reviews of records and live music. Their extensive coverage provided an in-depth examination of then-underground music scenes, serving as a comprehensive record of an era that transformed the American music landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its early years, Forced Exposure had a pronounced focus on hardcore punk, indie rock, and no wave genres. However, with the passage of time, the magazine expanded its purview to include noise music, experimental rock, and other fringe genres within its review sphere. Additionally, it went beyond strictly musical content, featuring interviews with offbeat film directors, avant-garde visual artists, and underground poets. This eclectic mix of content mirrored the maverick spirit of Forced Exposure, which consistently disregarded mainstream conventions to illuminate the fringe.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine, in addition to its printed issues, also branched into a record label that released music across a range of genres. Although it ceased print publication in 1993, Forced Exposure''s influence has persisted in the digital age. It transitioned to an online platform, offering record distribution, and continues to be a thriving hub for underground and experimental music exploration.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Forced Exposure stands as a testament to the passion for the unconventional. Its significance lies not only in its championing of the underground scene but also in its refusal to conform to mainstream tastes. The magazine''s legacy is one of audacity and rigor, a beacon for innovation within the music and arts domain.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Ford Times
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Ford Times', N'ford-times', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American lifestyle publication issued by Ford Motor Company, featuring travel stories, art, poetry, and news on Ford''s automobile advancements.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ford Times was an iconic American lifestyle magazine that saw its inception in 1908 under the aegis of the Ford Motor Company. Commissioned to be published monthly, the magazine was originally initated as a medium for the company to reach out to its employees and automobile customers, providing them with up-to-date company news and happenings. However, Ford Times soon evolved beyond specific company concerns to encompass a broader view of American life, culture, and motoring.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The pages of Ford Times were marked by a captivating blend of travel stories, humor pieces, poetry, recipes, and striking illustrations, many of which were created by renowned artists of the time. The magazine also offered recommendations for road trips. Such well-rounded content and its artful presentation set Ford Times apart as more than just an industry-specific publication; it stood as an illustrated guide to the mid-20th-century American lifestyle and leisure, a visual treat that resonated with a wide audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ford Times'' unmatched characterization and commitment to art had a significant bearing on its appeal. Through engaging regular features and memorable cover designs, it carved a niche for itself in the publishing world. It was a medium where art met industry, and the charm of the magazine lay in just that - its ability to balance commercial pursuits and creative aesthetics. Ford Times enlisted the expertise of eminent painters and illustrators like Charley Harper, a modernist artist known for his distinctive wildlife illustrations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also kept loyal Ford customers apprised of the company''s latest releases, improvements, and technological advancements. It served as a regular communication node between the Ford Motor Company and its customer base, maintaining a human touch that went well above and afar the roles assumed by typical company bulletins.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Whilst Ford Times ceased publication in 1993, almost 85 years since its commencement, the legacy it leaves behind is anything but ordinary. The magazine''s multi-faceted and broad-based approach to content, coupled with its artistic endeavor, makes it a noteworthy archive of American cultural history and automobile advancement.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Forest and Stream,
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Forest and Stream,', N'forest-and-stream,', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription 19th-century American outdoor magazine emphasizing hunting, fishing, and conservation; instrumental in the inception of Audubon Society.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Forest and Stream, dating back to its establishment in 1873, evolved as a significant American publication in the realms of hunting, fishing, and outdoor activities. The magazine''s roots are intertwined with the environmental conservation movement, as it projected a spirit of appreciation for nature, wildlife, and the joy that outdoor adventures lend to the American way of life.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Helmed by Charles Hallock, an avid angler and conservationist, Forest and Stream served as a platform to galvanize wilderness lovers, impart outdoor skills, and disseminate news and anecdotes of hunting and fishing exploits. Its columns, brimming with rich descriptions and stories on outdoor pursuits, distinguished the magazine as a premium source of knowledge and entertainment for its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although the content was largely defined by hunting and fishing along with other outdoor activities, Forest and Stream stood firmly as an advocate for wildlife protection and natural resource sustainability. Its editorial narratives often focused on environmental conservation issues, underscoring the necessity for regulated hunting and sustainable fishing practices.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The scope of Forest and Stream extended beyond outdoor leisure and activism, reaching into the scientific and literary realms. With content curated from the writings of natural scientists, practitioners, and nature enthusiasts, the publication offered myriad perspectives on America''s natural heritage. Renowned naturalists like George Bird Grinnell, who served as the editor of the magazine, frequently graced its pages with their contributions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also played a seminal role in the inception of conservation organizations. A notable example is the Audubon Society, an early advocate for the preservation of birds and their habitats, which found its foundations in the pages of Forest and Stream.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As such, Forest and Stream commanded a unique position in late 19th and early 20th century American media. Catering to a well-defined demographic with a synergy of outdoor recreation and environmental stewardship, it underscored the responsible enjoyment of nature''s bounty as an integral part of American life. Its legacy therefore, extends beyond mere publishing, and threads into the tapestry of American natural conservation history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Fortune Small Business
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Fortune Small Business', N'fortune-small-business ', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American publication focused on small business trends, management, and entrepreneur success stories; ceased print in 2009.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Fortune Small Business (FSB), a proud sibling publication to the titan of business journalism Fortune Magazine, catered explicitly to the unique needs and interests of small business owners across the United States. From the year of its inception in 1991, until it ceased its print issue in 2009, FSB served as a vital resource, illuminating the entrepreneurial landscape with timely, in-depth information and insightful analysis.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established by the eminent Time Inc., FSB proffered its readers a wealth of knowledge on various facets of small business management, encompassing sectors as diverse as manufacturing to technology and retail. Its content was characterized by a blend of feature stories, strategic advice, and profiles of successful entrepreneurs, striking a careful balance between practicality and inspiration.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine stood distinguished for its focus on both macroeconomic trends and micro-level business strategies, thereby evenhandedly serving the interests of budding entrepreneurs and established business owners. FSB’s comprehensive industry reports were particularly valued for the clarity they provided on complex economic dynamics affecting small businesses.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, FSB perpetuated its commitment to budding innovation by publishing an annual list of top innovative companies. Known as the "FSB 100," this list coalesced around thriving businesses that demonstrated significant innovation, providing readers with exemplary models of entrepreneurial success.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The sections titled "The Mogul Next Door" and "Innovation Nation" were staples of FSB''s strong editorial lineup, each dealing with different aspects of the small business ecosystem. While "The Mogul Next Door” painted intimate portraits of successful neighborhood entrepreneurs, “Innovation Nation” showcased pioneers at the forefront of technological and service-oriented breakthroughs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'FSB, by transforming small scale narratives into compelling conversations, successfully engaged a broad readership spanning business leaders, policymakers, and general business enthusiasts. Despite its culmination as a print publication in December 2009, it etched an indelible mark on the landscape of business publications. Now united with CNNMoney.com, the spirit of FSB continues to thrive in the digital vein, further extending its pivotal role in fanning the sparks of entrepreneurial spirit in America.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Forum
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Forum', N'the-forum', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Historic U.S. magazine (1885-1993) promoting intellectual discourse; published Mark Twain among others; known for open debate format.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Forum, a United States-based periodical of high repute, commenced its print journey in 1885 and spanned over a century, highly influential in disseminating critical intellectual discourse. Renowned for its commitment to candid, unrestricted discussion, the magazine was aptly named The Forum, implying an open space for public debate and scholastic exchange.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Co-founded by the illustrious partnership of Franklin H. Hooper and Isaac Lea, The Forum embarked on a mission to stimulate intellectual curiosity and provoke thought, while navigating the complex political, societal, and cultural landscapes. With its definite focus on long-form journalism, the magazine offered a thoughtful refuge from the clutter of short, focused news streams.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Forum embraced a broad spectrum of subject matter, encompassing politics, economics, culture, science, and the arts. The depth and breadth of its content rendered it a cherished intellectual companion among scholars, politicians, and the learned public. Its inclusive approach, inviting opinion and analysis from all corners of society, marked it as a democratic space in the world of magazines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A hallmark of The Forum was its willingness to publish dissenting viewpoints, resulting in vibrant dialogues within its pages. Its dedication to this principle led to the feature of prominent figures across the social and political spectrum, ensuring a balance of contrasting perspectives on critical issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notable in its legacy, The Forum was among the few select platforms that published famed author Mark Twain''s later works. Other distinguished contributors include eminent figures such as Woodrow Wilson, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, and Theodore Roosevelt, each leaving their indelible mark on the magazine’s intellectual fabric.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite multiple ownership changes and editorial tweaks, The Forum remained steadfast in its fundamental aim - to encourage enlightened discussion on pertinent issues. Over its long run, the publication evolved in format, transitioning from a hardcover magazine to a paperback periodical.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Finally, after 108 years, The Forum ceased publication in 1993. However, its formidable legacy as a crucible of intellectual exchange continues to illuminate the annals of American journalistic history. Its profound emphasis on open discussion, intellectual rigor, and diverse viewpoints has left an everlasting impact on the larger journalistic landscape.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Freedomways
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Freedomways', N'freedomways', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American quarterly (1961-1985) illuminating African American struggle and civil rights; included works from Alice Walker, Langston Hughes.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Freedomways, an influential American quarterly periodical, emerged in the volatile socio-political climate of 1961 as a beacon of African-American intellectualism and activist thought. It continued its relentless stride in championing civil rights dialogue and discourse until its final issue in 1985.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Created amidst the tumultuous Civil Rights era, Freedomways sought to illuminate the struggle of African Americans against racial injustice. A project shaped by the dedicated collaboration of W.E.B. Du Bois, famed black scholar, and Esther Cooper Jackson and Shirley Graham Du Bois, its founding editors, the journal emerged as a prominent platform for deepening the awareness and understanding of racial equality issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine, unique in its focus, united scholars, activists, and artists from the African American community and beyond, thereby amplifying minority voices and perspectives. It made an indelible mark in encouraging and fostering literature and art that represented the African American experience, thus shedding light on an oft-overlooked aspect of American society.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While invariably intertwined with the cause of racial equality, Freedomways broadened its scope beyond the American borders, underscoring the interconnection of the African American struggle with Pan-Africanism, the international labor movement, and the global anti-colonial struggle. This comprehensive approach allowed it to narrate the shared experiences of oppression and resistance across countries and cultures.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Famed literary personalities like Alice Walker and Langston Hughes found a congenial platform in Freedomways to express their creative prowess, their works unveiling the African American context and contributing to a more nuanced understanding of collective racial justice. The magazine also featured an impressive line-up of political figures who conveyed their vision for racial equality within its pages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Freedomways'' remarkable commitment to voicing the perspectives of racial minorities, stimulating intellectual discourse, and advocating social justice maintained its relevance across the globe. It persistently stood as a testament to the inextricable link between knowledge, creativity, and the enduring struggle for racial equality. The magazine may have ceased publication, but its impact is an inalienable aspect of journalistic and intellectual history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Freshmen Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Freshmen Magazine', N'freshmen-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American monthly magazine (1982-2009) focused on gay lifestyle and erotica, also addressing socio-political issues in the LGBTQ+ community.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Freshmen, an American monthly magazine, first dawned in the publishing scene in 1982, forging a distinct image in print media that catered specifically to a gay audience. Published by Specialty Publications, a branch of LPI Media, this periodical upheld a unique and compelling niche, contributing significantly to gay cultural dialogue and representation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With an overarching aim to celebrate and highlight the diversity of gay culture and lifestyle, Freshmen offered its readers an immersive exploration of gay narratives, experiences, and perspectives. The magazine''s striking portrayal of youthful vibrancy echoed throughout its pages, creating a resonant platform for myriad voices within the gay community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinct features of Freshmen was its commitment to unmasking authentic gay experiences and narratives. Its in-depth interviews and candid profiles of various personalities provided the readers a rare collective insight into the individual and shared experiences of the gay community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Not merely relegated to the portrayal of gay life, Freshmen also played a monumental role in the annals of gay erotica, boasting a substantial readership drawn by its photographic spreads. It elegantly juggled its role as a charted sector for gay erotica whilst simultaneously promoting a broader sense of community, understanding, and acceptance of gay culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, the magazine did not shy away from delving into serious discussions pertaining to AIDS, gay rights, societal acceptance, and ongoing legislative battles pertinent to the LGBTQ+ community. By doing so, Freshmen cemented its reputation as not merely an adult publication but a significant catalyst for discourse on important socio-political issues affecting its target readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its years of publication, Freshmen remained a steadfast beacon in gay literature, carving out a unique landscape where numerous identities, narratives, and viewpoints melded together, epitomizing the vibrant and diverse spectrum of gay culture. Its role in setting a narrative stage that firmly encapsulated the true color of the gay community has etched it incontestably into the fabric of LGBTQ+ cultural history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Friendship and Freedom
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Friendship and Freedom', N'friendship-and-freedom', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription 1921 American magazine by YWCA fostering interracial dialogue and understanding, promoting racial harmony in the era of segregation.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Friendship and Freedom, a groundbreaking publication of significant import, embarked upon capturing the attention of the American reading audience in 1921. Published by the Young Women''s Christian Association (YWCA), it traversed a pioneering path, serving as a beacon of allyship for Black and white women in the pursuit of racial equality.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Instigating crucial dialogue between different racial groups, Friendship and Freedom emerged as a compelling voice in the push for racial harmony during the pivotal era of the 1920s. It unfolded an unpreceded bridge of communication, aiming to disintegrate the prevalent racial barriers that marred the American landscape of the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Every issue of Friendship and Freedom bore testimony to resolute efforts in fostering interracial understanding. This was remarkably evident through its variety of articles, personal narratives, poetry, and news briefs. The content represented a diverse array of voices, standing as a testament to the shared aspiration of racial unity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another crucial stride that Friendship and Freedom undertook was its explicit attention towards the acknowledgement and understanding of the ''Negro problem.'' Through a series of enlightening features and discussions, the magazine strove to sensitize its primarily white readership about the deplorable racial struggles faced by their Black counterparts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The editors of Friendship and Freedom employed a unique editorial tactic. Rather than claim a firm stance on particular issues, they utilized a more subtle approach, channeling their agenda through illuminating narratives, thought-provoking commentaries, and discrete, symbolic illustrations. The objective was to inspire self-reflection and foster individual interpretation among the readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also unabashedly provided a steady platform for the display of Black excellence. It routinely honored Black contributors and highlighted their accomplishments in various arenas - education, arts and literature, women''s rights, and civil rights advocacy. Such representation worked towards dismantling racial stereotypes and cultivating respect and appreciation for Black culture and intellect.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although Friendship and Freedom was only in circulation for under a year, its influence permeates the annals of American periodical history for its audacious pursuit of racial harmony. Indeed, its legacy remains, serving as a tantalizing mirror to an era of crucial racial discourse and marking an early endeavor towards forging a path of racial understanding and unity in America.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- FringeWare Review
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'FringeWare Review', N'fringeware-review', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription 1992-1998 magazine exploring the confluence of counterculture and cyberculture, with focus on fringe, marginalized ideas and phenomena.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'FringeWare Review, a provocative and pioneering publication, commenced its delectable journey into the creative stratosphere in 1992. This unique piece of print was conceived and nurtured by Paco Nathan and Mondo 2000 alum Gareth Branwyn. As a platform, FringeWare Review strived to meld counterculture and computer subculture into a tantalizing fusion, providing thought-provoking content to the intrigued audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Breaking the conventional dimensions of magazine themes, FringeWare Review reveled in the unconventional. It focused on cyberculture, while exploring fringe, marginalized ideas and phenomena, thereby enriching the cultural lexicon. The magazine''s content ranged from articles on cyberpunk to visual culture, transgressive sexuality to techno-anarchy. Each edition convincingly established the publication as a galvanizing forum of intellectual discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Promoting an amalgamation of high-tech and art, FringeWare Review sought to expose the readership to eccentricities and the unexplored facets of culture, integrating marginal and mainstream narratives in each issue. The magazine offered an eclectic mix of persona and topics, unabashedly confronting taboo subjects and veiled constructs of society with equal vigor and charm.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Complementing the magazine''s cutting-edge textual content was its striking visual components. Its pages invited the eyes with a surreal blend of imagery, oscillating between the bizarre, the outlandish, and the profoundly ingenious. The aesthetic sensibilities of FringeWare Review augmented its intellectual appeal, successfully immersing its audience within its captivating world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'FringeWare Review also served as the namesake of a concurrently-operating online store, FringeWare, that dealt in offbeat products, eccentric literature, and unconventional software. The synergistic existence of the magazine with the online store made FringeWare a one-of-its-kind endeavor, shaking up the realms of printed and digital distribution.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s pages contained refreshing, idiosyncratically delivered perspectives, combining academic rigor with underground cultural meditations. All of these were intricately woven within the bimonthly issues, making FringeWare Review an illuminated tapestry of cyberculture and counterculture exploration.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Within its brief existence from 1992 to 1998, FringeWare Review carved out a singular niche for itself within the printed media landscape. By spotlighting the fringe, it informed, quested, and pushed boundaries, crafting an unforgettable legacy within the annals of alternative print culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Frontiers Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Frontiers Magazine', N'frontiers-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Biweekly LGBTQ+ publication active from 1981-2016, focusing on rights advocacy, cultural commentary, and community connectivity.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Frontiers, a trailblazer in the field of LGBTQ+ journalism, originated amid the vibrant societal turbulence of 1981 Los Angeles. Conceived by the enterprising minds of Bob Craig and David Stern, this biweekly publication endeavored to provide a voice for the often marginalized LGBTQ+ community and swiftly became synonymous with the struggle for rights and acceptance, providing a beacon for the progressive cause.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Frontiers represented a powerful and candid platform that underscored the socio-political realities, triumphs, and tribulations of the LGBTQ+ community. The magazine served as a critical link between the constantly evolving public sentiment and the ground-level realities within the community, lending invaluable insights into a wide array of topics concerning human rights, sexuality, health, politics, and culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Broad in its scope, yet laser-focused in its approach, Frontiers navigated myriad subjects. Detailing the community''s battles with HIV/AIDS, advocating for same-sex marriage rights, highlighting the fight for broader societal acceptance, and giving exposure to emerging LGBTQ+ artists and their works, the magazine was unyielding in its mission, earning its place as a pivotal player in local and national dialogues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to probing narratives and articles, Frontiers bolstered its content with exquisite visual dimensions. Unafraid to illuminate the full spectrum of LGBTQ+ lifestyles, portraits of real individuals paired with spotlight features on notable personalities were chronicled amidst a cascade of colorful photography, contributing to the magazine''s overarching narrative of diversity and authenticity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Distinct from other LGBTQ+ publications of its time, Frontiers nurtured a symbiotic relationship with its audience, harnessing reader-generated content to drive dialogues. The magazine''s acclaimed ''Letters to the Editor'' section served as a cherished conduit for readers to voice their opinions, share personal narratives, and dialogue with fellow members of the community. This interplay fostered a sense of belonging, fortifying Frontiers'' identity as a communal platform.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond its editorial accomplishments, Frontiers was commendable in its commitment to the business side of publishing. It aggressively pursued advertising relationships with prominent LGBTQ+ friendly businesses, thereby sustaining its financial stability in an era when LGBTQ+ publications often struggled to remain viable.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'From its inception in 1981 until ceasing publication in 2016, Frontiers was much more than a magazine - it was an instrument of discourse, a microphone for the voiceless, and a testament to the resilience and evolution of the LGBTQ+ community throughout changing times. Its indelible legacy remains etched into the annals of advocacy journalism.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Fuji Flyer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Fuji Flyer', N'fuji-flyer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A prestigious Japanese aviation publication providing in-depth industry insights since 1982.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Fuji Flyer" (富士フライヤー) is a prestigious Japanese publication that has garnered recognition and respect in its numerous years of operation. It has been an instrumental source of airborne and aviation content, establishing itself as a significant influence in global aviation discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'First published in 1982, "Fuji Flyer," whose native name, 富士フライヤー, constitutes a homonym to Japan''s iconic Mt. Fuji, has been an indomitable purveyor of aviation knowledge. The magazine is renowned for its comprehensive focus on a broad spectrum of topics within the realm of air transport, aviation technology, and affiliated industries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'For the non-Japanese world, Fuji Flyer Magazine acquires an attribute of authenticity, providing a cultural perspective on the aviation industry, with a decidedly Japanese tinge. Each monthly issue incorporates meticulously researched articles, industry news, expert interviews, and aircraft reviews. The Fuji Flyer showcases the East Asian stance on flying and aircraft, helping to diversify the typically western-centric aviation narrative.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Headquartered in Tokyo, "Fuji Flyer" renders encyclopedic knowledge as it fuses technical complexities with mainstream readability. Its English-translated variant, while faithfully retaining its cognitive depth, has proven immensely appealing to a global readership. As a testament to its international reach and reputation, "Fuji Flyer" is widely accessible in airports and major bookstores across continents.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, the magazine hosts an array of distinguished writing talents ranging from aircraft engineers to experienced pilots, and flight enthusiasts. This pool of diverse contributors further escalates its credibility, rendering it a veritable platform for the exchange of ground-breaking ideas and the latest breakthroughs in aviation technology.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With its quintessential Japanese precision, the editorial team of "Fuji Flyer" diligently adheres to stringent fact-checking procedures, ensuring that every piece of content is accurate, informative, and up-to-date. The magazine''s vast and ardent readership relies on this unwavering commitment, resulting in an influential voice in the expansive and perpetually evolving realm of aviation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The legacy of the "Fuji Flyer" stands as a beacon amongst aviation literature. Its unique lexicon of air travel, technology, and industry trends provides immediate relevance for its devout readership and new enthusiasts alike, forging a rich and respected narrative within global aviation discourse.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Fur Worker
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Fur Worker', N'the-fur-worker', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription German-originated American periodical for fur industry professionals, featuring industry news, artisan advice, and market trends.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"The Fur Worker," (Der Pelzarbeiter) an eminent American periodical primarily published in German, has held a distinguished position in the fur industry''s literature since its inception. Having underpinned various transitions within the trade, from artisanship to mechanization, the publication''s documentation provides valued discernment into the socio-economic undercurrents of North America''s fur industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Making its debut in the year 1885 with the aim of promoting and educating fur workers in the United States and beyond, "The Fur Worker," initially published solely in German as "Der Pelzarbeiter," became a juggernaut for the exchange of practices, trends, and legislation related to the fur industry. Its cross-continental pioneering role innately makes it a linchpin offering deep insights about the interplay of fashion, economy, and society.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is headquartered in New York, once considered the epicenter of fur trade during the 20th century. This strategically located base has allowed "The Fur Worker" a firsthand perspective on the significant developments within the industry, enabling it to capture the dynamics of the market with operose detail.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"The Fur Worker" stands out for its comprehensive engagement with the fur industry''s multifaceted composition. Each edition not only consists of industry news and regulatory updates, but it also offers practical advice columns for artisans. Furthermore, the forum sheds light on advancements in technology and new techniques in fur processing, thereby maintaining its relevancy amidst the fur industry''s metamorphosis.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has succeeded in binding a diverse array of writers under its name, from accomplished fur designers to industry analysts. This diverse catalog of contributors enriches the publication''s reputation, providing thought-leadership and factual representation of the industry''s landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the notable characteristics of "The Fur Worker" is its meticulous adherence to the principles of journalistic integrity. The magazine consistently ensures the accuracy and erudition of each article, with a strict lean towards presenting an unbiased portrayal of the industry at large. This steadfast commitment to factual representation enhances the publication''s credibility, situating it as a respected bastion in the fur trade discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Delighting in the challenge of demystifying a globally significant yet understudied industry, the legacy of "The Fur Worker" exists as a vital continuum within fur trade literature. Its potent blend of trade development updates, artisan insights, and market predictions proffer an unrivaled understanding of the fur industry''s historical contour and its future trajectories.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Furniture Style
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Furniture Style', N'furniture-style', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American periodical for interior design industry, covering furniture trends, market updates, and purchasing advice.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Furniture Style," is a highly regarded American periodical that constitutes a remarkable presence within the realm of interior design, specifically tailored to the furniture industry. Documenting various design movements and innovations, it has become a pivotal publication for professionals, enthusiasts, and industry insiders.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established in 1997, "Furniture Style" addresses a multitude of interests, built upon the orchestrations of prominent decorators, artists, and manufacturers. It serves as a platform for the discussions of furniture trends, industry updates, and sound advice on purchasing decisions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The headquarters of "Furniture Style," nestled in the fast-paced city of Chicago, presents a strategic vantage point that encapsulates the dynamic advances within the furniture industry. This positioning enables the magazine to provide its readership with an encompassing view of national and international trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Furniture Style" effectively communicates the many layers of the furniture industry. Every issue features industry news and commentary, reviews of furniture collections, showcases of upcoming designers, and practical advice for furniture retailing. It serves as a practical and inspiring repository for the furniture marketplace.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A key strength of "Furniture Style" lies in its diverse authorship. Its array of contributors ranges from renowned interior designers to astute industry analysts offering a comprehensive, multi-faceted perspective to its readers. This diversity ensures a rich content mix, unique perspectives, and a comprehensive overview of the industry''s landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Consistently displaying high standards of journalistic integrity, "Furniture Style" adheres closely to the accuracy of facts and impartiality of viewpoint. It maintains this commitment, providing its readership with trustworthy and informative content about the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In all, "Furniture Style" sits at the forefront of the furniture industry''s publications, embodying a renowned touchstone for designers, manufacturers, and enthusiasts alike. Commanding a compelling mix of design trends, market analysis, and retail advice, this etalon remains a force to be reckoned with amidst furniture trade literature, serving as a singularly insightful guide to the larger discourse of the industry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Fusion Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Fusion Magazine', N'fusion-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American music periodical highlighting wide-ranging genres, featuring interviews, album reviews, and industry insights.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Fusion" is an esteemed American music magazine, prominently situated in the intersection of musical genres. Since its inception in 1967, it has been offering an enlightening perspective on the world of music, primarily within the realm of rock, but with a distinctive appreciation for the eclectic blend of genres.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Anchored in Boston, Massachusetts, "Fusion" presents itself as a medium of interaction between the creators and audience. The magazine is highly regarded for its insightful commentary, the exploration of various music styles, and the promotion of emerging talents.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With its staunch dedication to the binding versatility of music, "Fusion" diligently covers a blend of genres, from Rock to Jazz, Blues to Classical, Folk to Experimental, making it a dynamic and diverse platform for music discussion. Each issue brings a repertoire of features, including comprehensive interviews, album reviews, and stories that delve into the world of artists across the spectrum.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The journalistic integrity that "Fusion" upholds is one of its hallmarks. Its rich palette of contributors includes renowned music critics, industry insiders, and passionate aficionados. Their collective wisdom forms the backbone of the magazine, empowering insightful narratives and informed critiques.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Fusion" consistently chronicles the evolution of music, identifying trends, highlighting achievements, and engaging with issues relevant to the industry. Among its memorable pages, one may expect the discovery of a fresh indie band, the celebration of an album anniversary of an established artist, or a dissection of an avant-garde music performance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Embedded within its creative ethos is a commitment to both mainstream and counterculture, documenting celebrated classics and groundbreaking innovations side by side. The result is a fine balance that reflects the shifting paradigms of the music world while paying homage to its roots.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Fusion," with its incisive commentary and eclectic coverage, has cemented its place as a vital resource for avid music lovers and industry professionals, expanding horizons, and shaping conversations in the musical landscape. It remains a beacon of the contemporary music scene, shining a light on the past, present, and future of music in its manifold forms.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Future Sex
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Future Sex', N'future-Sex-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Publication exploring intersection of technology and sexuality, fostering dialogue on intimacy and relationships in the digital age.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Future Sex", an avant-garde digital and print publication, entered the media sphere in 2014, presenting a unique exploration into sexuality and technology. The magazine''s core ethos revolves around the understanding and portrayal of how these two integral facets of human existence harmonize in the modern world. Originally published in Berlin, Germany, "Future Sex" offers a bold, contemporary perspective on intimate issues, presented through a variety of multimedia formats.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Future Sex" challenges traditional norms and fosters a dialogue about the intersection of technology, intimacy, and personal relationships. Striving for inclusivity, the magazine covers a broad spectrum of topics related to sexuality, making its content appealing to a broad, diverse readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine distinguishes itself with its innovative design and thought-provoking content, including interviews, op-eds, and features focused on the ever-evolving landscape of human intimacy in the modern world. From investigations into virtual reality and sex, to features on sex robots and adult applications, "Future Sex" asks its readership to contemplate what may lie on the horizon.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Falling under the umbrella of ethical journalism, "Future Sex" takes great care to approach sensitive topics with due respect, aiming to inform and enlighten without crossing boundaries of propriety. Its content includes contributions from some of the industry''s top writers, academicians, and experts in the field of technology and intimacy.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is lauded for not shying away from challenging discussions and embracing a philosophy that encourages open dialogue about the future of sex. Despite its relative newness, its provocative, yet insightful content has successfully pushed "Future Sex" into the limelight, transforming it into an influential voice within the industry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Gadfly Online
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Gadfly Online', N'gadfly-online', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Web-based and annual print publication exploring culture, politics, and society through intellectual, provocative content.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Gadfly Online, a provocative and influential publication, entered the media landscape in 1997, swiftly establishing itself as an integral platform for intellectual discourse. Functioning as a catalyst for engaging and thought-provoking dialogues, Gadfly Online has become renowned for its fearless exploration of culture, politics, and society.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded by Jeremy Landau and Jared Brown, the magazine operates out of Lawrence, Kansas and boasts a fervent readership that extends well beyond its geographical origins. While primarily known for its web presence, Gadfly Online also manifests in annual print formats, curating a compilation of the most highly-acclaimed articles of the year.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine is distinguished by its dedication to interweaving nuanced and intellectual analysis with topical relevance. Its uncompromising and evocative content, posed through features, interviews, and opinion pieces, paints the socio-political landscape with stark recognition and fierce boldness. Art, politics, culture, and their intertwined dynamics serve as the primary foci of Gadfly Online''s inquiries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The success of Gadfly Online lies not merely in its edifying content, but also in its efforts to bring lesser-known artists, musicians, writers, and political figures to the foreground. By embracing voices that veer away from the mainstream, Gadfly Online proactively contributes to an egalitarian media ecosystem.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With a team of seasoned editors and ardent contributors, Gadfly Online successfully explores the cultural fabric of contemporary society. It stimulates conversations that push boundaries, challenge norms, and, ultimately, inform its readers on a wide spectrum of topics, fostering a conscientious and engaged readership.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Gaited Horse
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Gaited Horse', N'the-gaited-horse', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription North American publication dedicated to non-trotting horse breeds, focusing on care, training, health, and equestrian events.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"The Gaited Horse", a specialized North American publication, came into existence with the core aim of catering to the informational needs of aficionados and enthusiasts of naturally gaited horses. Since its inception, it has become a beacon of knowledge and insight, focusing particularly on non-trotting horse breeds.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s mandate encompasses myriad facets of gaited horse care, training, health, and riding techniques. It opens up pathways for discourse about the intricacies, beauty, and distinctions of these equine types, encouraging a better understanding of such unique breeds. The Gaited Horse Magazine illustrates and examines the variances across different breeds, such as Icelandic horses, Paso Finos, Tennessee Walking Horses, and many more.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With a hands-on, practical approach, "The Gaited Horse" contains articles by accomplished veterinarians, renowned trainers, and industry professionals. This commitment to quality content ensures that readers receive actionable and helpful advice, enabling them to improve their personal practice of horsemanship.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also upholds notable coverage of various gaited horse shows, exhibitions, and competitions across North America, chronicling key performances along with expert analysis of the presented gaits. This replication of the vibrant equestrian scene not only informs readers, but it also solidifies the magazine''s celebration of the gaited horse community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True to its niche specialization, "The Gaited Horse" has become a trusted resource, a conduit for invaluable knowledge about gaited horse breeds. It continues to elevate generations of horse lovers'' understanding while showcasing the sheer variety and unique qualities inherent in these versatile equine breeds.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Galaxy
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Galaxy', N'the-galaxy', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription 19th-century U.S. periodical featuring serialized novels, short stories, essays, and scientific, historical, social discourse.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"The Galaxy", a highly regarded and influential periodical, was a cornerstone of American literary and sociopolitical culture during the latter half of the 19th century. Making its debut in 1866, the magazine was a potent platform for serialized novels, captivating short stories, astute essays, and critical editorial narratives. Throughout its existence, it stood as a testament to the richness and versatility of American intellectual thought and creative prowess.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Carving out a niche amidst other contemporary publications, "The Galaxy" was established under the co-editorship of William Conant Church, the seasoned journalist, and his brother Francis P. Church, the equally accomplished editor. Their editorial finesse turned it into a beacon for progressive and informed discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notable authors such as Mark Twain, Anthony Trollope, and Rebecca Harding Davis graced its covers, lending credence to the publication''s reputation as a destination for established literary figures. Twain''s "Memories of California and the Pacific" and Harding Davis'' collected essays are memorable instances of the magazine''s offerings.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its literary prowess, "The Galaxy" showcased essays dealing with scientific, historical, and social topics generating intellectual curiosity among its readers. Its "Scientific Miscellany" section was an open nod to enlightenment ideals, advocating for scientific temperance amidst existing readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Altogether, "The Galaxy" played a significant role in shaping the American literary and intellectual landscape. The magazine''s legacy carries potent remnants of the cultural transformation and intellectual evolution that it contributed to and continues to inspire literary scholars in understanding the dynamism of the 19th century''s cultural milieu.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Game Developer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Game Developer', N'game-developer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Industry-oriented publication (1994-2013) providing comprehensive analysis and insider perspectives on video game development.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Game Developer" magazine emerged in the late 20th century as a premier publication focused on the burgeoning video game industry. Established in 1994 by Miller Freeman, inc., under the editorial direction of industry veterans, the magazine quickly became an indispensable resource for both established professionals and aspiring newcomers in the field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Renowned for its in-depth analysis, "Game Developer" chronicled the evolution of video game design and development, including technical nuances, artistic techniques, and the complexity of the business landscape within the gaming industry. It was instrumental in bridging the chasm between game design theory and practical development, offering invaluable insights and bridging the gap between conceptualizing and creating innovative games.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of the "Game Developer" delved deep into the many facets of the industry, from interviews with leading game developers to detailed postmortems of popular games. The magazine also regularly featured articles on the latest technological advancements, programming techniques, game design methodologies, and industry trends. Notably, the magazine recognized and celebrated the achievements and innovations within the gaming sector through its annual Game Developers Choice Awards.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Game Developer’s" dedication to high-quality content, created by industry insiders, helped shape the conversations surrounding video game design. Readers benefited greatly from lessons learned by top professionals in the field, enriching their understanding of the industry and contributing to the magazine’s status as a revered resource.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Albeit no longer in print as of 2013, the magazine''s legacy lives on in its digital twin - the Gamasutra website. The influence of "Game Developer" remains a testament to its success in capturing and fostering the dynamic, creative spirit of the video game industry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Game Players
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Game Players', N'game-players', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Defunct American gaming magazine (1989-1998) known for comprehensive console game coverage and irreverent tone.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Game Players" is a defunct American bimonthly video game magazine that carved a unique place in gaming literature during the digital entertainment explosion of the late 20th century. Founded in 1989 by Robert Lock, under Signal Research, the magazine was dedicated to providing comprehensive coverage on console gaming culture, including news, previews, reviews, and other related content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The initial focus of "Game Players" was squarely on the then-popular Nintendo platforms, including the Nintendo Entertainment System and the Game Boy, but with the launch of Sega''s Genesis system, the magazine expanded its coverage. In 1991, the publication was renamed "Game Players Sega and Nintendo Guide", a reflection of its inclusive editorial coverage. By the mid-1990s, as Sony and other manufacturers entered the market, "Game Players" broadened its scope to cover all major gaming systems.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Known for its irreverent editorial tone and in-depth reviews, "Game Players" garnered a wide readership with its attention to qualitative content. Iconic sections in the magazine included features on strategies and cheats, as well as Game Doctor, a column addressing the readers'' gaming issues with an informal, cheeky dialogue. Simultaneously, it maintained a strong focus on in-depth reviews and previews, ensuring that readers were well-informed about the latest releases.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout the 1990s, "Game Players" went through several name changes and evolutions, reflecting not only changing market dynamics but also different editorial management and ownerships. In 1996, it was morphed into Ultra Game Players. Ultimately, in 1998, it transformed into Game Buyer, before all publication was ceased by Imagine Media.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its years of publication, "Game Players" played a central role in shaping the landscape of video game journalism. Its extensive coverage and distinct voice marked it as a vital chronicle of an industry in rapid evolution, capturing the rich tapestry of the video game culture of its time.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Games Unplugged
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Games Unplugged', N'games-unplugged', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American magazine (2000-2002) dedicated to board games, card games, tabletop role-playing, and miniature war games.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"Games Unplugged" was an American monthly magazine, primarily focused on the coverage of analogue or non-electronic games. Established in 2000, under the initial publisher, Fast Forward Entertainment, the magazine held a distinctive niche within the gaming literature, centering on traditional gaming forms amidst a global shift towards digital recreation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication''s thematic focus encompassed the broad realm of non-digital gaming, including board games, card games, tabletop role-playing games, and miniature war gaming. Not only did it introduce new games to its readers, but the magazine also offered intriguing gameplay strategies, insightful industry news, engaging interviews with game creators and designers, as well as comprehensive reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The salient feature of "Games Unplugged" was its emphasis on the communal aspect of traditional gaming forms, underscoring the social interactions and competitive camaraderie they offered in contrast to their digital counterparts. The magazine effectively communicated the charm of such gameplay, thus garnering the appreciation of enthusiasts who admired the elaborate mechanics and tangible nature of these style of games.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of content structure, "Games Unplugged" incorporated a blend of regular columns, focused features, and special theme issues. Key columns included previews of upcoming games and reviews of current ones, while features typically comprised in-depth interviews with industry luminaries or game profiles. Thematic issues were either centered around a specific game genre or timed with significant industry events, thereby curating tailored and relevant content for its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite receiving acclaim from the traditional gaming community for its content diversity and quality, "Games Unplugged", however, was short-lived. Its final issue was published in 2002. Despite its brief tenure, the magazine left an enduring legacy, as it showcased the ongoing vitality and creative innovation within the realm of non-electronic gaming during an era of digital predominance.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The GAO Journal
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The GAO Journal', N'the-gao-journal', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription U.S. Government Accountability Office''s publication from 1981 to 1993, focusing on policy, financial management and performance metrics.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "GAO Journal" was a significant publication by the United States Government Accountability Office, providing a crucial platform for conveying the agency''s research findings and operational insights to the public. Initiated in 1981, it served as an instrumental resource to inform government, academia, and individuals about the practical aspects of policy implementation, financial management, and performance measurement at the federal level.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The unique selling proposition of the "GAO Journal" lay in its authoritative and unbiased content. The publication was lauded for its effectiveness in unpacking complex matters related to government accountability and operations, thereby making such information accessible to a broader audience. It efficiently straddled the line between being academic yet prying, thereby asserting its distinguishing position among other government strategy journals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Its thematic spectrum covered a wide range of topics central to government performance and accountability, sourced from GAO''s extensive audit, evaluations, and investigative endeavours. The topics encompassed diverse domains such as healthcare, defense, education, fiscal management, and regulation, along with cross-cutting government reform issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Structurally, the "GAO Journal" combined both broad-based analysis pieces and in-depth explorations of specific subjects. These included interviews with key stakeholders, perspectives from GAO''s senior leaders, feature stories around critical issues, and analytical insights derived from GAO''s audit and investigative work. Furthermore, it often cast a spotlight on the GAO''s methodological approaches to tackling complicated issues of governmental performance measurement and evaluation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'This publication was pivotal in furnishing a deeper understanding of the intricacies and challenges associated with government operations at the Federal level. Although the "GAO Journal" discontinued its publication in 1993, its rich archive continues to serve as a treasure trove of research on key American public administration themes and issues.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The GAO Review
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The GAO Review', N'the-gao-review', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Quarterly publication by U.S. Government Accountability Office from 1966-2001, covering policy, federal management, and GAO operations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "GAO Review" was an esteemed quarterly publication issued by the United States Government Accountability Office, positioned at the core of the agency''s initiative to foster transparency and accountability in government operations. Commenced in 1966, this magazine served as a critical avenue for disseminating GAO''s comprehensive research, audit findings, and overarching mission to an audience encompassing government officials, researchers, and the public at large.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Distinguished for its credible and impartial content, the "GAO Review" bridged the gap between the intricate world of federal government operations and the public by deconstructing multifaceted concepts into digestible insights. Its content traversed an extensive range of topics in public policy, federal fiscal management, and the intricate operations of different sectors under government purview.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "GAO Review" typically encompassed original research articles, interviews with high-ranking GAO officials, analytical pieces reflecting upon the agency''s inner workings, methodologies, and investigative ventures, among other content. It provided a podium to the federal government and accountability experts to communicate their perspectives, promoting a healthy exchange of ideas and learnings to further the cause of effective governance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Covering areas as diverse as defense spending, environmental regulation, healthcare policy, and education programs, the "GAO Review" served as a repository of cutting-edge knowledge and practical insight, contributing significantly to the discourse around responsible governance and public policy.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "GAO Review" ceased publication in 2001, but its legacy endures through its substantial catalogue of issues that continue to hold value as historical records and foundations for further research in public administration and government accountability.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Gavin Report
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Gavin Report', N'the-gavin-report', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Weekly music industry magazine from 1958-2002, detailing radio charts, music trends and hosting influential industry seminars.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'"The Gavin Report," or the "Gavin," as it was widely known, was an influential weekly music industry trade magazine, published in San Francisco, United States, from 1958 until 2002. Named after its founder, Bill Gavin, a former disc jockey and record promoter, the magazine played a pivotal role in the evolution of the American music industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Bestowed with a palpable authority in the record industry, "The Gavin Report" served myriad roles throughout its publication tenure – a segmenter of radio markets, a predictor of hit records, and a reputable mediator between radio stations and record labels. Its research-intensive content included radio chart information and playlists, in-depth interviews with notable music industry figures, and cogent commentary on industry trends and issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Operating across the landscape of contemporary music, the magazine divided its music chart into distinctive formats, including Top 40, Adult Contemporary, Urban, Country, and more, providing a comprehensive coverage of music trends in the United States. Subsequently, these charts became benchmarks for both music programmers and record companies, chiefly due to the meticulousness of their compilation process.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Among the trailblazing initiatives undertaken by "The Gavin Report" was the "Gavin Seminar," an annual conference inaugurated in 1964 that brought industry professionals into dialogue with artists, music directors, program directors, and other influencers. These annual gatherings were particularly renowned for the "Gavin Awards," which recognized outstanding contributions to the music industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Bill Gavin’s editorial methodology, predicated on a strong belief in the symbiosis between radio and the record industry, established the ethos of "The Gavin Report". This approach garnered the enduring respect of the industry, bolstering the magazine''s reputation as one of the industry’s leading sources for music and radio insights.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The cessation of "The Gavin Report" in February 2002 underscored the end of an era in the American music industry - an industry that had been significantly shaped by Bill Gavin''s insights, initiatives, and indelible influence.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Jarry
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Jarry', N'jarry', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Brooklyn-based publication exploring the intersection of food and queer culture, active from 2015 to 2019.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Jarry* was a Brooklyn-based publication that explored the intersection of food and queer culture. The magazine was named after the slang term "jarry," which its creators defined as "a man who loves men and food." The magazine''s official website is no longer active as of 2023.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jarry Magazine was dedicated to exploring the connection between food and queer culture. It featured a variety of content, including profiles of key personalities in the food industry, personal stories related to food and identity, and explorations of the historical and cultural intersections of food and queer culture. Each issue revolved around a single theme, presenting essays, recipes, photographs, and other creative content to explore food through the queer lens.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jarry Magazine was founded by Lukas Volger and Steve Viksjo in 2015. The idea for the magazine came from Volger, who wanted to create a food magazine from a male gay perspective. The first issue of the magazine was released a year after this initial conversation. The magazine was created with the goal of building a community and filling a gap in the market, as most food magazines at the time were targeted towards women. The magazine was initially launched with the tagline "Men+Food+Men."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine gained recognition when Bay Area food journalist John Birdsall won a James Beard Foundation award for his article “Straight Up Passing: The State of Queer Chefs in America,” featured in the first issue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Between the third and fourth issues, Jarry decided to officially rebrand as a "queer food journal," expanding its scope to include the broader LGBTQ food world. The final issue, issue no. 6, was published on February 9, 2019.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jarry Magazine aimed to highlight and explore the contributions of queer individuals to modern food culture. The magazine featured articles on key figures in the food industry who were queer, such as James Beard, Richard Olney, and Craig Claiborne. The magazine also explored various ways in which queer and food culture intersected, from community and entertainment to personal stories of bonding and identity through cooking.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the most important aspects of Jarry was its ability to highlight the voices of up-and-coming queer creators. The magazine provided a platform for young artists and writers all over the world, giving them the opportunity to imprint themselves into the crowded world of media in a way that celebrated their identity and respected their experiences.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Visual Style' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jarry Magazine was known for its playful visual language, including its use of illustration. The logo and the soft touch coating on the cover were designed to reflect the approachability of the magazine. The typeface of the logo was envisioned to resemble the kind of handwriting people use when writing down notes for a recipe.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Additional Information' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to his work on Jarry, Lukas Volger is also known for his work as a cookbook author and food entrepreneur. He authored a cookbook titled “Bowl: Vegetarian Recipes for Ramen, Pho, Bibimbap, Dumplings, and Other One-Dish Meals,” and distributed “Made by Lukas” veggie burgers served at some New York restaurants and carried by various Whole Foods.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The word Jarry comes from Polari, British slang once used by performers and gay men, and means a man who loves men and food. The magazine was printed in Vancouver on high-quality matte paper with as many photos of men as of food.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Gay Chicago
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Gay Chicago', N'gay-chicago', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A premier LGBT-focused publication, covering news, events, profiles, and the evolving culture within the community.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Gay Chicago Magazine' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Gay Chicago Magazine was a staple publication in Chicago''s LGBT community, delivering news, events, and personal profiles that catered to the interests and needs of LGBT individuals in the region. This magazine was an invaluable tool that brought the community together, playing a significant role in shaping, informing, and enriching the city''s LGBT culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Origin' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was initially launched as ''Gay Life'' by Ralph and Craig Gernhardt in 1975, who saw the need for an information platform for the LGBT community in Chicago. This duo understood the importance of media representation in the fight for LGBT rights and the magazine quickly became a popular and trusted source of news and events within the community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Progression and Growth' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Gay Chicago Magazine rose in prominence throughout the 1980s and 1990s collaborating with various other Chicago LGBT organizations and service providers to provide a comprehensive overview of events, businesses, and news relevant to the LGBT community. It provided readers with everything from personal anecdotes and interviews to health-related pieces and special features. In 1984, the publication was officially renamed "Gay Chicago Magazine".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Management and Distribution' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Management of Gay Chicago Magazine was taken over by Tracy Baim in 2009, who was the co-founder of another LGBT newspaper, Windy City Times. The magazine continued its intrinsic role in the Chicago''s LGBT scene, adapting to digitalization before finally ceasing its print edition and shifting completely to the online platform in 2011.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With nearly four decades of experience, Gay Chicago Magazine remains a significant voice within the LGBT community in Chicago. It has played a critical role in the community’s history, covering a range of topics including the rise of HIV/AIDS, equal rights movements, and the evolution of the LGBT scene in Chicago. Despite its transition to complete digitalization in 2011, Gay Chicago Magazine continues its legacy of bringing forth important and relevant content for the LGBT+ community.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Gear Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Gear Magazine', N'gear-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Ground-breaking men''s lifestyle publication renowned for bold aesthetics and thought-provoking content (1998-2003).}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Gear Magazine' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Gear Magazine was a men''s lifestyle publication that gained brief but impactful significance in the late 1990s and early 2000s. It was well-regarded for its coverage of contemporary and thought-provoking topics, combined with a cutting-edge artistic aesthetic.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Establishment and Early Years' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established in 1998 by Bob Guccione Jr., son of Penthouse founder Bob Guccione Sr., Gear aimed to cater to an audience interested in a wide array of modern lifestyle topics. These topics ranged from current trends in fashion and music to in-depth features on technology and contemporary issues. The U.S.-based magazine quickly gained a reputation for its daring style and brash tone, positioning itself as a distinctive voice in the male-oriented magazine market.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Style' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Gear Magazine was renowned for its thought-provoking features and exclusive interviews, often featuring prominent figures in pop culture, sports, and entertainment industry. These profiles marked a significant attraction for the magazine’s readership and helped in shaping its public image. The magazine also notably tapped into the emerging world of digital and information technology, providing readers with up-to-date overviews and analyses.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, Gear presented a bold and assertive aesthetic, characterized by its provocative cover designs and exceptional photography. The magazine, however, was sometimes criticized for the objectification of women in its photo spreads, stirring controversy and debates on several occasions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Closure and Legacy ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication came to an end in 2003, due to declining sales and mounting criticism over its content. However, during its five-year lifespan, Gear offered a unique blend of lifestyle and cultural content, establishing a distinctive identity among male-oriented magazines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While Gear Magazine''s operation was short-lived, its influence continues to live on as a marker of late 20th-century male-targeted publications, which encapsulated an era of rapidly evolving societal standards and cultural norms. Its provocative approach to editorial and visual content serves as a reflection of both the times it operated in and the transitional state of media during this period.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Geek Monthly
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Geek Monthly', N'geek-monthly', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American print magazine (2006-2010) dedicated to geek culture, including tech, video games, comic books, and popular science.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Geek Monthly' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Geek Monthly was a popular American print magazine dedicated to geek culture, published from 2006 to 2010. It provided an exciting mix of content on diverse topics such as video games, comic books, technology, and popular science. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Fueled by the rising interest in geek culture in the 21st century, the publication was launched in 2006 by CFQ Media, an entity known earlier for the science fiction and horror film magazine, Cinefantastique. Geek Monthly gained traction among enthusiasts for its accurate, in-depth, and user-friendly presentation of geek-related content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Geek Monthly offered a compelling mix of content across various facets of geek culture. It provided reviews of emerging tech gadgets, previews and reviews of video games, updates on comic book releases, and coverage of the science fiction genre across various media. Apart from these, Geek Monthly also spotlighted the more serious side of geek culture, incorporating discussions about science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Geek Monthly''s coverage of entertainment included insightful interviews with celebrities relevant to the geek culture, including writers, movie creators, and television stars. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Transition to Digital' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2010, Geek Monthly ceased its print operations, transitioning to a digital-only format under the website name GeekExchange.com. The switch reflected the increasing digital consumption of media content, especially within the demographic niche Geek Monthly catered to. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the print version of Geek Monthly no longer exists, its digital avatar continues to entertain and inform a dedicated audience, serving as a testament to the evolution of media consumption and the enduring appeal of geek culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

